1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. d4
{ White immediately strikes in the middle of the board. After our natural reply  2...exd4  , we'll see what White is up to. }
2... exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out, Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some, we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Bc4
{ Playing in gambit style. White does not try to regain the pawn immediately. Another gambit approach is  3.c3  , when  3...Qe7!  is an ambitious reply. White has nothing better than  4.cxd4  Qxe4+  , giving Black the better chances. }
3... Nf6
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ Not the only move, but it makes sense to play it as this position needs to be part of our repertoire anyway. Why? Because after  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  @@StartBracket@@the only move consistent with a Petroff@@EndBracket@@  3.d4  ,  we need to take on d4, which transposes to the position at hand. 3... Nf6 is also the best move, so 'merging' those two lines is logical. }
4. Nf3
{ Going for rapid development. Plus, it's the only consistent move. After  4.e5  Black has  4...d5! }
4... Nxe4
{ Whenever you can grab e4 without being immediately punished... take it! Well, I am fond of this general principle, but you need to consider carefully when it loses time in the opening. This pawn grab gives White excellent development, but I believe it is not more than enough compensation. I have checked some other lines as well.  4...Nc6  transposes to a different opening after 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4. Black is fine here, but all of this is quite a sizeable amount of lines to learn for something you will rarely face.   4...Bb4+  is a good alternative, though... at the end, I decided on the pawn grab because it is the most principled move. }
5. Qxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bg5 Nc6 8. Qh4 d6 9. O-O-O Be6
{ This is the key idea to remember. We need to trade this dangerous bishop or gain a bit of time if White avoids the trade. Note that Black has not castled and needs to keep all options open and decide according to White's next moves. }
10. Bd3
{ Avoiding the trade, but losing some time. I believe Black is better now with precise play as indicated by the engine. White should probably play  10.Rhe1  , when  10...Bxc4  11.Qxc4  O-O  is fine for Black. White has some, but enough compensation. }
10... h6
{ This move 'threatens to threaten' the bishop on g5. If this bishop retreats, Black has got a nice discovered attack on the queen with Nd5 or Ng4. }
11. Rhe1 a6
{ This is a powerful move that has multiple ideas behind it. The most obvious is that Bb5 is not possible anymore - a move that would be annoying after ...Qd7. The main point, however, is that Black now has a stunning idea that is tough to prevent. }
12. Kb1
{ I don't see anything better - neither does the engine. Now Black's great idea comes into play. }
12... Kd7 { This is a cool idea! Now the bishop on g5 is attacked for real! }
13. Bc1
{ White has to avoid  13.Bd2?  when  13...g5  14.Qa4  b5  15.Bxb5  axb5  16.Qxb5  Ra5  wins for Black. }
13... Nd5
{ It is crucial to see here that  13...g5  14.Qa4  b5  is no good due to  15.Bxb5  axb5  16.Qxb5  .  The threat of Ne5+ is extremely awkward! The knight move to d5; however, it is very nice for us, destroying White's pawn structure. }
14. Qg3 Nxc3+ 15. bxc3 Bf6
{ With a clear advantage for Black. The King will have a safe place on b8, and a plan with ...g5 will provide good play against the misplaced queen - not to mention Black is a pawn up! }
