2. d4
{ White immediately strikes in the middle of the board. After our natural reply  2...exd4  , we'll see what White is up to. }
2... exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out, Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some, we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Nf3
{ White is aiming for a Scotch after  3...Nc6  , but we won't allow that to happen as we have better options. }
3... Bc5
{ I also checked  3...Bb4+  , concluding that it is a viable alternative. However, I liked  3...Bc5  even more, so this is the move I suggest playing. The key point is that the simple capture on d4 is now not in any way a Scotch Game transposition, but quite comfortable for Black. }
4. Bc4
{ White plays in gambit style. After  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  O-O  ,  followed by ...Re8, Black gets a good game with simple means. }
4... d6
{ I like this best. After  4...Nc6  , we will without justification transpose into dense theory, while  4...Nf6  5.e5  is murky and not advantageous. }
5. c3
{ Again,  5.Nxd4  Nf6  6.Nc3  O-O  is simple to play and fine for Black. } 5...
dxc3 6. Nxc3 Nf6
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ And we have transposed into a line that may also start with  1.e4  e5  2.d4  exd4  3.Nf3  Bc5  4.c3  dxc3  5.Nxc3  d6  6.Bc4  Nf6  .  Black is a pawn up, and White's compensation is questionable. The key point is that Black has not played ...Nc6, which often allows ...c6 and ...Nbd7 as an antidote to Bg5/Nd5 ideas. }
