1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. f4
{ The King's Gambit! Time to celebrate, and already on move two. Our opponent is giving us a pawn, and we will be better instantly. Wait, is it all that easy?! In fact, it is not, but it's no joke that we should strive for more than equality against this opening. Before going into move-by-move analysis, we should talk a bit about the history and nature of this opening. It is amongst the oldest openings; the earliest analysis is from the 15th century. The very first chess book by Lucena - yes, the guy of 'Lucena position' fame - has some information on the King's Gambit.   The idea of White's play is quite logical. Ideally, he would like to develop with Bc4, Nf3, and a later O-O. But wouldn't it be better if the f-file is open instead of being blocked by a pawn on f2? If you open the f-file, all is set to attack f7, the weakest spot in Black's camp. As you might have gathered, White is out for Black's King from move two. This sounds appealing, so why isn't the King's Gambit regarded as a good opening nowadays? Well, Vladimir Kramnik famously said: 'It loses a pawn and weakens White's king'. Not the most 'romantic' statement about the most romantic chess opening around.   The 21st-century problem for gambits is the enormous progress that has been achieved in defense. The Silicon chess player is not afraid to take pawns and defend if it works out, based on cold-blooded calculation. Alright, what does all that mean for us? Nowadays, there are many good defenses available against the King's Gambit. The main decision to make is how hard you want to try to punish White and how much time you need to learn these lines. You need to take into account that you won't get this opening frequently. If you get in on the board, it will be a prepared surprise, or you might be up against a specialist, who has it on the board much more often than you do. Therefore learning extremely complicated lines feels a bit uneconomical. On the other hand, you don't want to allow White to 'get away' with his bold opening choice too easily by playing something too 'soft'.   Alright, we should look at some moves now. Just one thing: If your opponent plays the King's Gambit, you instantly know he means business. He's ready to hit hard, so we need to be ready to hit back harder. This means your opponent will very likely get the type of game he wanted, but at the same time, he will often be just worse! Be mentally ready for this type of game - there won't be any subtle maneuvering in this game! }
2... exf4
{ As Kramnik said: 'It loses a pawn'! Jokes aside, Black has two main defenses against the gambit. Taking the pawn, as I suggest, and  2...d5  3.exd5  exf4  .  This second line is fine for Black, but I felt it was not as challenging as taking on f4. Of course, I need to mention this repertoire is modeled after Fabiano Caruana's games - so what does Fabiano play? Well, we don't know! He has not yet played against the King's Gambit in any of his games in the databases, which is somewhat surprising. Nowadays, because so many rapid and blitz games are in the public databases, you would expect at least the odd game, but there is just nothing. Alright, you need to trust my choices then ;-@@EndBracket@@ }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ This is the Schallopp Defence, named after a German master player of the 19th century. It always enjoyed a good reputation but never got to mainline status. However, this line has been covered in at least two books that I know of in recent years. The Schallopp was chosen by Nikolaos Ntirlis and Martin Lokander in their repertoire books for Black, indicating that it offers an excellent balance of easy to learn yet still ambitious enough to 'punish' White for going wild with the f-pawn on move two. When I looked at their analysis, it was very tough for me not to suggest  3...Nf6  as well.   My usual aim is to present lines that have not been covered too much before. At this particular point, however, I felt that 3... Nf6 is an almost ideal solution, in particular in the context of a Petroff-based repertoire. It is solid and classical but still challenging for White to play against. OK, with this intro out of the way... let's examine the move! Well, it attacks e4 right away, so White's choices are limited. Critical must be  4.e5  ,  after which we happily jump to h5! The knight is covering the booty on f4, but also may return later via g7. It is essential to see that 4. e5, advancing the pawn, presents a target to our pieces and the d-pawn. We will often go ...d6 to attack it quickly. }
4. e5
{ The most aggressive move and the one we are looking at in the Quickstarter. After  4.Nc3  d5  , Black has a good game, too. We examine this in detail inthe full chapter. }
4... Nh5
{ Now White's main tries are  5.Be2  and  5.d4  . We also check some rare alternatives inthe full chapter. }
5. d4 d6
{ Black attacks the pawn center immediately. I also checked  5...d5  @@StartBracket@@it is fine as well@@EndBracket@@, but it makes a lot of sense to try to get rid of the e5-pawn. }
6. Qe2
{ An odd-looking move, but it contains a trap that you may easily stumble into. }
6... d5
{ This is a strong move, but it is most important to avoid  6...Be7?  7.exd6  Qxd6  8.Qb5+!  and the h5-knight is lost! Now the queen looks misplaced on e2. }
7. c4 dxc4 8. Qxc4 c6
{ At this point, we can stop. Black is a pawn up and has excellent play, using e6 and d5 for his pieces. Besides the obvious ...Be6 there are ideas with ...Na6-b4/ c7-d5 as well. }
