1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. Bc4
{ This isthe Bishop's Opening. White starts with this natural bishop development before committing to play the knight to f3, keeping options open. Nowadays, this opening line is viewed as the only serious option for White if he wants to avoid the Petroff completely, and it is easy to understand why. After 1. e4 e5, there is just nothing else that at least poses some challenges. The gambits are all defanged, so what else is there besides 2. Bc4? In any case, our reply is quite obvious. }
2... Nf6
{ A natural reply, attacking e4. We will now examine  3.d3  , which is White's most promising try. Other moves are harmless or transpose, for example,  3.d4  exd4  we examined via 2. d4 exd4 3. Bc4   or  3.Nc3  Nxe4  is analyzed via 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4. }
3. d3
{ This is the most solid and best move. Now Black has an important choice to make. With moves like  3...Bc5  , or  3...Nc6  , usually followed by  4.Nf3  Bc5  , you may transpose to an Italian game/Giuoco Piano   or avoid this altogether and go  3...c6  .  I recommend playing 3... c6, which is also Caruana's usual choice. I also need to mention that the Italian game has seen a revival in recent years, and it is quite an effort for Black to learn to play against it. Our choice is much simpler to master. }
3... c6
{ Black prepares ...d5, gaining a tempo on the bishop. I need to mention an important idea that we will frequently see in this line. Black commonly checks with Bb4+, provoking c3, or initiates trades if White replies with Bd2. It is important to understand that c3 is a useful post for White's knight to increase pressure on d5, so a pawn on c3 is more of a handicap, for White, than an asset. }
4. Nf3 d5
{ If you like a low maintenance alternative, I suggest  4...Be7  ,  setting up with ...d6 later. This is very similar to a Closed Philidor formation where White has played rather timidly with an early d3. This line is better suited to keep it complicated and avoid trades. }
5. Bb3
{ This is by far the most popular move, keeping the tension in the center. White may also play  5.exd5  cxd5  6.Bb3  , when  6...Bb4+  7.c3  Bd6  is fine for Black. This concept is rather similar to the mainline. }
5... Bb4+
{ I mentioned this standard procedure before. Black argues that c3 is not useful and Bd2 or Nbd2 are too meek to pose any problems. }
6. Bd2
{ This has become the most popular move in recent times. Instead,  6.c3  is rather harmless. After  6...Bd6  7.Bg5  dxe4  8.dxe4  h6  9.Bh4  Qe7  10.Nbd2  Nbd7  Black has an easy game in a symmetrical pawn formation. We followed M.Carlsen-F.Caruana, Saint Louis 2014. The World Champion later sacrificed a piece for insufficient compensation and lost. }
6... Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2
{ This is not very popular, but it is an interesting move. White operates with the idea of playing Qg5, attacking both e5 and g7. }
7... O-O { An interesting concept, sacrificing the e5-pawn. } 8. Nxe5
{ White can also grab a pawn with  8.exd5  cxd5  9.Nxe5  , but  9...a5  10.a4  Nc6  gives Black excellent compensation. }
8... Qe7 9. f4 dxe4 10. d4 Be6
{ And Black had equalized in M.Ragger-L.Nisipeanu, Graz 2018. } *

