{ This has become the most popular move in recent times. Instead,  6.c3  is rather harmless. After  6...Bd6  7.Bg5  dxe4  8.dxe4  h6  9.Bh4  Qe7  10.Nbd2  Nbd7  Black has an easy game in a symmetrical pawn formation. We followed M.Carlsen-F.Caruana, Saint Louis 2014. The World Champion later sacrificed a piece for insufficient compensation and lost. }
6... Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2
{ This looks natural, but is not very challenging if Black plays precisely. }
7... a5 8. c3 Nbd7 9. exd5 cxd5 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Qc7
{ In M.Carlsen-F.Caruana, Stavanger 2018, Black went for 11... Re8. Caruana's position was OK in this game, but Carlsen played very well and set problems. The World Champion went on to win a nice game. I'd like to show one exciting idea that occurred some moves later. It continued  11...Re8  12.Nf1  b5  13.a4  b4  14.cxb4  axb4  15.Ne3  Bb7  16.d4!?  Carlsen sacs a pawn  16...e4  17.Ne5  Nxe5  18.dxe5  Rxe5  19.Qd4  and White had good play for the material investment.   I don't think  11...Re8  was a mistake, but I still like to suggest  11...Qc7  as an idea. This move was played between two of the strongest players in correspondence chess and therefore thoroughly checked. One difference to covering e5 with the rook is that the same pawn sac idea from the Carlsen game would not work as well, as, in the end, the queen can capture on e5. An additional point will be revealed in the coming lines. }
12. c4
{ An entirely different idea compared to Carlsen's approach. White may also play a la Carlsen with  12.Nf1  , but  12...b5  13.a4  bxa4  14.Bxa4  e4  15.dxe4  dxe4  16.Nd4  Nc5  leads to fine play for Black. }
12... d4 13. Ba4 b6 14. Qe2 Re8 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Bb7 17. Qf5 Bc8 18. Qe4
Bb7
{ And the game M.Kribben-A.Dronov, ICCF email 2016 ended in a draw by repetition. }
