1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is, of course, perfectly playable, but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them, you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6
{ The most natural move. Now White has a pretty broad set of choices. The most solid move is  3.Nf3  , when  3...Nc6  transposes to the Four Knights. }
3. Bc4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ White goes for a hybrid between the Vienna and the Bishop's Opening. Of course, this position also could have developed from  1.e4  e5  2.Bc4  Nf6  3.Nc3  .  Usually, White intends to build up a setup with d3 and f4, similar to a declined King's Gambit. This scenario could happen after, for example,  3...Nc6  4.d3  Bc5  5.f4  d6  6.Nf3  ,  which is a direct transposition to the 2... Bc5 reply to the King's Gambit. This is not part of our repertoire and, frankly speaking, 2...Bc5 is just a worse move than taking. Well, back to the Vienna now. There are some options for Black to avoid the mentioned transposition.   A popular and often recommended line is  3...Nc6  4.d3  Na5  ,  but my personal experience with this line is not very positive. Yes, you get the bishop pair, but White has straightforward play. I tried this ...Na5 line multiple times against a teammate in blitz and had huge problems. Maybe it is just my inability to play the position, but I like to avoid it. Black has a relatively easy recipe to equalize completely, and it nicely complies with the general rule that you should take the e4-pawn if possible. }
3... Nxe4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ We also use this motif in the line  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.Bc4  Nxe4  . Here things are a bit different because White has the queen sortie to  h5  , which is the only interesting try. }
4. Qh5
{ The only interesting try for White. After  4.Nxe4  d5  , we regain the piece with excellent play.   White can play  4.Bxf7+  , but  4...Kxf7  5.Nxe4  d5  gives Black the bishop pair and the center.  6.Qf3+  Kg8  7.Ng5!?  is trappy, but  7...Qd7!  is great for Black. }
4... Nd6
{ Only move. Now White has a choice between retreating the bishop to b3, or the more obvious capture on e5. }
5. Bb3
{ Instead  5.Qxe5+  Qe7  6.Qxe7+  Bxe7  7.Bb3  Nf5  is rather harmless for Black. White agrees to enter a queenless middlegame that poses no problems for Black. The resulting positions are symmetrical, but there are some imbalances due to the very different piece placements. If you would like to study a model game for this line: check the game A.Rosselli-Rubinstein, Baden-Baden 1925. I knew the middle-/endgame of that game for a long time @@StartBracket@@it is featured in several books@@EndBracket@@ and never knew it arose from this opening line. Looking at the position around move 20, I always assumed it started as a French Exchange, but now I know better. }
5... Be7
{ It is absolutely essential to play this move and to avoid  5...Nc6  , unless you know exactly what you are doing after  6.Nb5  . This is the utterly crazy 'Frankenstein-Dracula'-variation... which is probably not that great in the first place for Black anyway.   Just go  5...Be7  and be fine, instead! }
6. Qxe5 O-O 7. d4 Nc6 8. Qf4 Na5 9. Bd5
{ This position was on the board in the game F.Caruana@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@-A.Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2014. It seems that Caruana wanted to surprise Giri with this anti-Petroff line. }
9... c6 { This is more active than Giri's  9...Ne8  . } 10. Bf3 b5
{ With interesting play. Black intends to play ...b4 and ...Nb5 to free up the d-pawn. }
