1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is, of course, perfectly playable, but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them, you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6
{ The most natural move. Now White has a pretty broad set of choices. The most solid move is  3.Nf3  , when  3...Nc6  transposes to the Four Knights. }
3. g3
{ An old favorite of Boris Spassky's. As usual, I recommend playing ...d5, if allowed. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ White now needs to decide where to place the knight on g1. The most challenging option is to place it on f3, putting more pressure on Black's center. Note that these positions often arise from a different and more common move order. There is the so-called 'Glek System' in the Four Knights after  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.g3  , which we answer with  4...d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  .   If White plays  7.Nf3  now, we will get exactly this position. }
7. Nf3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This position is most frequently seen from the move order  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.g3  d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  , the 'Glek System. }
7... Bc5
{ I have to admit that I never studied this system for Black and always played  7...Bd6  ,  in this position. Protecting the pawn on e5 somehow felt right, but this is quite passive compared to the development to c5. The Bc5 setup has been recommended in recent books by Ntirlis and Lokander and their argument in favor of Bc5 looks convincing to me. }
8. O-O O-O
{ Starting from here, White has some moves that all fit into the scheme of development but may be played in various move orders. Most of the time, White will play d3, Re1, or Qe2 to attack e5. There are also ideas with an early Rb1 to utilize the half-open b-file. You need to know some rules of thumb for Black: we will cover e5 with Qf6 if White attacks it with Re1, thus making Nd2 impossible due to the pressure on f2. If White attacks e5 with Qe2, Re8 is the better reply. If White plays a slow move, we will go ...Bb6 as a good waiting move. It makes any Rb1 less effective, and the bishop is stable on b6.   Once the bishop is on b6, White sometimes tries the move a4, intending to play a5 to distract a defender from the e5-pawn. This is an important motif worth noting - a4 usually means we need to lend extra protection to e5. We often delay the development of the c8-bishop for a moment to be flexible with this piece. Move orders might seem confusing here, but don't worry too much. If you get it slightly wrong, you won't be in severe trouble. Black's position is fundamentally sound, and sensible moves should give you a good position, even if you don't remember or find all of the optimal moves. }
9. Re1 Qf6
{ This is almost forced but also an integral part of our setup. Note that  9...Re8  runs into  10.d4!  , which gives White a small advantage. }
10. d3 Bb6
{ If nothing is pressing to do, like defending e5, we will play this good waiting move. }
11. Be3
{ Our bishop is strong on b6, so trading it makes some sense. In this way, White also prepares finally to move the f3-knight to play it to e4 or c4. }
11... Bg4 { 'No knight move for you!' } 12. h3 Bh5 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nd2
{ White finally managed to move the knight, trying to improve it to e4 or c4. There is a drawback, though. }
14... Qh4
{ Shakh Mamedyarov reached this position twice, against Daniel Fridman and Dimitry Jakovenko. In both games Black held his own nicely with a quick ...f5 push to get active play on the kingside. }
*

