ar.   In the Quickstarter, we will look at  4.a3  d5  , which is the trickiest version of the 'small waiting moves'.   We will also check  4.Nxe5  , the crazy Halloween Gambit, and  4.Bc4  , which gives us good play after  4...Nxe4  .   A good line for White is  4.g3  , but after  4...d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  Bc5  we transpose to lines that we examine via 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5. }
4. Bc4
{ The Italian Four Knights. Quite surprisingly, this very natural move can be answered very effectively by Black, equalizing immediately. }
4... Nxe4
{ A common theme in the open games. Black temporarily sacs the knight, getting it back with a ...d5 fork. I need to emphasize that Black does not get an advantage, as many older books tried to prove. However, it is somewhat likely that a player on the white side who plays into this line, not knowing that  4...Nxe4  is strong, will make mistakes later as well. This is also why White scores so badly after 4...Nxe4. Any other mistake will be costly. }
5. Nxe4
{ Even worse is  5.Bxf7+  Kxf7  6.Nxe4  d5  ,  when Black has the bishop pair and the center. The key point is that we often manage to castle by hand, with a later ...Rf8 and ...Kg8. }
5... d5 6. Bd3
{ The only move to keep the balance for White. After  6.Bb5  dxe4  7.Nxe5  Qg5  8.Nxc6  Qg5  Black is much better. }
6... dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6
{ Black has equalized easily here. You could stop at this point, but there is one line I'd like to show. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ White intends to take on c6 and win the e5 pawn next. This line looks very natural and might be seen frequently if White avoids the earlier pitfalls. }
9... Nb4
{ I like this idea, threatening ...f5! It is still equal, but there are some interesting complications. You could analyze this position in a lot more depth, but this is not very economical for such a rare line, so I'll just give some sample lines. }
10. c3 { Against  10.d4  we have  10...f5  , with good play. } 10... f5 11. Bb1
e4 12. cxb4 exf3 13. Qxf3 Bd7
{ Black has a nice compensation for the pawn here. } *

