{ This is White's best option if he does not want to enter a line exclusive to the Petroff. The main tries are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  , but you should be aware that  3.Nc3  will be played a lot against you, particularly at the amateur/club level. It is vital to have good answers prepared because you'll face them frequently. But there is an additional incentive to be well prepared.   White players MIGHT know the Four Knights Game well, but this does not need to be the case! Often they will play 3. Nc3 just because they have nothing prepared against the Petroff, and they have 3. Nc3 only as an 'escape hatch' line, just against this Petroff move order. Against 2... Nc6, they'd play the Ruy Lopez or Italian, but only against the Petroff, they'd enter the Four Knights without any deep knowledge. As mentioned, that does not need to be the case, but you might meet people over the board that have no detailed knowledge - so we should be well prepared, trying to exploit this. }
3... Nc6
{ We transpose tothe Four Knights game with this move. Objectively speaking, this is the best move, and it should be played. Fabiano Caruana has never faced 3. Nc3, so we don't exactly know for sure what he would play, but I'd be amazed about a different move. It involves a bit of theory, but the alternatives are not convincing or somewhat against the spirit of the Petroff.  3...Bb4  is a way to save theoretical workload, but I think White is slightly better after  4.Nxe5  ,  as I have analyzed in my Keep it Simple 1. e4 repertoire.   A choice worth considering is  3...d6  , angling to transpose into a Philidor after  4.d4  exd4  or  4...Nbd7  . Caruana has played the Philidor occasionally in Blitz/Rapid, with decent results. So this is worth looking at if you want to explore an additional option.   It would be weird to include some Philidor lines in this repertoire, so I decided to go for the mainline with  3...Nc6  .  This is also a versatile choice: if you also play 2... Nc6 or intend to include this later, it is necessary to have something prepared against the Four Knights anyway. The theoretically most explored lines areScotch Four Knights with  4.d4  , orthe Spanish Four Knights starting with  4.Bb5  .  These main lines are examined in the following chapter.   We also need to check some sidelines that White has tried. Against almost all slow moves, I recommend playing 4... d5. It is not a coincidence that 4. Bb5 and 4. d4 are the main lines... they stop ...d5! In some cases, 4... d5 will lead to lines where we are playing the Scotch Four Knights with colors reversed, and White has made an extra move. This extra move helps White, but not to the extent that it changes the position much. This applies to 4. a3 d5, 4. h3 d5 and 5. Be2 d5. By the way: it is not necessary to know the Scotch Four Knights inside and out, from White's point of view, to play in this fashion with Black. Note that we have to play the Black side after 4. d4, so the position types are familiar.   In the Quickstarter, we will look at  4.a3  d5  , which is the trickiest version of the 'small waiting moves'.   We will also check  4.Nxe5  , the crazy Halloween Gambit, and  4.Bc4  , which gives us good play after  4...Nxe4  .   A good line for White is  4.g3  , but after  4...d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  Bc5  we transpose to lines that we examine via 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5. }
4. d4
{ I have recommended 4. d4 in my Keep it Simple 1. e4 Repertoire for White, so it's my job now to play against my recommendation. This is not such a big deal as this line does not give White an advantage anyway. Against a mainline defense like 1... e5, White does not get an edge, but a line like the Scotch Four Knights is a good choice for White. It is easy to play, and Black has many ways to go wrong. White is also very solid, with a sound development and no weaknesses. Sounds like a good advertisement for White? Well, if you look closely at Black's position, you will conclude that those virtues apply equally for Black, as well. From a pawn structure point of view, Black will be slightly worse on the queenside, but this is a minor concern. }
4... exd4
{ The only other active move,  4...Bb4  is unsound. We have checked the lines starting with, for example, 4. a3 d5 5. Bb5, concluding that White is playing with fire. We should avoid this and play the mainline. }
5. Nxd4
{ Here White has the funky knight jump  5.Nd5  , the Belgrade Gambit. Black's best bet against it is  5...Nb4!  ,  which we analyze a bit more inthe full chapter. Black's key idea is to trade the d5-knight quickly, for example, in the line 6. Bc4 Nbxd5 7. exd5 Bb4+, when White is struggling to prove compensation for the pawn. }
5... Bb4
{ This move enjoys the best reputation. Black develops quickly, and pinning the knight puts some pressure on the e4-pawn. Note that Black is already set to castle on the next move, and he currently has three pieces in play instead of White's two. This is not that relevant if White plays the well-established mainline that I recommend in my 'Keep it Simple 1. e4'-Repertoire, but any deviation that delays development or weakens the structure will prove costly. Usually, White knows what he is doing, and you will reach the position on move eight quickly, but at lower levels, you might face one of the bad alternatives that give Black excellent chances. }
6. Nxc6
{ White needs to develop and cover e4. To play Bd3, you need to take on c6 first. Very logical, but White has tried some worse alternatives that we check in the full chapter. }
6... bxc6 7. Bd3
{ By far the most sensible move. Again alternatives are downright bad or at least questionable. }
7... O-O 8. O-O d5
{ In this position, Black has a choice between three lines. Caruana has only faced this opening once, in an online rapid game, and he played  8...d6  .  This was certainly played with a fight in mind. However, I am not a huge fan of playing 8... d6 in this particular situation due to the annoying pin,  9.Bg5  . It is not terrible for Black, but I would rather avoid it.   The second option is to play  8...Re8  , keeping options open. This is the move I would play if I needed to win the game at all costs. However, the verdict is still open if Black can equalize with this move, as about all main moves against it @@StartBracket@@  9.Qf3  ,  9.Bg5  ,  9.Re1  @@EndBracket@@ pose problems that are not easily met.   The traditional mainline is simply to play  8...d5  ,  opening the position immediately. White will capture after which  9.--  Bg4!?  is our choice. This move was unknown until 2018, when it was played in several master-level games. This line is perfectly sound but also may lead to positions that make it very difficult for Black to play for a win with Black. Admittedly, if you have the Petroff in your repertoire you should not mind a draw too much, because there are some forced drawing lines that you can hardly avoid. }
9. exd5
{ White sometimes tries  9.e5  , but  9...Ng4  10.Bf4  f6  is nice for Black. }
9... Bg4
{ This move is one of the most remarkable novelties introduced in recent years. It was first played at a higher level in 2018 - maybe someone played it before, outside of mainstream databases. It is amazing that after the traditional  9...cxd5  , the position has been played more than 8000 times in Mega 2018, while no one ever played  9...Bg4  - for more than a century.   When I was writing my 'Keep it Simple 1. e4' repertoire I was not aware of the move, either, as it first saw the light of day when my Chessable release went live. Some months later, we have more games and analyses, and now we know that 9... Bg4 is perfectly playable for Black. White has tried some lines to refute it directly, but these fail and end in very drawish positions. White can, however, keep the game going with modest moves, which is my recommendation for White. These lines are about equal but not an immediate draw.   I recommend the whole 9... Bg4 line for Black because you still have surprise value, and objectively it seems to be perfectly fine. I need to mention that 9... cxd5 is, of course, playable as well - I think that White has the more straightforward game there, but Black is close to equal. It involves much more theory, though, than 9... Bg4, which presents another argument in favor of the bishop move. }
10. f3
{ The most principled move for sure. I checked it for White, of course, and did not find anything convincing. The move  10.Ne2  was my recommendation for White, when after  10...cxd5  11.h3  Bh5  12.c4  White argues that Black's pawn structure is slightly worse. True, but Black's pieces are active, and any possible advantage for White must be insignificant. }
10... Bh5 11. Bg5
{ This is the most exciting move, avoiding the lengthy and forcing lines that emerge after taking on c6. After  11.dxc6  Qd4+  12.Kh1  Bxc3  13.bxc3  Qxc3  Black equalizes easily. }
11... Qd6
{ It looks computerish, and it is, of course, a Stockfish suggestion. Well, if it works, I don't mind that much how it looks! First of all, White can't take on c6 now due to Qc5+, so we are not giving up material this way. So what is White supposed to play? The critical move seems to be  12.Bxf6  , but this seems satisfactory to me. What else is there on move  12. We need to check some alternatives, which we do inthe full chapter. }
12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Ne4 Qxb2
{ This is better than regaining the pawn with  13...Qd4+  . } 14. dxc6 Qd4+ 15.
Kh1 Bg6
{ Black is a pawn down now, but it is a doubled pawn for White. I don't see any particular danger here. If everything else fails, you often have the emergency exit, namely to go for an opposite-colored bishop endgame later in the game. }
