{ The starting position of the Petroff. Now White's main moves are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  .   There are alternatives, but the only challenging one is  3.Nc3  , after which I recommend playing  3...Nc6  , transposing into aFour Knights game. This is Fabiano Caruana's choice, too.   In the Quickstarter, I'll also have a quick look at the dubious gambit  3.Bc4  . }
3. Nc3
{ This is White's best option if he does not want to enter a line exclusive to the Petroff. The main tries are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  , but you should be aware that  3.Nc3  will be played a lot against you, particularly at the amateur/club level. It is vital to have good answers prepared because you'll face them frequently. But there is an additional incentive to be well prepared.   White players MIGHT know the Four Knights Game well, but this does not need to be the case! Often they will play 3. Nc3 just because they have nothing prepared against the Petroff, and they have 3. Nc3 only as an 'escape hatch' line, just against this Petroff move order. Against 2... Nc6, they'd play the Ruy Lopez or Italian, but only against the Petroff, they'd enter the Four Knights without any deep knowledge. As mentioned, that does not need to be the case, but you might meet people over the board that have no detailed knowledge - so we should be well prepared, trying to exploit this. }
3... Nc6
{ We transpose tothe Four Knights game with this move. Objectively speaking, this is the best move, and it should be played. Fabiano Caruana has never faced 3. Nc3, so we don't exactly know for sure what he would play, but I'd be amazed about a different move. It involves a bit of theory, but the alternatives are not convincing or somewhat against the spirit of the Petroff.  3...Bb4  is a way to save theoretical workload, but I think White is slightly better after  4.Nxe5  ,  as I have analyzed in my Keep it Simple 1. e4 repertoire.   A choice worth considering is  3...d6  , angling to transpose into a Philidor after  4.d4  exd4  or  4...Nbd7  . Caruana has played the Philidor occasionally in Blitz/Rapid, with decent results. So this is worth looking at if you want to explore an additional option.   It would be weird to include some Philidor lines in this repertoire, so I decided to go for the mainline with  3...Nc6  .  This is also a versatile choice: if you also play 2... Nc6 or intend to include this later, it is necessary to have something prepared against the Four Knights anyway. The theoretically most explored lines areScotch Four Knights with  4.d4  , orthe Spanish Four Knights starting with  4.Bb5  .  These main lines are examined in the following chapter.   We also need to check some sidelines that White has tried. Against almost all slow moves, I recommend playing 4... d5. It is not a coincidence that 4. Bb5 and 4. d4 are the main lines... they stop ...d5! In some cases, 4... d5 will lead to lines where we are playing the Scotch Four Knights with colors reversed, and White has made an extra move. This extra move helps White, but not to the extent that it changes the position much. This applies to 4. a3 d5, 4. h3 d5 and 5. Be2 d5. By the way: it is not necessary to know the Scotch Four Knights inside and out, from White's point of view, to play in this fashion with Black. Note that we have to play the Black side after 4. d4, so the position types are familiar.   In the Quickstarter, we will look at  4.a3  d5  , which is the trickiest version of the 'small waiting moves'.   We will also check  4.Nxe5  , the crazy Halloween Gambit, and  4.Bc4  , which gives us good play after  4...Nxe4  .   A good line for White is  4.g3  , but after  4...d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  Bc5  we transpose to lines that we examine via 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5. }
4. Bb5
{ The Spanish Four Knights. Black's main lines always have been  4...Bb4  and  4...Nd4  , and those moves are indeed fine. However, I am going to recommend a different move, namely  4...Bc5  .  I believe this move is absolutely fine and the main lines have practical drawbacks. I need to be clear here: Black is completely fine, but in particular 4... Nd4 seems like a tough choice in a practical game. White may play the extremely boring  5.Nxd4  ,  against which it is very tough to play for a win. Or White may challenge you in the mainline. Then you need to know up to 25 moves of super-sharp theory to make a draw with a perpetual ultimately. There are multiple lines like that to remember, by the way - it is not just one. All this does not matter at the professional level: they are usually OK with a draw like that.   The second option is 4... Bb4, which I like better from a practical point of view. It is less tactical, so less effort is required to learn it, compared to 4... Nd4. However, after considering some other options, I remembered that I had recommended 4... Bc5 already back in 2012 when I released some Youtube videos on the subject. I checked my old analysis and was pleasantly surprised that Black is in even better shape nowadays, compared to some years ago. So why not go for this line? I need to mention that Caruana played 4... Nd4, but also 4... Bc5 once in this line - so I guess we have an endorsement by the challenger, in this case. }
4... Bc5
{ After  4...Bc5  White's most critical idea is to take on e5, either right away with  5.Nxe5  ,   or after  5.O-O  O-O  6.Nxe5  .   Before we check these, a quick word about  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.Nxe5  , which grabs a pawn. We are not concerned, as  6...Bxf2+!  7.Kxf2  Qd4+  quickly regains the material with good play. }
5. Nxe5
{ This pseudo-sacrifice has traditionally been the argument against 4... Bc5, but the current state of theory suggests that Black has good chances to equalize, and not just with one continuation. Let's have a closer look. }
5... Nxe5 6. d4 Bd6
{ Not the only move even though it looks very natural. Here Black has the good alternative, namely 6... a6, which has gained ground in recent years. The idea is to include the moves  6...a6  and  7.Be2  before retreating.   When I analyzed the 4... Bc5 line for my Youtube repertoire in 2012, I suggested  6...Bd6  , and I still see no problems with that move. }
7. f4
{ This is the most interesting move. White has also tried  7.dxe5  Bxe5  8.O-O  , when  8...O-O  transposes to the line 5. O-O O-O 6. Nxe5. }
7... Nc6
{ with O-O inserted for both sides, we play the knight to g4. In this particular version, however, going back to c6 is simpler to learn and play. }
8. e5 Bb4 9. exf6 Qxf6 10. a3
{ Here  10.Be3  is less critical, as it blocks the e-file. After  10...d5  11.O-O  Bxc3  12.bxc3  Bf5  Black is fine, enjoying good play on the light squares. }
10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 d5 12. O-O Bf5 13. Re1+
{ This looks like the critical try, but Black holds his own nicely. After  13.Rb1  O-O-O  Black was fine in the game R.Praggnanandhaa-I.Lysyj, Moscow 2018. }
13... Be4 14. Bd3 Qg6
{ White needs to continue with forcing the play. The excellent play on the light squares would give Black an easy game, otherwise. }
15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qd3 f5 17. Qb5
{ It looks dangerous, but Black has a good solution. } 17... O-O 18. Qxb7 Rab8
19. Qa6 { White needs to avoid  19.Qxc7??  Rf7  . } 19... Qe6
{ Black has full compensation, a key idea being to transfer the knight to c4, if possible. }
*

