ar.   In the Quickstarter, we will look at  4.a3  d5  , which is the trickiest version of the 'small waiting moves'.   We will also check  4.Nxe5  , the crazy Halloween Gambit, and  4.Bc4  , which gives us good play after  4...Nxe4  .   A good line for White is  4.g3  , but after  4...d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  Bc5  we transpose to lines that we examine via 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 d5. }
4. Bb5
{ The Spanish Four Knights. Black's main lines always have been  4...Bb4  and  4...Nd4  , and those moves are indeed fine. However, I am going to recommend a different move, namely  4...Bc5  .  I believe this move is absolutely fine and the main lines have practical drawbacks. I need to be clear here: Black is completely fine, but in particular 4... Nd4 seems like a tough choice in a practical game. White may play the extremely boring  5.Nxd4  ,  against which it is very tough to play for a win. Or White may challenge you in the mainline. Then you need to know up to 25 moves of super-sharp theory to make a draw with a perpetual ultimately. There are multiple lines like that to remember, by the way - it is not just one. All this does not matter at the professional level: they are usually OK with a draw like that.   The second option is 4... Bb4, which I like better from a practical point of view. It is less tactical, so less effort is required to learn it, compared to 4... Nd4. However, after considering some other options, I remembered that I had recommended 4... Bc5 already back in 2012 when I released some Youtube videos on the subject. I checked my old analysis and was pleasantly surprised that Black is in even better shape nowadays, compared to some years ago. So why not go for this line? I need to mention that Caruana played 4... Nd4, but also 4... Bc5 once in this line - so I guess we have an endorsement by the challenger, in this case. }
4... Bc5
{ After  4...Bc5  White's most critical idea is to take on e5, either right away with  5.Nxe5  ,   or after  5.O-O  O-O  6.Nxe5  .   Before we check these, a quick word about  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.Nxe5  , which grabs a pawn. We are not concerned, as  6...Bxf2+!  7.Kxf2  Qd4+  quickly regains the material with good play. }
5. O-O { White castles first and only later commits to action in the center. }
5... O-O
{ Caruana tried  5...d6  in an online Blitz game against MVL, but I believe that White is better after  6.d4  .   It's nothing special for White, but  5...O-O  is to be preferred here. We avoid a d2-d4 pawn push this way and are not afraid of the capture on c6. Now the pseudo sacrifice on e5 is the critical line, but White often tries slow moves that pose no problem at all. }
6. Bxc6
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This is a relatively harmless choice here. White's capture on e5 is harmless on the next move so that the game will look a lot like an Anti-Berlin @@StartBracket@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  @@EndBracket@@  where White has castled early on and put a knight on c3 - two choices that are toothless. }
6... dxc6 7. Nxe5
{ This is just fine for Black. It is important to note that 6. Bxc6 and  7.Nxe5  is a different story when the black bishop is on b4; later, Nd3 is less effective. White also has the slow  7.d3  ,  when Black covers e5 with  7...Qe7  or  7...Re8  and equal chances. }
7... Re8 8. Nc4 { Or  8.Nd3  Bg4  9.Qe1  Bd4  , when Black is in great shape. }
8... b5
{ Just taking with  8...Nxe4  is also fine, but  8...b5  is more ambitious. }
9. Ne3 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Rxe4 11. d3 Re6
{ The rook lift to g6 becomes an interesting option now. Black is for choice here, but White is still quite solid. }
