6. Nxe5
{ The pseudo-sacrifice must be the critical move, but Black holds his own nicely at the moment. Against the slow move  6.d3  Black's best reply is  6...Nd4  , which we check inthe full chapter. }
6... Nxe5 7. d4 Bd6 8. f4
{ This pawn phalanx is quite a sight, but concrete analysis shows that Black holds his own in a complicated struggle. Instead,  8.dxe5  Bxe5  is easy for Black to handle. }
8... Neg4
{ This is my preference here. Most of the time, White tries to regain the piece immediately with  9.e5  , but there have been other attempts to delay this procedure. }
9. e5
{ The most straightforward and popular move. In the full chapter, we'll also check the rare moves  9.Be2  and  9.h3  , which both should be answered with  9...Bb4  . }
9... Be7
{ In the recent Olympiad game V.Kovalev-L.Aronian Black went for  9...Bb4  ,  which is a viable alternative. After our bishop move to e7, White has tried various moves, but  10.f5  seems most interesting. }
10. f5
{ This appears to be the most dangerous move. In the full chapter, we also examine  10.Be2  d6   and  10.h3  d6  ,  when White will likely take on f6 after all. }
10... d6 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. Qf3
{ In the latest Chessbase Magazine GM E. Postny analyzes the line 4... Bc5 and concludes that it is an excellent alternative to the mainlines. However, he dislikes going into this position and recommends that Black should deviate earlier. 9... Bb4, as played by Aronian, or 8... Nc6 are possible ways to do that, and Black is OK there. I am still sticking with my preference for 9... Be7. If you dislike the coming lines, then I do mention good alternatives. }
12... d5
{ I suggest playing this instead of  12...c6  13.Bd3  d5  , when Postny suggests  14.g4!  for White, and concludes that this position is much easier for White to play. I agree - this indeed looks dangerous. The point of my move order is twofold: you may play a quick ...Bb4, trying to take the knight on c3 and get control over e4. The second point is to play ...c5 in one move if appropriate. }
13. g4
{ Certainly the most principled move. After  13.Bd3  Black should strike in the center with  13...c5  . }
13... Bb4 14. g5 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Ne4
{ Black managed to get the knight to e4. It is a very tough position with many possible moves for both sides. I will simply show one interesting line. }
16. f6 g6 17. Ba3 Re8
{ Instead  17...c5  or  17...c6  are possible, but the exchange sac is a fascinating option. }
18. Bxe8 Qxe8
{ Black has compensation in this position. Moves like ...Qa4 and ...Bf5 are coming, while the white bishop is pointing into thin air. }
