1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. Nf3
{ White's most popular move by a mile. Developing the knight and attacking e4 at the same time makes a ton of sense. }
2... Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. Now White's main moves are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  .   There are alternatives, but the only challenging one is  3.Nc3  , after which I recommend playing  3...Nc6  , transposing into aFour Knights game. This is Fabiano Caruana's choice, too.   In the Quickstarter, I'll also have a quick look at the dubious gambit  3.Bc4  . }
3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  . After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5
{ This is the traditional way to play the 3. d4 line for White. In recent years this mainline has not been tested much on the higher level. The current state of theory suggests that Black should be fine with the lines presented here. Caruana never faced this particular line, which shows that it is indeed out of fashion. Whenever an opponent played 3. d4, White would opt for a different approach on move 4 or 5. }
5... Nd7
{ As mentioned before, Caruana never faced this line, so we can only guess what would happen here. However,  5...Nd7  is the mainline, and Black has not experienced problems lately, so this seems like a perfect guess. What does the move do? Black immediately challenges the centralized knight on e5, avoiding any long-term concessions. For example,  5...Nc6  would allow doubled pawns, while  5...Bd6  and taking on e5 later concedes the pair of bishops. It needs to be said that the move has one serious practical implication: if White wants to force an immediate draw, he can do so by sacrificing on f7, which leads to an unavoidable repetition of moves.   After  5...Nd7  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qh5+  Ke7  8.Qe2  , you need to play  8...Kf7  and repeat. This should be kept in mind if a draw is completely unacceptable in a particular game. }
6. Qe2
{ This move was played in probably the most famous game of the whole line with 5... Nd7. World Champion Anatoly Karpov played it against Bent Larsen in 1980... and Larsen went on to win an excellent game against the dominant player of that time. After this game, 6. Qe2 was still tried quite frequently, and the reason is quite clear: White wins a pawn, which is always tempting. The good news is that the mandatory pawn sac gives us great compensation. Let's see what I am talking about. }
6... Nxe5 7. Bxe4 dxe4 8. Qxe4
{ The knight is lost, and White will be a pawn up, but Black's compensation will be compelling as the coming lines show. }
8... Be6 9. Qxe5
{ 9.dxe5  is even worse after  9...Bd5  10.Qg4  h5  , giving Black a strong initiative. }
9... Qd7
{ We enjoy good development and the pair of bishops. Black's position is straightforward to play. Even if you don't find the  best line at all times is often the emergency exit to trade the dark-squared bishop for the knight and go into an opposite-colored bishops scenario where the pawn count does not matter most of the time. }
10. O-O
{ The most natural move. White can also start with  10.Be3  , when it is crucial to avoid  10...O-O-O?  11.Qa5  .   Black should play  10.Be3  Bb4+  instead, which might lead to a similar play as 10. O-O in many cases. An independent line is  11.c3  Bd6  12.Qxg7  O-O-O  , which gives Black an excellent position for the material deficit. }
10... O-O-O 11. Be3 Bb4
{ A truly excellent concept, first played by Larsen against Karpov in 1980. I think it is truly admirable that he looked at the 5... Nd7- line without prejudice, analyzed this far, and concluded to have reasonable compensation. Nowadays, we switch on the engine to tell us that it should work - Larsen had to do it entirely on his own. Why is that a strong move, by the way? The key is to recognize that White had Qa5 on the agenda, which is now prevented. }
12. Nc3
{ Karpov's choice in the famous Larsen game. This is one of the very few cases of Karpov committing a strategic mistake. As we will see, it leads to a passive and challenging to play position for White. Better than  12.Nc3  are  12.c3  or  12.a3  . In both cases, Black has good play for the pawn, as examined in the full chapter. }
12... f6 13. Qg3 Bxc3
{ Very nicely played. Now the opposite-colored bishops favor Black, as the light squares in White's camp are weak. }
14. bxc3 h5
{ An important motif to remember. Black intends to push the pawn to h3, provoking more weaknesses on the light squares around White's King. }
15. h4 g5
{ And here I'll stop quoting the game A. Karpov-B. Larsen, Tilburg 1980. Larsen has a great attack here and went on to win a classic game that is worth studying till the end. }
