2. Nf3
{ White's most popular move by a mile. Developing the knight and attacking e4 at the same time makes a ton of sense. }
2... Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. Now White's main moves are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  .   There are alternatives, but the only challenging one is  3.Nc3  , after which I recommend playing  3...Nc6  , transposing into aFour Knights game. This is Fabiano Caruana's choice, too.   In the Quickstarter, I'll also have a quick look at the dubious gambit  3.Bc4  . }
3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  . After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5
{ This is the traditional way to play the 3. d4 line for White. In recent years this mainline has not been tested much on the higher level. The current state of theory suggests that Black should be fine with the lines presented here. Caruana never faced this particular line, which shows that it is indeed out of fashion. Whenever an opponent played 3. d4, White would opt for a different approach on move 4 or 5. }
5... Nd7
{ As mentioned before, Caruana never faced this line, so we can only guess what would happen here. However,  5...Nd7  is the mainline, and Black has not experienced problems lately, so this seems like a perfect guess. What does the move do? Black immediately challenges the centralized knight on e5, avoiding any long-term concessions. For example,  5...Nc6  would allow doubled pawns, while  5...Bd6  and taking on e5 later concedes the pair of bishops. It needs to be said that the move has one serious practical implication: if White wants to force an immediate draw, he can do so by sacrificing on f7, which leads to an unavoidable repetition of moves.   After  5...Nd7  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qh5+  Ke7  8.Qe2  , you need to play  8...Kf7  and repeat. This should be kept in mind if a draw is completely unacceptable in a particular game. }
6. O-O
{ This move invites @@StartBracket@@almost forces@@EndBracket@@ Black to take on e5, which leads to a pawn structure that is frequently seen in the 3. d4 variation. }
6... Nxe5
{ Black has experimented with  6...Be7  and  6...Bd6  ,  but taking looks very natural. It makes a lot of sense to get rid of the d7-knight, freeing up the c8-bishop. }
7. dxe5 Nc5
{ White was threatening to undermine the knight with c4, so this retreat is not entirely voluntary. White now needs to decide on two issues mostly: do you want to keep the bishop on d3, and do you want to push f4 soon? White has tried a range of moves here, but Black is acceptable in any case. }
8. Nc3
{ This not only develops the piece but also threatens  Nxd5  , so you need to avoid a routine move like  8...Be7  , for example. In this case,  9.Nxd5!  Qxd5?  10.Bb5+  wins the queen!   Instead of  8.Nc3  White has also tried  8.Be3  frequently, when I suggest playing  8...c6  .   After the direct  8.f4  , we should play  8...Nxd3  9.Qxd3  g6  ,  planning ...Bf5. }
8... c6 { The pawn needs some support, so we play this useful move. } 9. Ne2
{ This has been tried by some strong players, most noticeably by Mamedyarov against Kramnik. Against  9.f4  , we again have the plan  9...Nxd3  10.Qxd3  Bc5+  11.Kh1  g6  ,  with ...Bf5 on the cards. }
9... Be7 10. f4 f6
{ Against f4-ideas by White, you have two options.   A: take on d3 and play ...g6 to stop the f-pawn or   B: go for ... f6, attacking the center.   In this particular case. ...f6 is fine as there is no Qh5 reply, and White has played somewhat slowly with Nc3-e2. In general, my take is to play plan B, if possible. Otherwise, stick with plan A. I have a preference for B because getting rid of the somewhat obstructing e5-pawn is desirable. }
11. Be3 O-O
{ Kramnik instead took on d3 immediately, but the capture White cannot prevent anyway, so it makes some sense to keep the tension. }
12. Qd2
{ 11... O-O is a yet unplayed suggestion, so that we will explore a bit without any practical examples. 12. Qd2 looks very natural to connect the rooks. }
12... Nxd3
{ You may also wait even longer with this move. Stockfish also likes the eccentric  12...Qd7  , but taking is just fine. }
13. cxd3 c5 14. d4
{ This is correct. White should not allow the d-pawn to go to d4. A pawn advance to d4 would create an excellent square on d5 for Black's pieces. }
14... c4
{ I suggest closing it with  14...c4  , but  14...b6  seems playable as well. Now we will play the pawn to f5 soon, shutting down White's kingside play. Then we'll try to set the queenside majority in motion. The engine calls it equal, but I'd rather be Black here. }
