{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  . After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. dxe5
{ As White was struggling more and more to get anywhere with the traditional  5.Nxe5  , this capture became more popular. The e-pawn obstructs the Black pieces, but Black has a healthy development and chances to set his majority in motion later. These positions are about equal, but not in a sterile way - there is play left, which is not the case in many  5.Nxe5  mainlines. }
5... Nc5
{ The main move. Black either wants to push the d3-bishop back to e2 or take it at an opportune moment. }
6. Be2
{ White preserves the bishop pair. White may also allow the capture and play  6.Nc3  or the more popular  6.O-O  . Black shouldn't take immediately, but rather play  6...Be7  7.Nc3  c6  8.Nd4  Nxd3  9.Qxd3  O-O  10.f4  , when  10...f6!  is good reply. The key idea in this line is  11.e6  f5!  , leaving Black in good shape. }
6... Be7 7. O-O
{ By far the mainline. White needs to castle anyway and keeps options open. }
7... O-O 8. Be3 c6
{ Black's idea is to develop with ...Nbd7 and possibly ...Qc7/...f6 to follow. I also like  8...Nc6  instead, with about equal play. It makes sense to develop and put pressure on  e5  quickly.   It comes down to a matter of taste, but I think my choice  8....c6  is simpler to learn and play. }
9. c4
{ This makes more sense now, compared to 8. c4. Now Black is committed to a pawn on c6, so a later ...Nc6 is impossible. Black is still fine, of course, as we will see. }
9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nbd7
{ Black intends to develop with ...Nb6 and then choose the best square for the bishop on c8. Note that the e5-pawn is a possible target if White is not careful. }
12. b4
{ A direct approach that @@StartBracket@@almost@@EndBracket@@ forces the knight back to e6. The @@StartBracket@@'almost'@@EndBracket@@ is used because of the playable  12...b5  , but I suggest just moving the attacked piece. }
12... Ne6 13. a3 Nb6 14. Ba2 Nc7 15. Nc3 Be6
{ And Black had equalized in the game S.Movsesian- D.Fridman, German Bundesliga 2013. GM Daniel Fridman is a Petroff expert, and his games are always worth studying. We have been club and teammates for some years for the team of Muelheim-Nord. During that time, he played the Petroff a lot against top-level opposition, with good results. }
