{ This is the traditional way to play the 3. d4 line for White. In recent years this mainline has not been tested much on the higher level. The current state of theory suggests that Black should be fine with the lines presented here. Caruana never faced this particular line, which shows that it is indeed out of fashion. Whenever an opponent played 3. d4, White would opt for a different approach on move 4 or 5. }
5... Nd7
{ As mentioned before, Caruana never faced this line, so we can only guess what would happen here. However,  5...Nd7  is the mainline, and Black has not experienced problems lately, so this seems like a perfect guess. What does the move do? Black immediately challenges the centralized knight on e5, avoiding any long-term concessions. For example,  5...Nc6  would allow doubled pawns, while  5...Bd6  and taking on e5 later concedes the pair of bishops. It needs to be said that the move has one serious practical implication: if White wants to force an immediate draw, he can do so by sacrificing on f7, which leads to an unavoidable repetition of moves.   After  5...Nd7  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qh5+  Ke7  8.Qe2  , you need to play  8...Kf7  and repeat. This should be kept in mind if a draw is completely unacceptable in a particular game. }
6. Nxd7 Bxd7 7. O-O { Certainly the most natural and popular move.. } 7... Bd6
{ This is the mainline at the professional levels nowadays. Black has also tried other moves, most notably  7...Qh4  . This active move is probably not entirely sound, but it is worth looking at if you want a sharp option to play occasionally. After  7...Bd6  White's only hope for advantage is some very concrete play based on attacking the knight on e4 and the pawn on d5. Any slow approach is completely harmless - Black has no weaknesses, and the pieces are well developed. What White will try is some combination of the moves c4, Nc3, and Qh5. Black's responses are quite natural, but it pays to know the lines precisely. This whole complex of lines is not played that frequently anymore at the top level because with 'perfect play,' Black will fully equalize. }
8. Qh5
{ The quick queen sortie enjoyed some popularity, but Black has now figured out how to defuse the idea. }
8... Qf6
{ In the spirit of the Petroff: Our central pawn is attacked, so we attack the white central pawn as well. }
9. Nc3
{ This is the most popular and critical move. After  9.Qxd5  Bc6  10.Bb5  O-O-O  11.Qb3  Bxb5  12.Qxb5  Qxd4  Black is fine. }
9... Qxd4 10. Be3 Qe5 11. Qxe5+ Bxe5 12. Nxd5 Nf6
{ At first, it looks like dead equal already, but White still has an idea. }
13. Rae1
{ This looks a bit odd, as  13.Rfe1  is more natural. After  13.Rfe1  O-O  14.Bc5  Bxb2  the complications lead to equal chances, as analyzed inthe full chapter. }
13... Nxd5 14. Bd4 O-O-O 15. Bxe5 Nb4 16. Bxg7 Nxd3 17. cxd3 Rhg8
{ Black's pawn deficit is only temporary. He's active, with counterplay against g2. The opposite-colored bishops are an additional drawing factor. }
