{ This is the mainline at the professional levels nowadays. Black has also tried other moves, most notably  7...Qh4  . This active move is probably not entirely sound, but it is worth looking at if you want a sharp option to play occasionally. After  7...Bd6  White's only hope for advantage is some very concrete play based on attacking the knight on e4 and the pawn on d5. Any slow approach is completely harmless - Black has no weaknesses, and the pieces are well developed. What White will try is some combination of the moves c4, Nc3, and Qh5. Black's responses are quite natural, but it pays to know the lines precisely. This whole complex of lines is not played that frequently anymore at the top level because with 'perfect play,' Black will fully equalize. }
8. c4
{ This is the mainline by pure game count. White attacks the base of the e4-knight, which leaves little choice for Black. }
8... c6 9. cxd5
{ White has also tried  9.Nc3  , which after  9...Nxc3  10.bxc3  O-O  11.cxd5  usually transposes to 9. cxd5. }
9... cxd5
{ Now White has two ways to win the d5 pawn. In both cases, Black will have excellent piece play to compensate for the material loss. }
10. Qh5
{ This line is worked out to a draw with perfect play. In many cases, it is rather White who might slip in the complications. }
10... O-O
{ This is the idea, of course. We give up the d5 pawn for activity. Instead  10...Nf6?  11.Re1+  is just awful for Black. }
11. Qxd5 Bc6 12. Qh5 g6
{ Logical and forced up to now. White now should stay on the h-file to keep h4 covered, preventing the black queen from joining the attack. }
13. Qh3
{ This is by far the main move, but Black has worked out how to equalize against it. After  13.Qh6  Black has  13...Re8  when  14.Be3  Bf8  15.Qh3  h5  leads to good play for Black. }
13... Ng5 14. Qg4
{ After  14.Bxg5  Qxg5  Black has good compensation for the pawn by simple development. Doubling the rooks on the e-file is a good follow-up when White struggles to organize their play. }
14... Ne6
{ Now Black's threat is to play ...h5, followed by just taking on d4. } 15. Bh6
{ White has to avoid  15.Nc3  h5  16.Qh3  Nxd4  , with Black being already better. }
15... Bf4
{ Wow, a nice shot! Black may also play  15...Re8  with equal play at the end, but maybe some opponents want to take on f8 now? }
16. Bxf8
{ This loses spectacularly. White has to play  16.Bxf4  Qxd4  17.Nc3  Qxf4  , with equality. }
16... h5 17. Qd1 Bxg2
{ Black has too many attacking pieces near White's King. This sacrifice smashes the pawn shield for the decisive attack. }
18. Kxg2 Qg5+ 19. Kh3 Bc7 20. f4 Nxf4+ 21. Rxf4 Qxf4
{ And Black's attack is impossible to fend off. } *

