10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. Qh5 g6
{ @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pppb1ppp/3b4/3p4/3Pn3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@ Again, Black gives up the d5-pawn for activity. Note that there is a line with a similar theme: after  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  O-O  10.Qh5  we need to play  10...f5  , as  10...g6  gives away the d5-pawn for nothing. Here we can sac the pawn for counterplay. One key difference with ...f5 in those two cases is that Black already has an isolated d-pawn, which makes creating additional weak squares with 12... f5 less attractive. I rather give up the problem pawn and prove equality by playing actively. That being said, Black has scored decently with 12... f5 as well. I don't regard it as sound as the pawn sac. }
13. Qxd5 Qc7
{ Black has a good development and now double attacks the pawns on c3 and h2 @@StartBracket@@with check@@EndBracket@@. At this point, White has tried a lot of moves, not getting anywhere ultimately. Still, we need to check many lines now. White quite often starts with  14.Bh6  , but he might also play this move later, basically forcing the rook to move. This way, we get some transpositions, but it is not difficult to play for Black, as the ideas remain the same. }
