1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. Nf3
{ White's most popular move by a mile. Developing the knight and attacking e4 at the same time makes a ton of sense. }
2... Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. Now White's main moves are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  .   There are alternatives, but the only challenging one is  3.Nc3  , after which I recommend playing  3...Nc6  , transposing into aFour Knights game. This is Fabiano Caruana's choice, too.   In the Quickstarter, I'll also have a quick look at the dubious gambit  3.Bc4  . }
3. Nxe5 { Taking the pawn is White's most popular and natural move. } 3... d6
4. Nxf7
{ This is the Cochrane gambit. White sacrifices the knight for two pawns and hopes that the black king in the center gives compensation. It is not an entirely correct line, but you can't expect to refute it outright. One thing needs to be mentioned: you should play the lines suggested here; alternatives don't convince as much. Let's check the details. }
4... Kxf7 5. d4
{ White's main move, occupying the center.  5.Bc4+?  is wrong due to  5...d5  6.exd5  Bd6  ,  when Black will be the one attacking after ...Rf8 and ...Kg8 next. }
5... c5
{ This is the most important idea to remember. Black immediately attacks White's center and intends to make use of his extra piece and development advantage. Black needs to avoid the clear mistake  5...Nxe4?  due to  6.Qh5+  Ke7  7.Qe2  .  White regains the piece with interest in this line. We should also avoid playing passively with slow moves. White's play is too simple in this case. He will build up a strong center with f4 and a later e5 and have quite reasonable compensation. }
6. dxc5
{ After  6.Bc4+?  d5  7.exd5  b5!  Black is taking over the initiative quickly. }
6... Nc6
{ The alternative  6...d5  is also promising. However,  6...Nc6  is a good move, and the following positions may also arise from the different move order 5. Nc3 c5 - it, therefore, makes sense to choose this line as we need to know it anyway. Black enjoys an excellent development now, making the somewhat open king position less relevant. }
7. Bc4+ Be6 8. Bxe6+ Kxe6
{ Now Black has three pieces in play! Don't worry too much about the king; we will go back to f7 in short order and White does not have any piece developed that could harm us. }
9. Nc3 Kf7
{ The king needs to be withdrawn from the center quickly. It is worse to play  9...dxc5  due to  10.Qe2  , which gives White too much play for the invested material. }
10. Qe2 Qd7
{ @@StartFEN@@r2q1b1r/pp4pp/2npkn2/2P5/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ The queen needs to help against the idea to play Qc4+. It is important to note that in the line with  9.O-O  Kf7  10.Qe2  we play  ...Qe8  instead. The reason becomes apparent when we check the move  11.Be3  .  After this move, we now simply take on c5 and prevent queenside castling, which would not be possible with the queen on e8. This point is not relevant after the early 9. O-O. Against the quick kingside castling going ...Qe8 is sensible as it also attacks the pawn on e4 immediately. }
11. Be3 dxc5 12. f4 Rd8
{ This is the engine's improvement on  11...Re8  , played in the game V.Topalov-V.Kramnik, Linares 1999. I am still quite amazed that Topalov dared to play this line against Kramnik. }
13. e5 { The way Topalov played against  12...Re8  does not work here. } 13...
Ng4 14. Rd1 Nd4
{ This is very strong now. With the rook on e8 White would have  15.Bxd4  cxd4  16.h3  now, because  16...Ne3  fails due to  17.Qxe3  . }
15. Bxd4 cxd4 16. O-O h5 { Black has a huge advantage and should win. } *

