4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Tame alternatives are  4.Nc4  and  4.Nd3  , which don't seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defense. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4
{ We have regained the pawn. Now White's traditional mainline is  5.d4  , but the move  5.Nc3  has gained much popularity in the last decades and is regarded as the 'Modern Main Line' of the Petroff. There are some less popular alternatives that we will briefly examine in the Quickstarter. }
5. d4 d5 6. Bd3
{ The only sensible move and the mainline not by miles, but rather light-years. }
6... Bd6
{ This is Caruana's choice, but I like to point out that Black also has excellent results with a line that most of the top Chinese players play. This line starts either  6...Be7  7.O-O  Bf5   or  6...Bf5  7.O-O  Be7  and is extremely solid for Black. I had employed this line in a crucial game this year @@StartBracket@@2018@@EndBracket@@ when I needed a draw with Black against GM Stanley Martinez to fight for the top prizes in the San Sebastian Open.   The 'Chinese Wall' is a worthy alternative to our choice  6...Bd6  ,  which is a more ambitious way to play. Black is placing the bishop on the most active square and challenges White to prove that the knight on e4 is a liability in an otherwise symmetrical position. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ Almost invariably played, and for a good reason. White needs to pressure the d5-pawn and knight on e4; there is just no other reasonable plan to pursue. Lines like  8.Re1  Bf5   or  8.Nbd2  Bf5  are completely harmless. }
8... c6
{ This is the actual starting point, the tabiya of the 6... Bd6 Petroff mainline. All deviations before are harmless for Black or, at best, transpose here. Now White has tried a range of moves and ideas. The key piece is the knight on e4. It is active on e4, but also subject to attacks. All the natural moves available to White have some connection to the knight. White may play Nc3 now or after the trade or attack the knight on e4 with Re1 or Qc2. The play is very concrete and tactical, so knowing the lines well and calculating precisely are important key virtues in this complex of lines. }
9. Nc3
{ The most popular move, and the one I would expect to happen most frequently at the non-professional level. It is a very natural continuation for sure and often the choice of players who don't know deep theory at this point. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4
{ Black has also played  10...Bg4  here, but we follow Caruana's repertoire and taking on c4 seems like the soundest choice anyway. }
11. Bxc4 Bf5
{ We reached the most common pawn structure in the Petroff. White does not have many options with pawn play but rather relies on piece activity. Now  12.Bg5  is the latest trend, but White has tried a lot of moves besides that. We'll check these alternatives in the dedicated chapter. }
12. Bg5
{ One of the most recent tries to break down Caruana's Petroff featured this move. It was played in A.Giri-F.Caruana, Baden-Baden 2018. }
12... Qa5 13. Nh4
{ The concrete idea of this line. Black now needs to drop back to e6. After  13...Bg6  14.f4!  is terrible for Black. }
13... Be6 14. Bxe6 Qxg5 15. Nf3 Qa5
{ Caruana played  15...Qd8  against Giri. He equalized with this move but ultimately lost the game after some wrong decisions. I suggest playing  15...Qa5  instead. I don't think it is much of a difference, but I feel you are organizing a bit quicker with Black. }
16. Bb3 { Against  16.Qb3  we have  16...Qb6  . } 16... Nd7
{ Please don't take on c3! After  16...Qxc3  17.Ng5  Black is immediately killed on the kingside. }
17. Qd3 Rae8 18. g3 g6
{ And Black was OK in B.Bellahcene-P.Tregubov, Brest 2018. Just as in the Giri-Caruana game, White may continue to play and maneuver in such a position. You need to be patient and be ready to play a long game if White desires to do so. }
