{ This is the actual starting point, the tabiya of the 6... Bd6 Petroff mainline. All deviations before are harmless for Black or, at best, transpose here. Now White has tried a range of moves and ideas. The key piece is the knight on e4. It is active on e4, but also subject to attacks. All the natural moves available to White have some connection to the knight. White may play Nc3 now or after the trade or attack the knight on e4 with Re1 or Qc2. The play is very concrete and tactical, so knowing the lines well and calculating precisely are important key virtues in this complex of lines. }
9. cxd5 { White trades first, followed by Nc3. } 9... cxd5 10. Nc3
{ This line was quite popular about 20 years ago, but nowadays, it is not viewed as particularly dangerous for Black. One indicator is that no one has tried it yet against Fabiano Caruana, and there were plenty of chances to do so by top players. }
10... Re8
{ This seems like a good, low-maintenance solution to me. Black also has the sharper  10...Nxc3  11.bxc3  Bg4  , but this is quite a chunk of theory for not that great a reward. }
11. Re1
{ More popular than 11. h3, but it leads to more trades. After  11.h3  I suggest  11...Nxc3  12.bxc3  h6  , as analyzed in more detail in the full chapter. }
11... Nxc3 12. Rxe8+ Qxe8 13. bxc3 Bg4 { The most active move. } 14. Rb1 Nd7
{ Important to remember. The pawn on b7 is tactically covered, so we simply develop the knight. White has to avoid  15.Rxb7?  Nb6  , when the rook is trapped. }
15. Bd2 h6 { And Black had equalized in R.Fridman-V.Savchenko, Germany 2011. }
