1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. Nf3
{ White's most popular move by a mile. Developing the knight and attacking e4 at the same time makes a ton of sense. }
2... Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. Now White's main moves are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  .   There are alternatives, but the only challenging one is  3.Nc3  , after which I recommend playing  3...Nc6  , transposing into aFour Knights game. This is Fabiano Caruana's choice, too.   In the Quickstarter, I'll also have a quick look at the dubious gambit  3.Bc4  . }
3. Nxe5 { Taking the pawn is White's most popular and natural move. } 3... d6
4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Tame alternatives are  4.Nc4  and  4.Nd3  , which don't seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defense. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4
{ We have regained the pawn. Now White's traditional mainline is  5.d4  , but the move  5.Nc3  has gained much popularity in the last decades and is regarded as the 'Modern Main Line' of the Petroff. There are some less popular alternatives that we will briefly examine in the Quickstarter. }
5. d4 d5 6. Bd3
{ The only sensible move and the mainline not by miles, but rather light-years. }
6... Bd6
{ This is Caruana's choice, but I like to point out that Black also has excellent results with a line that most of the top Chinese players play. This line starts either  6...Be7  7.O-O  Bf5   or  6...Bf5  7.O-O  Be7  and is extremely solid for Black. I had employed this line in a crucial game this year @@StartBracket@@2018@@EndBracket@@ when I needed a draw with Black against GM Stanley Martinez to fight for the top prizes in the San Sebastian Open.   The 'Chinese Wall' is a worthy alternative to our choice  6...Bd6  ,  which is a more ambitious way to play. Black is placing the bishop on the most active square and challenges White to prove that the knight on e4 is a liability in an otherwise symmetrical position. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ Almost invariably played, and for a good reason. White needs to pressure the d5-pawn and knight on e4; there is just no other reasonable plan to pursue. Lines like  8.Re1  Bf5   or  8.Nbd2  Bf5  are completely harmless. }
8... c6
{ This is the actual starting point, the tabiya of the 6... Bd6 Petroff mainline. All deviations before are harmless for Black or, at best, transpose here. Now White has tried a range of moves and ideas. The key piece is the knight on e4. It is active on e4, but also subject to attacks. All the natural moves available to White have some connection to the knight. White may play Nc3 now or after the trade or attack the knight on e4 with Re1 or Qc2. The play is very concrete and tactical, so knowing the lines well and calculating precisely are important key virtues in this complex of lines. }
9. Qc2 Na6 10. a3 Bg4 11. Ne5
{ The only critical move at this moment.  11.Bxe4  dxe4  12.Qxe4  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  Qh4  14.g3  Qxd4  is even slightly better for Black. }
11... Bf5
{ This is Caruana's choice, but the traditional  11...Bxe5  is interesting as well. }
12. b4
{ This not only gains space, but it has a very tactical justification. Black has the idea to play ...Nac5, using the unstable position of the knight on e5. This would happen in the line  12.Be3  Nac5!  , as discussed inthe full chapter. }
12... Nc7
{ Caruana's novelty in his game against Vishy Anand in Wijk aan Zee 2018. Fabiano lost this game, but it was not due to this new concept. The great point comes on the next move. I want to mention that black also has the stunning  12...c5  at his disposal. I couldn't find a white advantage against this either, but you can do worse than trust Caruana in the Petroff.  A general note: general considerations don't play a massive role in the upcoming complications; it's just a matter of 'it works' or 'it doesn't work' in most cases. The lines are incredibly tactical, and I advise you to analyze them to understand the tactical ideas better. I will guide you through the jungle, but in some cases, there are so many possibilities that showing all lines is just overkill - you should put it on the board and use your engines to explore on your own. }
13. f3
{ The most obvious and critical move - what is black doing with this pin now? Still, it is worth checking the alternative move  13.Nc3  . In the dedicated chapter, you'll find more about the crazy complications after this move. }
13... Bg6
{ It is remarkable that 13. f3 can be answered by this calm retreat! It is not the only move, by the way: in a game played some months after the debut of the line  13...Bxe5  was tried, and Black drew later in A.Shirov-M.Antonsen, Helsingor 2018. I checked this line and found no substantial problem, but I see no reason to deviate from Caruana's original concept. }
14. Nxg6
{ In the Quickstarter, we'll have a look at this move. White takes on g6, intending to grab the knight on e4 next. Taking the knight immediately is wrong. After  14.fxe4  Bxe5  15.dxe5  dxe4  the point ...Qd4+ gives Black the advantage.   Anand played differently:  14.c5  Bxe5  15.dxe5  Ng5  16.Bb2  White's idea is to play Nd2 and f4, harassing the knight on g5  16...Bxd3   @@StartBracket@@This is the improvement on Caruana's  16...d4  , which did not work out well for him. After the better move, Black is completely fine according to Vishy Anand's annotations in NIC magazine.@@EndBracket@@  17.Qxd3  a5  @@StartBracket@@This detail is crucial as it allows a later trade on a1.   Anand mentions the alternative  17...g6  18.f4  Ne4  19.Nd2  Nxd2  20.Qxd2  Ne6  21.Rae1  and White keeps more attacking potential on the board.@@EndBracket@@  18.Nd2  axb4  19.axb4  Rxa1  20.Bxa1  Nge6  21.f4  g6  The final move of Anand's analysis, concluding that Black has no problems. We should check White's most direct approach.  22.f5  gxf5  23.Qxf5  On general grounds, I wouldn't be worried much here with Black. White has a non-piece on a1 so that we won't get checkmated. Qg5 Black is fine here, in particular, if White decides to trade queens. The white bishop and pawn structure don't go well together in endgames. }
14... fxg6 15. fxe4
{ Of course, we need to check what happens if White grabs the piece. Instead  15.c5  Bxh2+  16.Kxh2  Qh4+  17.Kg1  Ng3  gives Black a crushing attack. }
15... dxe4 16. Rxf8+ Bxf8 17. Bxe4 Qxd4+ 18. Kf1 Qf6+
{ This is very important to remember. You should not take on a1, as after  18...Qxa1  19.Bb2  Qa2  20.Bd3  things are not at all clear, and White seems to be better if anybody. }
19. Kg1 Qd4+ { And it is a draw. } *

