1. e4 e5
{ Hello and Welcome to the Quickstarter Guide of 'The unbreakable Petroff, Caruana's complete Repertoire against 1.e4'.  This course provides a complete repertoire against 1. e4, based on the classical reply 1... e5.   The repertoire choices are based on Fabiano Caruana's opening repertoire, who played the Petroff Defence with excellent results in his run to become Magnus Carlsen's World Title challenger in 2018.   A large portion of this course is devoted to the Petroff, but we also cover sidelines that White may play, from the romantic King's Gambit to the solid Four Knights game.  In most cases, I have selected the lines based on Fabiano Caruana's games. This makes a choice easy for the main lines. Sidelines, however, are rare for reasons.   On the top level, these dubious or unambitious options are rarely seen. Therefore, I needed to choose antidotes against the sidelines according to my taste and preferences.   My usual approach in this course is a maximalist one. Given a choice, I will usually suggest the most ambitious continuation. A good example is the reply to the King's Gambit. It is relatively easy to equalize against it, but I recommend playing more ambitiously.   This involves more lines to study but also leads to more exciting chess.   In the Quickstarter Guide, we will examine the essential lines of this course. After studying this chapter, you will be able to employ the repertoire in your games.   Later, you can learn all the details of the dedicated chapters. The analysis can be intense in many lines because the Petroff is a very tactical opening. It is tough to learn all the lines until the very end.   Depending on your preferences, it might make sense to pause some variations if you feel that you don't need this depth at your level of play. }
2. Nf3
{ White's most popular move by a mile. Developing the knight and attacking e4 at the same time makes a ton of sense. }
2... Nf6
{ The starting position of the Petroff. Now White's main moves are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  .   There are alternatives, but the only challenging one is  3.Nc3  , after which I recommend playing  3...Nc6  , transposing into aFour Knights game. This is Fabiano Caruana's choice, too.   In the Quickstarter, I'll also have a quick look at the dubious gambit  3.Bc4  . }
3. Nxe5 { Taking the pawn is White's most popular and natural move. } 3... d6
4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Tame alternatives are  4.Nc4  and  4.Nd3  , which don't seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defense. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4
{ We have regained the pawn. Now White's traditional mainline is  5.d4  , but the move  5.Nc3  has gained much popularity in the last decades and is regarded as the 'Modern Main Line' of the Petroff. There are some less popular alternatives that we will briefly examine in the Quickstarter. }
5. Nc3
{ This is the modern mainline of the Petroff. When the Petroff got more popular at the start of the Millenium, White had a hard time proving anything in the traditional mainline of  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@this is still the case, actually!@@EndBracket@@. So White turned attention to other tries, and  5.Nc3  quickly emerged as an exciting weapon to combat the Petroff. Nowadays, 5. Nc3 is the mainline of the Petroff, so we need to take it very seriously. We'll discuss the ideas connected to after the next move. }
5... Nxc3
{ Most natural and best. However, I'd like to mention that I have played  5...Nf6  in classical time control chess and quicker formats. The main reason is not so much the quality of the move, but rather my lack of knowledge of the main lines. When I prepared the Petroff as a surprise weapon at the end of 2017, I wanted a simple line that my opponents probably don't know all that well, so I went for 5... Nf6. I still think this is a decent choice, but it should not be the main recommendation in a repertoire heavily influenced by Fabiano Caruana's way of handling the black pieces. Caruana always played  5...Nxc3  , so this has to be the choice. }
6. dxc3
{ This is the idea connected to the modern mainline. By capturing this way, White emphasizes the development and prepares a quick queenside castling. The following moves by White will often be Be3/Qd2/ O-O-O. It is essential to understand that the queenside pawn formation for White is excellent in terms of king safety. White will therefore play queenside castling, almost no matter what Black is doing... so Black needs to decide where to place the king. You may castle queenside as well, which is the safe and sound choice, but It is more exciting to castle kingside.   When this course was released in 2018, Fabiano Caruana mainly had played with O-O-O as Black, but he had also tried the sharper option twice: he played the early O-O vs. Ray Robson at the US Championships and against Levon Aronian at the Olympiad. So at the time of writing, it was not 100% clear what Fabiano's preference was. I decided to cover O-O-O, but just a couple of weeks later, during the World Championship Match in London, Caruana played the ...O-O version and later analysis and games indicated that Black's chances are entirely satisfactory. While ...O-O-O lines remain playable, the current theoretical status of ...O-O is better, and therefore I decided to focus on this approach for the 2021 update of the course. }
6... Be7
{ In this chapter, we will cover Black's approach to castle kingside in the Modern Main Line. Before the World Championship Match 2018, Caruana had frequently played the lines covered inChapter 9, involving ...O-O-O. In the actual Match in London, however, his choice was to castle kingside. This approach is now the main battleground of the Modern Mainline and therefore covered in this chapter. White's choice now is between  7.Bf4  and the more popular move  7.Be3  . Black needs to be aware that the difference between these moves is quite substantial. Black is in fine shape, but you don't have a universal plan for both lines. We'll also have a quick look at White's rare alternatives on move 7, but these pose no particular problems. }
7. Bf4
{ This move is White's main alternative to  7.Be3  . It was out of fashion for a long time but recently gained some popularity. The reason is not so much that  7.Bf4  is particularly strong, but rather Black's excellent results against 7. Be3. After 7. Be3 Black is doing fine with the plan ...Nd7-f6, followed by ...c5. This plan is not possible against 7. Bf4, as White's bishop is geared towards d6, so a later ...c5 would just blunder the d6-pawn. This means that Black needs an entirely different approach against 7. Bf4 than 7. Be3. The tried and tested method against 7. Bf4 involves a quick ...Nd7-c5 maneuver, intending to hit the f4-bishop with ...Ne6 in some lines. Let's have a closer look. }
7... O-O
{ We always castle short in this chapter. There is nothing wrong about going for ...O-O-O, either. You could argue that the bishop on f4 is not ideally placed to fight ...O-O-O, as it exerts no pressure on a7. The choice between queenside and kingside castling is a matter of taste. In this chapter, we'll focus on ...O-O-O, which is somewhat more confrontational. }
8. Qd2 { White prepares queenside castling, the logical follow-up. } 8... Nd7
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/8/2P2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@ Our knight almost always goes to ...d7 in this chapter, but the move involves more than just one idea. In the line  7.Be3  O-O  8.Qd2  Nd7  ,  we play to transfer the knight to f6, helping to defend the kingside. The moves ...c5 and ...d5 are on our agenda. With the white bishop sitting on f4, this pawn formation is unattainable due to the pressure on d6. Therefore, we switch gears and use the knight on the square c5, planning to play ...Ne6 quickly. }
9. O-O-O Nc5
{ After  9...Nc5  , White's mainline is  10.Be3  , but the moves  10.Nd4  and  10.h4  are frequently played, too. Against Nd4 ideas, the reply ...Ne6 is a good option for Black. }
10. Be3
{ White moves the bishop again before ...Ne6 would come with a tempo. In some cases, Bxc5 is an option for White, too. Our reply prevents this idea. }
10... Ne4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/8/2P2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@ This move is relatively rare but strong. It is suggested by GM Dhopade in his 'Playing the Petroff' book and is a good solution, as it leads to very similar positions to  7.Be3  O-O  8.Qd2  Nd7  9.O-O-O  Nf6  . }
11. Qe1
{ This move is played most of the time, but Black has no problems at all against it. The alternative  11.Qd4  Nf6  ,  intending ...c5, also looks fine for Black. }
11... Re8
{ A strong move, placing the rook opposite to White's queen. We have ...Bf6 next, improving the scope of the rook and the bishop at the same time. }
12. Bd3 Bf6
{ Black has a comfortable position. Note that the move ...Nc5 is an option for Black to attack and possibly trade the strong bishop on d3. In the long run, pushing the queenside pawns is a good idea, too. }
*

