6... Be7
{ In this chapter, we will cover Black's approach to castle kingside in the Modern Main Line. Before the World Championship Match 2018, Caruana had frequently played the lines covered inChapter 9, involving ...O-O-O. In the actual Match in London, however, his choice was to castle kingside. This approach is now the main battleground of the Modern Mainline and therefore covered in this chapter. White's choice now is between  7.Bf4  and the more popular move  7.Be3  . Black needs to be aware that the difference between these moves is quite substantial. Black is in fine shape, but you don't have a universal plan for both lines. We'll also have a quick look at White's rare alternatives on move 7, but these pose no particular problems. }
7. Be3
{ White mainline by a mile. The bishop move prepares queenside castling, just like  7.Bf4  does. The square e3 seems to be the slightly better spot, as the maneuver ...Nd7-c5 is unattractive for Black. Against 7. Bf4, this idea works well. }
7... O-O
{ Almost a 'premove' in this chapter. Now White's clear mainline is the natural  8.Qd2  . }
8. Qd2
{ White prepares queenside castling immediately, a very natural choice. } 8...
Nd7
{ We would like to transfer our knight to f6, where it serves multiple purposes. It helps to defend the kingside but also eyes the squares e4 and d5. Now White castles queenside in the overwhelming majority of games. }
9. O-O-O
{ If Black decides to castle kingside in the Modern Mainline, this position is very likely to appear on the board. White's deviations are not particularly challenging, as we have already examined in this chapter. }
9... Nf6
{ Black has two main setups to choose from: Playing for ...c6 and ...d5 or aiming for the more aggressive setup with ...c5 and ...d5, which needs to be prepared with 9... Nf6. The first plan seems viable, but Fabiano Caruana successfully employed the more ambitious approach in the World Championship Match in London 2018. After this important game 9... Nf6 quickly gained popularity and is now established as Black's main way to fight the Modern Main Line.   The most important and popular reply to  9...Nf6  is  10.Bd3  ,  which we focus on in the Quickstarter. Black's play is very similar against all of them: we play ...c5 and start play on the queenside quickly. Ideas including ...Be6, ...Qa5 and ...b5 as a pawn sacrifice come to mind. }
10. Bd3
{ By far the most popular move. After our natural reply  10.Bd3  c5  White has a wide choice, with the moves.  11.Kb1  and  11.Rhe1  being the main lines.   White may also start with moves like  10.Kb1  or  10.Rhe1  , and after  10...c5  go for  11.Bd3  to transpose to our chosen move order 10. Bd3. }
10... c5
{ We play this move, pretty much regardless of White's 10th move. Now White has tried many moves. In most cases, we'll continue developing with ...Be6, but there are some cases where the pawn sacrifice ...b5! should be played. We should take this opportunity against  11.Kb1  and  11.c4  ,  while against other moves, I recommend developing the bishop first. The bishop development does not work well against 11. Kb1 or 11. c4, as 12. Ng5 is annoying. We can't capture on a2, compared to other moves. This is a good way to remember the difference between the two scenarios: develop the bishop if it attacks a2, while against 11. Kb1 and 11. c4 we switch to the aggressive ...b5! pawn sacrifice. }
11. Kb1 { A prophylactic approach by White, covering the a2-pawn. } 11... b5
{ It's essential to remember this move! After 11. Kb1 White has covered the a2-pawn, so  11...Be6?!  is less precise due to  12.Ng5!  ,  when we can't capture on a2. After our move  12...b5!  White usually doesn't dare to take the b-pawn, as Black gets excellent play for the small material investment. White's most challenging approach is based on a kingside attack, with ideas like Bg5, followed by Qf4-h4. Black is fine in all lines, but it can get very tactical. }
12. Rhe1
{ White's main try in this position. You also meet  12.Bg5  , which after  12...Be6  13.Rhe1  Rb8  transposes to the lines we are about to examine.   It's bad for White to play  12.Bxb5?  , as  12...Be6!  13.Rhe1  Rb8  gives Black excellent play. }
12... Rb8 { The correct move order.  12...Be6?!  13.Ng5  should be avoided. }
13. Bg5
{ White's most dangerous and demanding try. The following lines are deep and quite tactical. }
13... Be6
{ It is crucial to avoid  13...c4?  14.Nd4!  Bd7  15.Nf5  Bxf5  16.Bxf5  , when White is much better. }
14. Qf4
{ White goes for the Qf4-h4 plan. The following lines are extremely tactical and worth learning, as it would be tricky to figure them out over the board. }
14... Qa5 { The most logical choice, going for a counter-attack. } 15. b3
{ GM Liviu-Dieter Nisipeanu played this move in his game against GM Daniel Fridman in Magdeburg 2019. He won a great game, but Black's defense can be improved, as we will see. In the full chapter, we'll also examine the fun alternative  15.Rxe6  , which leads to equal chances after a tactical melee. }
15... c4
{ Black has playable alternatives here. In the game Nisipeanu-Fridman  15...h6  was the choice of my former teammate. This move should lead to a draw after  16.Bxh6  , but Daniel later slipped and allowed an attractive finish for his opponent.   I suggest  15...c4  , as it looks much easier to handle and gives Black chances to play for a win, too. }
16. Bf5 cxb3 17. axb3
{ This is more challenging than  17.cxb3  , when  17...b4  18.Bxe6  fxe6  looks fine for Black. We immediately threaten ...Nd5 in this position. }
17... d5
{ The move  17...b4  also works and leads to equal chances.   After our choice, many possible lines are fine for Black. A common scenario is that White starts a sacrificial attack now, but it is only good enough for a draw. Here's a sample line:  18.Rxe6  fxe6  19.Re1!  Rb6  20.Rxe6  Qxc3  21.Qh4  Rxe6  22.Bxe6+  Kh8  23.Bf5  Nh5!  24.Bxh7  Ba3!  25.Bc1  Bxc1  26.Kxc1  Qa1+  27.Kd2  Kxh7  28.Qxh5+  and it will end in a draw. }
