11. Rhe1
{ White centralizes the rook on the open e-file. This natural move is the most popular and was chosen by Magnus Carlsen in the mentioned World Championship game against Fabiano Caruana. }
11... Be6 12. Kb1
{ White covers the a2-pawn with the king. This move is the most popular and was played by Magnus Carlsen in the London match against Fabiano Caruana. White may also react with  12.a3  , but  12...c4!  gives Black good counter chances. The full chapter shows the details. }
12... Qa5
{ A natural reply. Here  12...b5?!  is wrong due to  13.Ng5  .   After the better move  12...Qa5  White has a fundamental choice between the solid  13.c4  , leading to a queen trade, and the sharper  13.a3  .  Carlsen played 13. c4 in the World Championship match, but it seems that 13. a3 is the more critical and certainly more exciting choice. }
13. c4
{ The conservative choice. White forces the queen trade and tries to claim a slight edge due to the more active pieces and the d6-pawn. A closer look reveals that Black is okay and should equalize comfortably, as in the Carlsen-Caruana encounter. White's alternative is  13.a3  , which we examine in the full chapter. After  13...c4  14.Be2  Ne4  15.Qc1  d5  16.Bd4  b5  Black gets equal chances after interesting complications. }
13... Qxd2 14. Bxd2
{ White intends Ng5 with this move, which we need to attend to. } 14... Rfe8
{ Caruana played  14...h6  against Carlsen, which is fine, too. I still suggest  14...Rfe8  , as  15.Ng5  is not a threat after we have covered the e7-bishop. We can simply reply  15...Bd7  .  A closer look shows that moving the e6-bishop to c6 via d7 is a very reasonable setup, so we don't mind being provoked by Ng5. In general, Black can be happy here. There is more than one way to obtain equal chances. }
