[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Bc4
{ Playing in gambit style. White does not try to regain the pawn immediately. }
3... Nf6
{ Not the only move, but it makes sense to play it as this position needs to be part of our repertoire anyway. Why ? Because after 1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6  (the only move consistent with a Petroff)  3. d4 we need to take on d4, which transposes to the position at hand. 3... Nf6 is also the best move, so 'merging' those two lines is very logical. }
4. e5 { This is met with a standard counter-blow. } 4... d5
{ Black is already better. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Bc4
{ Playing in gambit style. White does not try to regain the pawn immediately. }
3... Nf6
{ Not the only move, but it makes sense to play it as this position needs to be part of our repertoire anyway. Why ? Because after 1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6  (the only move consistent with a Petroff)  3. d4 we need to take on d4, which transposes to the position at hand. 3... Nf6 is also the best move, so 'merging' those two lines is very logical. }
4. Nf3 { Going for quick development. Plus, it's the only consistent move. }
4... Nxe4
{ Whenever you can grab e4 without being immediately punished... take it! Well, I am really fond of this general principle, but you need to consider carefully when it loses time in the opening. This pawn grab gives White very good development, but I believe it is not more than enough compensation. I have checked some other lines as well.  4...Nc6  transposes to a different opening after 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4. Black is fine here as well, but all of this is quite a sizeable amount of lines to learn for something you will face very rarely.   4...Bb4+  is a good alternative though... at the end I decided on the pawn grab because it is the most principled move. }
5. Qxd4 Nf6 6. Bg5
{ This is also frequently played but it just transposes to 6. Nc3 after the following very natural sequence. }
6... Be7 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Qh4 d6 { And we reach the line starting with 6. Nc3. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Bc4
{ Playing in gambit style. White does not try to regain the pawn immediately. }
3... Nf6
{ Not the only move, but it makes sense to play it as this position needs to be part of our repertoire anyway. Why ? Because after 1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6  (the only move consistent with a Petroff)  3. d4 we need to take on d4, which transposes to the position at hand. 3... Nf6 is also the best move, so 'merging' those two lines is very logical. }
4. Nf3 { Going for quick development. Plus, it's the only consistent move. }
4... Nxe4
{ Whenever you can grab e4 without being immediately punished... take it! Well, I am really fond of this general principle, but you need to consider carefully when it loses time in the opening. This pawn grab gives White very good development, but I believe it is not more than enough compensation. I have checked some other lines as well.  4...Nc6  transposes to a different opening after 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d4 exd4. Black is fine here as well, but all of this is quite a sizeable amount of lines to learn for something you will face very rarely.   4...Bb4+  is a good alternative though... at the end I decided on the pawn grab because it is the most principled move. }
5. Qxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bg5 Nc6 8. Qh4 d6 9. O-O-O Be6
{ This is the key idea to remember. We need to trade this dangerous bishop or we will gain a bit of time if White avoids the trade. Note that Black has not castled and needs to keep all options open and decide according to White's next moves. }
10. Bd3
{ Avoiding the trade, but losing some time. I believe Black is better now with precise play as indicated by the engine. }
10... h6
{ This move 'threatens to threaten' the bishop on g5. If this bishop retreats Black has got a nice discovered attack on the queen with Nd5 or Ng4. }
11. Rhe1 a6
{ This is a very strong move that has multiple ideas behind it. The most obvious one is that Bb5 is not possible any more - a move that would be annoying after ...Qd7. The main point however is that Black now has a stunning idea that is tough to prevent. }
12. Kb1
{ I don't see anything better - neither does the engine. Now Black's great idea comes into play. }
12... Kd7
{ This is the cool idea ! Now the bishop on g5 is attacked for real ! } 13. Bd2
{ This is a mistake and instantly loses, showcasing why ...a6 is so important. }
13... g5 14. Qa4 b5
{ And the queen is in a deadly net. White loses material for no compensation. }
15. Bxb5 axb5 16. Qxb5 Ra5
{ The bishop on d2 blocks the d-file, making Ne5+ ineffective. } *

