1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. c3
{ The Danish gambit. It never enjoyed any popularity because it was worked out quite early on that Black equalizes effortlessly with  3...d5  . This is not the move I recommend though - Black actually has a move to play for an advantage even. }
3... Qe7
{ Yes, it looks ugly - but central pawns should be taken if the opportunity presents itself, and with this move it will now be difficult for White to hold on to e4. }
4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. Bd3 d5 { And again White is struggling to stay in the game. } 6.
e5 Nc6 7. Bb5 Nd7 8. Qxd5 Ncxe5
{ White now faces too many threats - Black's attack is extremely strong. } *

