[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Nf3
{ White is aiming for a Scotch after  3...Nc6  , but we won't allow that to happen as we have better options. }
3... Bc5
{ I also checked  3...Bb4+  , concluding that it is a viable alternative. However, I liked  3...Bc5  even more, so this is the move I suggest playing. A key point is that the simple capture on d4 is now not in any way a Scotch Game transposition, but actually quite comfortable for Black. }
4. Nxd4 { As it turns out this is very harmless. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 O-O
{ Black gets in a quick ...Re8 against the king on e1. White needs to be careful here. I only found one higher-level game with this position, so let's follow this game for some moves. There are alternatives along the way of course, but this line is too rare to analyze deeply. }
6. Bg5 Re8 7. Be2 Nc6 8. Nb3 Bb4 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 h6
{ A cautious move instead of grabbing on e4. Black will take on e4 after Bh4, so White needs to take and give up on the bishop pair. }
11. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ With a very comfortable position for Black in M.Illingworth-G.Kovacs, Budapest 2011. }
