[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Qxd4
{ This is usually called the 'Centre Game', a strange name if you ask me. The German name is even weirder: 'Mittelgambit', which translates to 'gambit in the middle'... well, it's not even a gambit, so why is it called gambit ? Anyway, Black has various good options against it. }
3... Nc6 4. Qa4
{ This is rarely seen, and for good reason. The queen is actually a bit offside on a4 and offers Black the option of c5 for the bishop. }
4... Bc5
{ This bishop is very nicely placed. It looks at the f2-pawn, thus making it more difficult for White to castle queenside, which is the usual procedure in this opening, and a point of moving the queen so early on. }
5. Nc3 d6 6. Bd2
{ White still tries to castle queenside, but it is just not working. } 6... Nf6
{ Now ...Ng4 is a serious idea. } 7. f3 O-O 8. O-O-O Ne5
{ Black threatens to play ...c6/...b5 to chase the queen. White is in huge trouble already. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ According to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them, against some we even are able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Qxd4
{ This is usually called the 'Centre Game', a strange name if you ask me. The german name is even wierder: 'Mittelgambit', which translates to 'gambit in the middle'... well, it's not even a gambit, so why is it called gambit ? Anyway, Black has various good options against it. }
3... Nc6 4. Qa4
{ This is rarely seen for good reason. The queen is actually a bit offside on a4 and gives Black a good development option for the bishop on c5. }
4... Bc5
{ This bishop is very nicely placed. It looks at the f2-pawn, thus making it more difficult for White to castle queenside, which is the usual procedure in this opening and a point of moving the queen so early on. }
5. Nf3 d6 6. Bg5 Ne7 { This avoids a pin and prepares an idea I like to show. }
7. c3 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 f5
{ Black is grabbing the initiative, gaining space on the ill-placed bishop. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Qxd4
{ This is usually called the 'Centre Game', a strange name if you ask me. The German name is even weirder: 'Mittelgambit', which translates to 'gambit in the middle'... well, it's not even a gambit, so why is it called gambit ? Anyway, Black has various good options against it. }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3
{ This is the best square for the queen. It makes ...d5 harder to play and covers c5, stopping ...Bc5. }
4... Nf6 5. Bd2
{ This move does not have much independent significance after our reply. } 5...
Bb4 6. a3
{ This is probably better than transposing to the main line with 6. Nc3, but it is still rather harmless. }
6... Bxd2+ 7. Nxd2 O-O 8. O-O-O d5
{ This is very principled as White has neglected to control this square. Black may also play 8... Re8, which is a more complicated option. }
9. Qg3 dxe4
{ This proves that Black has no problems at all. I don't see anything better at this point. }
10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Rxd8 Nxg3 12. Rxf8+ Kxf8 13. hxg3 Bf5
{ With a completely level game. } *

