[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Qxd4
{ This is usually called the 'Centre Game', a strange name if you ask me. The German name is even weirder: 'Mittelgambit', which translates to 'gambit in the middle'... well, it's not even a gambit, so why is it called gambit ? Anyway, Black has various good options against it. }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3
{ This is the best square for the queen. It makes ...d5 harder to play and covers c5, stopping ...Bc5. }
4... Nf6 5. e5
{ This somewhat naive move is objectively very bad for White, but in order to refute it we need to sacrifice a piece. If you want to learn all of the lines following the piece sacrifice to be 100% sure you get it right you will need to spend a lot of time on a line that might never happen. I'll just show you the most important lines and then I suggest you just go for it if the opportunity arises. The resulting positions are hellish for White to defend, in any case. OK, what is it all about ? Let's see the moves ! }
5... Ng4 6. Qe2 d6
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n5/4P3/6n1/4Q3/PPP2PPP/RNB1KBNR w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@ Here the simpler 6... d6 is strong, compared to the more complicated piece sac after  6.Qe4  Ngxe5  . }
7. exd6+ Be6 { And Black has an enormous attack for just a single pawn ! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #19"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Qxd4
{ This is usually called the 'Centre Game', a strange name if you ask me. The German name is even weirder: 'Mittelgambit', which translates to 'gambit in the middle'... well, it's not even a gambit, so why is it called gambit ? Anyway, Black has various good options against it. }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3
{ This is the best square for the queen. It makes ...d5 harder to play and covers c5, stopping ...Bc5. }
4... Nf6 5. e5
{ This somewhat naive move is objectively very bad for White, but in order to refute it we need to sacrifice a piece. If you want to learn all of the lines following the piece sacrifice to be 100% sure you get it right you will need to spend a lot of time on a line that might never happen. I'll just show you the most important lines and then I suggest you just go for it if the opportunity arises. The resulting positions are hellish for White to defend, in any case. OK, what is it all about ? Let's see the moves ! }
5... Ng4 6. Qe4 { The critical move that requires us to sac the piece. } 6...
Ngxe5
{ Going  6...d6  here is answered by  7.exd6+  Be6  8.Ba6!  , and although perhaps difficult to believe, this is not better for Black! Well, we can take on  e5  and will most likely win a miniature anyway! I first learned of that move from the classic Jan Gustafsson DVD. }
7. f4 d5 8. Qe2 Bg4 9. Nf3 Bc5 { Develop, develop, develop ! } 10. h3 Bxf3 11.
gxf3 O-O 12. fxe5 Nxe5
{ And Black has a winning attack. A natural move like ...Re8 will be very strong. }
*

