[Round "?"]
[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #27"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. d4 exd4
{ Played according to the principle that a central pawn should always be taken if it is possible. Now White actually has quite a wide choice of lines. As it turns out Black is fine against all of them. Indeed, against some we are even able to play for an advantage already. }
3. Qxd4
{ This is usually called the 'Centre Game', a strange name if you ask me. The German name is even weirder: 'Mittelgambit', which translates to 'gambit in the middle'... well, it's not even a gambit, so why is it called gambit ? Anyway, Black has various good options against it. }
3... Nc6 4. Qe3
{ This is the best square for the queen. It makes ...d5 harder to play and covers c5, stopping ...Bc5. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ The next few moves are almost forced. White quickly needs to castle queenside to leave the e-file, while Black plays the most logical moves as well. }
6. Bd2 O-O 7. O-O-O Re8
{ The pressure on e4 is mounting. Objectively speaking Black is already better here, but there are some quite murky lines ahead. It's just like that: if White wants to play some dubious, but aggressive, line there is little to stop him. You can't avoid the odd crazy game and have to be confident in the complications when they are better for you. }
8. Qg3
{ This is the most popular move, but recent games and analysis show that Black is in excellent shape in the coming tactical melee. }
8... Nxe4
{ I have always played the alternative capture with the rook, but this move seems to be even more convincing. }
9. Nxe4 Rxe4
{ We have snatched an extra pawn in the centre and should be clearly better if we avoid being checkmated in the next moves. Currently it appears White is in bad shape here. }
10. Bf4 Qf6
{ A strong, active move. The pawn on c7 is covered by tactical means. } 11.
Bxc7 d6 { And the bishop is trapped ! } *

