5. Nc3 Be6 6. Bb3
{ This has been played by Ivanchuk in a rapid game against Karjakin. Ivanchuk employs the King's Gambit very occasionally against top level opposition in faster time controls - the element of surprise is much more effective when you don't have much time to remember your prepared lines. That being said, Black is still in excellent shape here. }
6... Nf6
{ Karjakin played  6...Nd7  , which is also fine. The direct attack against  e4  seems more powerful, though. }
7. Nf3 Qh6
{ Important: this is better than going to h5, as it covers f4 and allows Nh5 if appropriate. }
8. d4 Be7
{ Now White has more than one move that he might try. We will play with ... Nh5,...Nbd7 and castle queenside in most cases. I don't want to drill any deeper. Black is a pawn up and White has inadequate compensation. }
