10. Bxe6 { White tries to break through in the centre with this sequence. }
10... fxe6 11. e5 dxe5
{ Here Ntirlis'  11...Nh5  and  11...a6  are alternatives worth checking. I didn't find more than unclear/equal play, though. }
12. dxe5 Nd5 13. c4 Nb4 14. Qe4 Kc8 15. Bxf4 Qh5
{ Ntirlis analyzes  15...Nc5  16.Bxh6  Nxe4  17.Bc1  Bc5  with equality. I agree with this assessment and suggest the queen move instead, to keep it more complicated. We will go with .. .Nc6, ...Be7 and ...Rf8 in most cases. I will conclude this line here as you need to stop somewhere ! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Early Gambits And Attacks"]
[Black "Early Gambits and Attacks: 1 e4 e5 2.f4 and 2.d4 #68"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit! Time to celebrate, and already on move two. Our opponent is giving us a pawn and we will be better instantly. Wait, is it all that easy?! In fact it is not, but it's no joke that we should strive for more than equality against this opening. Before going into move-by-move analysis we should talk a bit about the history and nature of this opening. It is amongst the oldest openings, the earliest analysis are from the 15th century. In fact the very first chess book by Lucena - yes, the guy of 'Lucena position' fame - has some information on the King's Gambit.   The idea of White's play is actually quite logical. Ideally, he would like to develop with Bc4, Nf3 and a later O-O. But wouldn't it be better if the f-file is open instead of being blocked by a pawn on f2? If you open the f-file then all is set to attack f7, the weakest spot in Black's camp. As you might have gathered, White is out for Black's king from move two. This all sounds appealing, so why isn't the King's Gambit regarded as good opening nowadays? Well, Vladimir Kramnik famously said: 'It loses a pawn and weakens White's king'. Not the most 'romantic' statement about the most romantic chess opening around.   The 21st century problem for gambits is the enormous progress that has been achieved in defence. The Silicon chess player is not afraid to take pawns and defend, if it works out, based on cold blooded calculation. Alright, what does all that mean for us? Nowadays there are in fact many good defences available against the King's Gambit. The main decision to make is how hard you want to try to punish White and how much time do you need to invest to learn these lines. You need to take into account that you won't get this opening frequently. If you get in on the board, it will be a prepared surprise or you might be up against a specialist, who has it on the board much more often than you do. Therefore learning extremely complicated lines feels a bit uneconomical. On the other hand you don't want to allow White to 'get away' with his cheeky opening choice too easily by playing something too 'soft'.   Alright, we should look at some moves now. Just one thing: If your opponent plays the King's Gambit you instantly know he means business. He's ready to hit hard, so we need to be ready to hit back harder. This means your opponent will very likely get the type of game he wanted, but at the same time he will often be just worse! Be mentally ready for this type of game - there won't be any subtle manoeuvring in this game! }
2... exf4
{ As Kramnik said: 'It loses a pawn'! Jokes aside, Black has two main defences against the gambit. Taking the pawn, as I suggest, and  2...d5  3.exd5  exf4  . This second line is fine for Black, as well, but I felt it was not as challenging as taking on f4. One thing I need to mention of course: this repertoire is modelled after Fabiano Caruana's games - so what does Fabiano play? Well, we don't know! He has not yet played against the King's Gambit in any of his games in the databases, which is somewhat surprising. Nowadays, because so many rapid and blitz games are in the public databases, you would expect at least the odd game, but there is just nothing. Alright, you need to trust my choices then ;-@@EndBracket@@ }
3. Bc4
{ This is usually called the 'Bishop's Gambit'. White's natural development scheme is Bc4 and Nf3, so unsurprisingly  3.Bc4  and  3.Nf3  are the main moves.   Against the bishop move we have some good options. The easiest is probably  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.Nc3  c6  , but I felt this is not enough in order to play for more than equality. Recent books on the King's Gambit recommend to give the check on h4, and I have to agree that this is an excellent choice. It is in fact not such a big hassle to learn and White has to fight hard for equality, that he maybe won't even get. }
3... Qh4+ 4. Kf1
{ White's idea is that Nf3 will be a tempo against the queen, which is supposed to be enough 'compensation' for the king being on f1. Concrete analysis, however, shows that White won't get a substantial lead in development, which puts the whole concept into question. }
4... d6
{ This is important. We combine the check on h4 with this modest looking move. The less modest idea is to play ...Be6, ...Nd7 and castle queenside. This accomplishes a lot. We actually make use of the queen moves @@StartBracket@@castling is prepared@@EndBracket@@ and ... Be6 is an important tempo gainer that protects f7 at the same time. As a rule of thumb we will play the mentioned moves next if we are allowed to do so. In case of Nf3 we need to move the queen. The main choice is between f6 and h6, keeping an eye on the f4 pawn. I recommend to play Qh6, because this still allows Ngf6 to be played. If you remember the setup with Be6/Nd7/O-O-O and h6 as the square for the queen you should be fine. Let's look at some specific lines. }
5. Nf3 { Very natural play, and the most popular move. } 5... Qh6
{ This is our standard square for the queen. It covers the pawn and we retain the possibility of playing Nf6-h5 in some cases. }
6. d4 Be6 7. Bxe6 { The capture is nothing to worry about, as usual. } 7...
fxe6 8. g3
{ Concrete play by White. Anything slow will just be met by ...Nd7 or ...Nc6, preparing queenside castling. White is still a pawn down with a bad king. }
8... e5
{ This is a fine move, played by one of the top polish players, Mateusz Bartel. }
9. dxe5
{ This happened in the aforementioned game V.Koziak-M.Bartel, played in 2011. Better is  9.Nc3  , but Black is fine against that with normal moves as well. }
9... Qh3+ 10. Kf2 dxe5 { And Black threatens ...Bc5+ and is already winning. }
*

