 don't want to allow White to 'get away' with his cheeky opening choice too easily by playing something too 'soft'.   Alright, we should look at some moves now. Just one thing: If your opponent plays the King's Gambit you instantly know he means business. He's ready to hit hard, so we need to be ready to hit back harder. This means your opponent will very likely get the type of game he wanted, but at the same time he will often be just worse! Be mentally ready for this type of game - there won't be any subtle manoeuvring in this game! }
2... exf4
{ As Kramnik said: 'It loses a pawn'! Jokes aside, Black has two main defences against the gambit. Taking the pawn, as I suggest, and  2...d5  3.exd5  exf4  . This second line is fine for Black, as well, but I felt it was not as challenging as taking on f4. One thing I need to mention of course: this repertoire is modelled after Fabiano Caruana's games - so what does Fabiano play? Well, we don't know! He has not yet played against the King's Gambit in any of his games in the databases, which is somewhat surprising. Nowadays, because so many rapid and blitz games are in the public databases, you would expect at least the odd game, but there is just nothing. Alright, you need to trust my choices then ;-@@EndBracket@@ }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ This is the Schallopp Defence, named after a German master player of the 19th century. It always enjoyed a good reputation, but never got to mainline status. However, in recent years this line has been covered in at least two books that I know of. The Schallopp was chosen by Nikolaos Ntirlis and Martin Lokander in their repertoire books for Black, indicating that it offers an excellent balance of easy to learn yet still ambitious enough to 'punish' White for going wild with the f-pawn on move two. When I looked at their analysis it was very tough for me not to suggest 3... Nf6 as well. My usual aim is to present lines that have not been covered too much before, but at this particular point I felt that 3... Nf6 is an almost ideal solution, in particular in the context of a Petroff based repertoire. It is solid and classical, but still challenging for White to play against. OK, with this intro out of the way... let's examine the move ! Well, it attacks e4 right away, so White's choices are limited. Critical must be 4. e5, after which we happily jump to h5! The knight is covering the booty on f4, but also may return later via g7. It is important to see that 4. e5, advancing the pawn, presents a target to our pieces and the d-pawn. We will often go ...d6 to attack it quickly. }
4. e5 Nh5 5. Be2
{ This is supposed to be best, but White is struggling here as well. } 5... d6
6. O-O Nc6 7. d4 g6
{ In many lines with a closed centre we are able to play ...g5, but here it falls short due to  7...g5?  8.d5!  and after  8...Nxe5  9.Nxe5  dxe5  10.Bxh5  we lose the knight  ! }
8. Nc3 Bg7
{ The engines give Black only a slight edge, but quite obviously this opening was a failure for White. In his Kings' Gambit book, John Shaw continues with the following line. }
9. exd6 cxd6 10. d5 Ne5 11. Nd2
{ And now Shaw states that White will regain the pawn, but he cannot claim any advantage for White. This is a truly weird statement, because White is just in terrible shape, and quite obviously so. About any reasonable move is better for Black and it is tough to call which one is best. }
11... O-O
{ Ntirlis quotes the correspondence game M.Marchisotti-A.Lukasova that continued  11...Nf6  instead, which is also fine for Black. An unconventional way to assess this position is to compare it with lines in the Sicilian where black has played ...e5, for example in the Najdorf, and White replied f4, which got taken. Then White often later plays a knight to d5 which gets captured. The pawn structure in this sequence of events is identical to ours. Here Black has great piece placement and White is disorganized. One idea for White in these structures is to play c4-c5, often supported by b4. This is nowhere in sight here. So just dropping back to f6 is excellent, as well. I suggest castling, asking White: what's next ? }
12. Bxh5
{ What else ? Black is better after this, but I don't see any other sensible ideas. }
12... gxh5 13. Qxh5 Bg4 { traps the queen. } *

