{ White goes for a hybrid between the Vienna and the Bishop's Opening. Of course, this position also could have developed from 1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. Nc3. Usually, White's intention is to build up a setup with d3 and f4, quite similar to a declined King's Gambit.   This scenario could happen after, for example  3...Nc6  4.d3  Bc5  5.f4  d6  6.Nf3  ,  which is a direct transposition to the 2... Bc5 reply to the King's Gambit. This is not part of our repertoire and, frankly speaking, 2... Bc5 is just a worse move compared to taking. Well, back to the Vienna now. There are some options for Black, to avoid the mentioned transposition.   A popular and often recommended line is  3...Nc6  4.d3  Na5  ,  but my personal experience with this line is not very positive. Yes, you get the bishop pair, but White has really easy play. I tried this ...Na5 line multiple times against a team mate in blitz and had huge problems. Maybe it is just my inability to play the position, but I like to avoid it. In fact, Black has a relatively easy recipe to equalize completely and it nicely complies with the general rule that you should take the e4-pawn if possible. }
3... Nxe4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ We also use this motif in the line  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.Bc4  Nxe4  .  Here things are a bit different because White has the queen sortie to h5, which is the only interesting try. }
