[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game, an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is of course perfectly playable but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level, because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6 { The most natural move. Now White has quite a wide set of choices. }
3. Bc4
{ White goes for a hybrid between the Vienna and the Bishop's Opening. Of course, this position also could have developed from 1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. Nc3. Usually, White's intention is to build up a setup with d3 and f4, quite similar to a declined King's Gambit.   This scenario could happen after, for example  3...Nc6  4.d3  Bc5  5.f4  d6  6.Nf3  ,  which is a direct transposition to the 2... Bc5 reply to the King's Gambit. This is not part of our repertoire and, frankly speaking, 2... Bc5 is just a worse move compared to taking. Well, back to the Vienna now. There are some options for Black, to avoid the mentioned transposition.   A popular and often recommended line is  3...Nc6  4.d3  Na5  ,  but my personal experience with this line is not very positive. Yes, you get the bishop pair, but White has really easy play. I tried this ...Na5 line multiple times against a team mate in blitz and had huge problems. Maybe it is just my inability to play the position, but I like to avoid it. In fact, Black has a relatively easy recipe to equalize completely and it nicely complies with the general rule that you should take the e4-pawn if possible. }
3... Nxe4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ We also use this motif in the line  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.Bc4  Nxe4  .  Here things are a bit different because White has the queen sortie to h5, which is the only interesting try. }
4. Qh5 Nd6
{ Only move. Now White actually has a choice between retreating the bishop to b3, or the more obvious capture on e5. }
5. Qxe5+
{ White agrees to enter a queenless middlegame that poses no problems for Black. The resulting positions are symmetrical, but there are some imbalances due to the very different piece placements. If you would like to study a model game for this line: check the game A.Rosselli-Rubinstein, Baden-Baden 1925. I actually knew the middle-/ endgame of that game for a long time @@StartBracket@@it is featured in several books@@EndBracket@@ and never knew it arose from this opening line. Looking at the position around move 20 I always assumed it started as a French Exchange, but now I know better. }
5... Qe7 6. Qxe7+ Bxe7 7. Bb3 Nf5
{ This is the best move order. The knight immediately frees up the d-pawn and eyes the d4-square. }
8. Nf3 c6
{ Going for ...c6 and ...d5 is the most natural setup, trying to play against White's b3-bishop and c3-knight. }
9. d4 d5 10. O-O f6
{ This is an idea to remember. Black's king will be fine on f7 and the f6-pawn might prepare a later expansion on the kingside. }
