[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game, an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is of course perfectly playable but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level, because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6 { The most natural move. Now White has quite a wide set of choices. }
3. g3
{ An old favorite of Boris Spassky's. As usual I recommend playing ...d5, if allowed. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ White now needs to decide where to place the knight on g1. The most challenging option is to place it on f3, putting more pressure on Black's centre. Note that these positions often arise from a different, and actually more common, move order.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ There is the so-called 'Glek System' in the Four Knights after  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.g3  , which we answer with  4...d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  .   If White plays  7.Nf3  now we will get exactly this position. }
7. Ne2
{ By avoiding Nf3 White tries to keep the diagonal open for the bishop. Unfortunately for White, this falls short to our strong reply. }
7... Be6 8. O-O Bd5
{ Black is already slightly better in this position. White's star piece gets traded and Black enjoys a space advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game, an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is of course perfectly playable but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level, because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6 { The most natural move. Now White has quite a wide set of choices. }
3. g3
{ An old favorite of Boris Spassky's. As usual I recommend playing ...d5, if allowed. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Nc6
{ White now needs to decide where to place the knight on g1. The most challenging option is to place it on f3, putting more pressure on Black's centre. Note that these positions often arise from a different, and actually more common, move order.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ There is the so-called 'Glek System' in the Four Knights after  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.g3  , which we answer with  4...d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  .   If White plays  7.Nf3  now we will get exactly this position. }
7. Nf3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This position is most frequently seen from the move order  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.Nc3  Nc6  4.g3  d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  6.Bg2  Nxc3  7.bxc3  , the 'Glek System. }
7... Bc5
{ I have to admit that I never studied this system for Black and always played  7...Bd6  ,  in this position. Protecting the pawn on e5 somehow felt right, but this is actually quite passive compared to the development to c5. The Bc5 setup has been recommended in recent books by Ntirlis and Lokander and their argument in favour of Bc5 looks convincing to me. }
8. O-O O-O
{ Starting from here White has some moves that all fit into the scheme of development, but may be played in various move orders. Most of the time White will play d3, Re1 or Qe2 to attack e5. There are also ideas with an early Rb1 to utilize the half-open b-file. Some rules of thumb for Black you need to know: we will cover e5 with Qf6 if White attacks it with Re1, thus making Nd2 impossible due to the pressure on f2. If White attacks e5 with Qe2, Re8 is the better reply. If White plays a slow move we will go ...Bb6 as a useful waiting move. It makes any Rb1 less effective and the bishop is stable on b6. Once the bishop is on b6 White sometimes tries the move a4, intending to play a5 to distract a defender from the e5-pawn. This is an important motif worth noting - a4 usually means we need to lend extra protection to e5. We often delay the development of the c8-bishop for a moment to be flexible with this piece. Move orders might seem confusing here, but don't worry too much. If you get it slightly wrong, you won't be in severe trouble. Black's position is fundamentally sound and sensible moves should give you a fine position, even if you don't remember or find all of the optimal moves. }
9. d3
{ This move will often transpose to  9.Re1  or  9.Qe2  ,  but White sometimes tries to keep the rook on f1 for the time being. }
9... Bb6
{ If there is nothing pressing to do, like defending e5, we will play this useful waiting move. }
10. Re1 Qf6
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2n5/2b1p3/8/2P2NP1/P1PP1PBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 6 9@@EndFEN@@ This transposes to  9.Re1  Qf6  10.d3  . }
*

