11. Be3
{ Our bishop is strong on b6, so trading it makes some sense. In this way White also prepares finally to move the f3-knight in order to play it to e4 or c4. }
11... Bg4 { 'No knight move for you !' } 12. h3 Bh5 13. g4 Bg6 14. Nd2
{ White finally managed to move the knight, trying to improve it to e4 or c4. There is a drawback though. }
14... Qh4
{ Shakh Mamedyarov reached this position twice, against Daniel Fridman and Dimitry Jakovenko. In both games Black held his own nicely with a quick ...f5 push to get active play on the kingside. }
