[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #22"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game, an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is of course perfectly playable but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level, because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6 { The most natural move. Now White has quite a wide set of choices. }
3. a3
{ Hmm, what is that about? There is a trick involved. If Black now plays  3...d5  4.exd5  Nxd5  5.Qh5  this is interesting for White. This is important to remember, because my general approach is to play ...d5 whenever possible, but here it is not the best solution. We easily sidestep this idea by just developing and only later playing ...d5. }
3... Nc6 { Now White has nothing better than 4. Nf3. } 4. Nf3 d5
{ And we transpose to the Four Knights with 4. a3 d5, which is comfortable for Black. }
