[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #23"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game, an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is of course perfectly playable but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level, because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6 { The most natural move. Now White has quite a wide set of choices. }
3. f4
{ The most aggressive option, but Black quite easily defuses all attacking attempts. It needs to be mentioned that this line is still quite popular at the club/amateur level, so it makes a lot of sense to study it a bit. }
3... d5
{ It is an exaggeration to say that this is the only move you need to know against 3. f4, but there is some truth to it.   You absolutely need to avoid  3...exf4?  , as  4.e5  forces the sad retreat to g8. Our usual recipe is to play ...d5 whenever possible anyway, no exception here. }
4. exd5
{ A rare line that leads to somewhat strange positions. It's useful to know the best line against it, to save time on the clock. Figuring it out over the board might prove tricky. }
4... Nxd5 5. fxe5 { Just grabbing the pawn ! } 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 Qh4+
{ White allows this annoying check. What now ? } 7. Ke2
{ Forced, as  7.g3  Qe4+  loses the rook. If White chooses 4. exd5 he usually aims for this position and hopes that Black does not know it and burns time figuring out whether White blundered into it or not. You might search for a long time over the board trying to find a refutation and ultimately failing. Black can't refute this play, but we will be very comfortable. }
7... Bg4+ 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Qe1 Qh5
{ This is the most important move to remember. Keeping queens on is better than regaining the pawn by taking on e1 and f3. }
10. Kd1 { It's funny how king and queen switched places. } 10... Bxf3+ 11. gxf3
O-O-O
{ Black has good play here as the white king will never find an entirely save place. }
12. Qe4 Qxe5 13. d4 Qa5
{ Black was fine in H.Nakamura-S.Milliet Cap d'Agde 2010 @@StartBracket@@rapid@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #24"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game, an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is of course perfectly playable but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level, because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6 { The most natural move. Now White has quite a wide set of choices. }
3. f4
{ The most aggressive option, but Black quite easily defuses all attacking attempts. It needs to be mentioned that this line is still quite popular at the club/amateur level, so it makes a lot of sense to study it a bit. }
3... d5
{ It is an exaggeration to say that this is the only move you need to know against 3. f4, but there is some truth to it.   You absolutely need to avoid  3...exf4?  , as  4.e5  forces the sad retreat to g8. Our usual recipe is to play ...d5 whenever possible anyway, no exception here. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. d3 { This is a bad move, but it sets a trap. } 5... Nxc3
{ You need to avoid the tempting  5...Qh4+  6.g3  Nxg3  7.Nf3  Qh5  8.Nxd5  and Black is in trouble. }
6. bxc3 d4
{ This is the reason why 5. d3 is dubious. Black isolates the e5-pawn and gains space. On a more concrete level: it is actually difficult for White now to keep the pawn count level. Taking on d4 does not work and Black will just take on c3 next, in most cases. }
7. Nf3 Nc6 8. cxd4 Bb4+
{ A key move to remember. This is much better than immediately taking on d4, as after  8...Nxd4  9.c3  Nxf3+  10.Qxf3  is possible. }
9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Nxd4 11. c3 Nxf3+ 12. gxf3
{ The point: the queen can't recapture now and white's position feels very loose. Black is better here and has many possible moves. }
12... O-O
{ Simplest, but the more active  12...f6  is also attractive. In any case, Black is fine. }
