{ It is an exaggeration to say that this is the only move you need to know against 3. f4, but there is some truth to it.   You absolutely need to avoid  3...exf4?  , as  4.e5  forces the sad retreat to g8. Our usual recipe is to play ...d5 whenever possible anyway, no exception here. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3
{ The most popular and best move. Black has more than one respectable answer to it, with  5...Be7  and  5...Bc5  being most popular. }
5... Bc5
{ I learned the basics of this move from the Gustafsson DVD years ago. I don't own it anymore, so I am actually not sure of the precise lines recommended on that DVD, but I remember the key points. I checked the current state of theory and Black is in good shape, so I decided to go for it. I need to mention that I found one game played by Caruana in which he chose  5...Nc6  . This is a tricky move for White to face, as there is only one good reply,  6.Bb5  .  Unfortunately, for Black, this happens to be quite OK for White and in comparison I believe that 5... Bc5 gives Black more chances to play for an advantage. }
6. d4 Bb4 7. Bd2 c5
{ Black immediately puts pressure on White's centre. I think White has a hard time here avoiding trouble. }
8. Nxe4 { Trying to resolve the central tension directly, but it fails. } 8...
dxe4 9. Bxb4 cxb4 10. Ng1 { Ouch ! } 10... O-O
{ Black is better here, and not just a little bit. Just develop quickly and enjoy the hunting the white king ! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #32"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nc3
{ The Vienna Game, an opening that is quite unpopular at the professional level. It is of course perfectly playable but it does not pose too many serious problems for Black. We need to be aware that it is still frequently played at the club level, because there are some traps that Black might fall into. If you know how to avoid them you should get a good game. }
2... Nf6 { The most natural move. Now White has quite a wide set of choices. }
3. f4
{ The most aggressive option, but Black quite easily defuses all attacking attempts. It needs to be mentioned that this line is still quite popular at the club/amateur level, so it makes a lot of sense to study it a bit. }
3... d5
{ It is an exaggeration to say that this is the only move you need to know against 3. f4, but there is some truth to it.   You absolutely need to avoid  3...exf4?  , as  4.e5  forces the sad retreat to g8. Our usual recipe is to play ...d5 whenever possible anyway, no exception here. }
4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. Nf3
{ The most popular and best move. Black has more than one respectable answer to it, with  5...Be7  and  5...Bc5  being most popular. }
5... Bc5
{ I learned the basics of this move from the Gustafsson DVD years ago. I don't own it anymore, so I am actually not sure of the precise lines recommended on that DVD, but I remember the key points. I checked the current state of theory and Black is in good shape, so I decided to go for it. I need to mention that I found one game played by Caruana in which he chose  5...Nc6  . This is a tricky move for White to face, as there is only one good reply,  6.Bb5  .  Unfortunately, for Black, this happens to be quite OK for White and in comparison I believe that 5... Bc5 gives Black more chances to play for an advantage. }
6. d4 Bb4 7. Bd2 c5
{ Black immediately puts pressure on White's centre. I think White has a hard time here avoiding trouble. }
8. a3 { Probably best at this point. } 8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Nc6 10. Bd3 Bg4
{ And again I'd rather be Black here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #33"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Qh5
{ White is going for Scholar's mate. Not the best possible line for White, but it is not going to be completely terrible for him either. With White you can afford some liberties without ending up seriously worse. So don't feel provoked too much, just play normal moves and you'll be fine. }
2... Nc6 3. Bc4 g6
{ No checkmate, please ! The move ...g6 slightly weakens the kingside, but it is no problem at all. We just need to switch to a fianchetto setup to make use of the move and patch up the dark squares this way. }
4. Qf3 Nf6 5. Ne2 Bg7 6. d3 d6
{ Black is fine in this position. One future idea is to try to trade the bishop on c4 by means of ...Na5 or ...Be6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #34"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Ne2
{ I have played 1... e5 on a regular basis against 1. e4 for quite some time now, and I don't think this move has ever been played against me in any at least somewhat serious game. I was surprised to see that it has one idea that is useful to know, in particular for a Petroff player.   If you have the Petroff in mind you probably think of  2...Nf6  first, but after  3.d4  Nxe4  4.f3  this is actually just about equal. With the best move Black has chances to fight for an advantage against careless play. }
2... Bc5
{ We should avoid  2...Nc6  3.d4  exd4  4.Nxd4  ,  transposing to a Scotch. White shouldn't get a mainstream opening position anymore after 2. Ne2, we need to 'punish' this move as much as possible. }
3. c3 d5 { There is no Nc3 for White, so this is promising for Black. } *

