[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #37"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. a3 { Odd, but there is a trap involved. } 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6
{ This position we examine via 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. a3 Nc6.   Black is fine, he just needs to avoid  3...d5  4.exd5  Nxd5  5.Qh5  with tricky complications. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #38"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. c4
{ The pawn structure with c4 and e4 enjoys a good reputation when reached out of many lines of the English Opening. Going for it in this move order, however, is dubious. }
2... Nc6 3. Nc3 Bc5
{ This is the problem. Black has excellent control over d4, and this bishop is very strong. }
4. g3 d6 5. Bg2 f5
{ This is all you need to know. Pushing the f-pawn is strong, going for play along the f-file after castling kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
