[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #40"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This is the Bishop's Opening. White starts with this natural bishop development before committing to play the knight to f3, keeping options open. Nowadays this opening line is viewed as the only serious option for White if he wants to avoid the Petroff completely, and it is easy to understand why. After 1. e4 e5 there is just nothing else that at least poses some challenges. The gambits are all defanged, so what else is there besides 2. Bc4? In any case, our reply is quite obvious. }
2... Nf6 3. Nc3 Nxe4
{ And we transpose to the line 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bc4 Nxe4 - please refer to this move order for details. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Bishop's Opening, Vienna"]
[Black "Bishop's Opening, Vienna: 1 e4 e5 2.Bc4/Nc3/rare lines #41"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This is the Bishop's Opening. White starts with this natural bishop development before committing to play the knight to f3, keeping options open. Nowadays this opening line is viewed as the only serious option for White if he wants to avoid the Petroff completely, and it is easy to understand why. After 1. e4 e5 there is just nothing else that at least poses some challenges. The gambits are all defanged, so what else is there besides 2. Bc4? In any case, our reply is quite obvious. }
2... Nf6 3. Qe2
{ White uses the queen to protect e4, and placing it opposite Black's king makes it difficult to play ...c6 and ...d5 straightaway. We need to develop and castle first. }
3... Bc5
{ Please note that this is not an Italian Game. The knight not being on c6 is a serious accomplishment for Black, still having the option to play ...c6 soon. }
4. Nf3 O-O
{ There is no need to cover the pawn of course. We'd like to play ...d5 in one go, if possible. }
5. Nxe5 { This is suicidal and was never tried, but let's have a quick look. }
5... d5 6. exd5 Re8 7. d6 { The only interesting try. } 7... Bxf2+ 8. Kxf2 Rxe5
9. Qxe5 Ng4+ { A good day at the office. } *

