1. e4 e5 2. Bc4
{ This is the Bishop's Opening. White starts with this natural bishop development before committing to play the knight to f3, keeping options open. Nowadays this opening line is viewed as the only serious option for White if he wants to avoid the Petroff completely, and it is easy to understand why. After 1. e4 e5 there is just nothing else that at least poses some challenges. The gambits are all defanged, so what else is there besides 2. Bc4? In any case, our reply is quite obvious. }
2... Nf6 3. d3
{ This is the most solid and best move. Now Black has an important choice to make. With moves like  3...Bc5  or  3...Nc6  , usually followed by  4.Nf3  Bc5  you may transpose to an Italian game/Giuoco Piano or avoid this altogether and go 3... c6. I recommend playing 3... c6, which is also Caruana's usual choice. I also need to mention that the Italian game has seen a revival in recent years and it is actually quite an effort for Black to learn to play against it. Our choice is much simpler to master. }
3... c6
{ Black prepares ...d5, gaining a tempo on the bishop. I need to mention an important idea that we will frequently see in this line. Black commonly checks with Bb4+, provoking c3, or initiates trades if White replies with Bd2. It is important to understand that c3 is a useful post for White's knight to increase pressure on d5, so a pawn on c3 is more of a handicap, for White, than an asset. }
4. Nf3 d5
{ If you like a low maintenance alternative, I suggest  4...Be7  ,  setting up with ...d6 later. This is very similar to a Closed Philidor formation where White has played rather timidly with an early d3. This line is better suited to keep it complicated and avoid trades. }
5. Bb3
{ This is by far the most popular move, keeping the tension in the centre. }
5... Bb4+
{ I mentioned this standard procedure before. Black argues that c3 is not useful and Bd2 or Nbd2 are too meek to pose any problems. }
