[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Petroff Sidelines and Four Knights"]
[Black "Petroff Sidelines and rare Four Knights #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d3
{ Not exactly the refutation of the Petroff, but there is none available anyway. White just covers e4 and will either play a King's Indian attack formation with g3 or a reversed Philidor with Be2, Nbd2, c3 etc. Black won't have any problems equalizing here as the overall approach by White is just too slow. However, it will be a game with a full board and no deep theoretical lines and possible simplifications. }
3... Nc6
{ That is the most natural and logical move. I also like Sakaev's suggestion of  3...d6  ,  followed by 4... g6. It is a good alternative, but in this repertoire I suggest playing for ...d5 whenever possible, so there is little reason to proceed otherwise here. }
4. Be2 { The reversed Philidor approach. } 4... d5
{ One rule of thumb of the open games is: if Black manages to play ...d5, without being immediately punished, he has at least equalized. }
5. exd5
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This has become a bit more popular, very likely because  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  4.Nf3  exd4  5.Nxd4  Be7  is not a bad line for Black and an extra tempo makes a difference in some variations. In particular  6.g3  d5!?  is quite tactical, but better for White. }
5... Nxd5 6. O-O Bd6
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ White's best option against the Philidor line  1.e4  d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  4.Nf3  exd4  is related to playing g3. Please see my Keep it Simple 1. e4 repertoire for details, if you are interested.   Now, being a tempo down, this is not great. Here  6...g6  7.d4  is fine for White.   Instead  6...Bd6  is a sensible move to prepare castling and cover e5. I think it is equal already, if you continue with common sense play. }
7. Re1 O-O 8. h3 Bf5
{ Black is certainly at least equal here. You may continue with ...Qd7 and centralize rooks, next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Petroff Sidelines and Four Knights"]
[Black "Petroff Sidelines and rare Four Knights #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d3
{ Not exactly the refutation of the Petroff, but there is none available anyway. White just covers e4 and will either play a King's Indian attack formation with g3 or a reversed Philidor with Be2, Nbd2, c3 etc. Black won't have any problems equalizing here as the overall approach by White is just too slow. However, it will be a game with a full board and no deep theoretical lines and possible simplifications. }
3... Nc6
{ That is the most natural and logical move. I also like Sakaev's suggestion of  3...d6  ,  followed by 4... g6. It is a good alternative, but in this repertoire I suggest playing for ...d5 whenever possible, so there is little reason to proceed otherwise here. }
4. Be2 { The reversed Philidor approach. } 4... d5
{ One rule of thumb of the open games is: if Black manages to play ...d5, without being immediately punished, he has at least equalized. }
5. Nbd2 Bc5
{ Against the closed Philidor White goes for Bc4, so we happily go for this setup with reversed colors as well. It is tricky to analyze and learn the closed Philidor structures, because it is more of a setup than a concrete string of moves. They are not a frequent guest in our games, so I'll show you the main line and give you some general advice at the end of the line. }
6. O-O O-O 7. c3 a5
{ Always prevent b4! If they play c3 or a3, you just play ...a5 and stop the immediate b-pawn push. Some other rules of thumb are: don't trade on e4 unless you have clear motivation to do so. It makes little strategic sense to improve White's bishop on e2. We should also maintain the tension in the centre in general, making useful moves like ...Re8, ...h6, ...Ba7. Another attractive idea is to transfer the knight from f6, heading towards the f4-square. It makes a lot of sense to look at some complete games with this structure, it is tough to learn on a move-by-move basis. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Petroff Sidelines and Four Knights"]
[Black "Petroff Sidelines and rare Four Knights #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d3
{ Not exactly the refutation of the Petroff, but there is none available anyway. White just covers e4 and will either play a King's Indian attack formation with g3 or a reversed Philidor with Be2, Nbd2, c3 etc. Black won't have any problems equalizing here as the overall approach by White is just too slow. However, it will be a game with a full board and no deep theoretical lines and possible simplifications. }
3... Nc6
{ That is the most natural and logical move. I also like Sakaev's suggestion of  3...d6  ,  followed by 4... g6. It is a good alternative, but in this repertoire I suggest playing for ...d5 whenever possible, so there is little reason to proceed otherwise here. }
4. g3
{ White is going for a King's Indian attack formation, fianchettoing the bishop. }
4... d5 5. Nbd2
{ White keeps the tension in the centre. Unlike in the reversed Philidor, trading on e4 is a better option now as the bishop will be on g2 and removing the d3-pawn with the trade is less of a concession. }
5... dxe4 6. dxe4 Bc5 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O a5
{ Black will play ...b6 and ...Ba6 next, with a fine game. } *

