1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bc4
{ You still meet this move at the amateur/club level. Black has the choice to be better in a slightly murky position or just equalize without any problem at all. I have played the latter in some of my online blitz games before I learned how to punish White for his choice. You should definitely play the more ambitious line, that we will explore now. }
3... Nxe4
{ According to the general rule that you should take the central pawn when you can do so unpunished. Ever wondered why the Berlin defence to the Ruy is so popular? }
4. Nc3
{ White plays for development, making the pawn sac permanent if Black plays accordingly. }
4... Nxc3
{ I strongly suggest playing this way, trying to refute White's gambit. I am guilty of playing  4...Nc6  here, transposing into the line 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Bc4?! Nxe4. This line is fine for Black, of course, but it is equal if White plays well from this point on. The main reason I played like this was ignorance, but now I know that taking on c3 is good for Black. }
5. dxc3 f6
{ This is the key move, covering the important central pawn. Now the stakes are quite high, already. White needs to get something going, otherwise Black is just clearly better with extra material and central dominance. Objectively speaking Black is on top here, but it is still somewhat murky. }
6. O-O
{ White castles first, but after our simple reply there is still need for quick action. Note that now 7. Nxe5 is a real threat! }
6... Nc6
{ It is important to note that  6...c6??  is bad, because  7.Nxe5  is killing. }
7. Nh4
{ Similar to 6. Nh4, but there is no decent alternative. Against slow moves you can also develop slowly. A key idea is to play ...d6/...Qd7/...Nd8 and ultimately ...c6 and ...d5. White has little to show for his sacrifice. }
7... g6 8. f4 Qe7
{ The move  8...f5  is very strong, as well. Black is better, just as after my choice of  8...Qe7  . }
9. Kh1 d6 10. f5 Qg7 *

