{ This is White's best option if he does not want to enter a line exclusive to the Petroff. The main tries are  3.Nxe5  and  3.d4  ,  but you should be aware that 3. Nc3 will be played a lot against you, in particular at the amateur/club level. It is very important to have good answers prepared, just because of the likelihood of these lines appearing on the board. But there is an additional incentive to be well prepared. White players MIGHT know the Four Knights Game well, but this does not need to be case! Often they will play 3. Nc3 just because they have nothing prepared against the Petroff and they have 3. Nc3 only as an 'escape hatch' line, just against this Petroff move order. Against 2... Nc6 they'd play the Ruy Lopez or Italian, but only against the Petroff they'd enter the Four Knights, without any deep knowledge. As mentioned, that does not need to be the case, but you might meet people over the board that have no detailed knowledge - so we should be well prepared, trying to exploit this. }
3... Nc6
{ We transpose to the Four Knights game with this move. Objectively speaking, this is the best move and it should be played. Fabiano Caruana has never faced  3.Nc3  , so we don't exactly know for sure what he would play, but I'd be very surprised about a different move. It involves a bit of theory, but the alternatives are not convincing or somewhat against the spirit of the Petroff.  3...Bb4  is a way to save theoretical workload, but I think White is just slightly better after  4.Nxe5  ,  as I have analyzed in my Keep it Simple 1. e4 repertoire.   A choice worth considering is  3...d6  , angling to transpose into a Philidor after  4.d4  exd4  or  4...Nbd7  . Caruana has played the Philidor occasionally in Blitz/Rapid, with decent results. So this is worth looking at if you want to explore an additional option.   It would be weird to include some Philidor lines in this repertoire, so I decided to go for the main line with  3...Nc6  .  This is also a more universal choice: if you also play 2... Nc6, or intend to include this at a later stage, it is necessary to have something prepared against the Four Knights anyway. Now the theoretically most explored lines are Scotch Four Knights with  4.d4  , or the Spanish Four Knights starting with  4.Bb5  . These main lines are examined in the following chapter. We also need to check some sidelines that White has tried. Against almost all slow moves I recommend playing  4...d5  .  It is not a coincidence that 4. Bb5 and 4. d4 are the main lines... they stop ...d5! In some cases, 4... d5 will lead to lines where we are playing the Scotch Four Knights with colours reversed, and where White has made an extra move. This extra move helps White, but not to the extent that it changes the position much. This applies to 4. a3 d5, 4. h3 d5 and 5. Be2 d5. By the way: it is not necessary to know the Scotch Four Knights inside and out, from White's point of view, in order to play in this fashion with Black. Note that we have to play the Black side after 4. d4 as well, so the position types are familiar. }
4. Nxe5
{ The Halloween gambit. This is the type of opening that you immediately know to be incorrect @@StartBracket@@'It just can't work !'@@EndBracket@@, but proving it is actually not that easy. Let's have a look. }
4... Nxe5 5. d4 Nc6 6. d5 Ne5 7. f4 Ng6 8. e5 Bc5
{ Here  8...Ng8  is probably the best move in computer terms, but I want to suggest this alternative as it gives Black a nice attack. Turning the game around like this against an attacker is often a good idea. }
9. exf6 O-O 10. fxg7 { Very greedy play! } 10... Re8+ 11. Be2 d6 12. Qd3 Nh4
13. Qg3 Qf6
{ And again Black's attack is tough to defend against. Black already is clearly better, with Nh4-f5-d4 being a key idea. }
*

