{ A common theme in the open games. Black temporarily sacs the knight, getting it back with a ...d5 fork. I need to emphasize that Black does not get an advantage, as many older books tried to prove. However, it is somewhat likely that a player on the white side who plays into this line, not knowing that 4... Nxe4 is strong, will actually make mistakes later as well. This is also why White scores so badly after 4... Nxe4. Any further mistake will be costly. }
5. Nxe4 d5 6. Bd3 { The only move to keep the balance for White. } 6... dxe4 7.
Bxe4 Bd6
{ Black has equalized easily here. You could stop at this point, but there is one line I'd like to show. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Re1
{ White intends to take on c6 and win the e5 pawn next. This line looks very natural and might be seen frequently if White avoids the earlier pitfalls. }
9... Nb4
{ I really like this idea, threatening ...f5! It is still equal, but there are some interesting complications. In fact, you could analyze this position in a lot more depth, but this is not very economical for such a rare line, so I'll just give some sample lines. }
10. d4 f5 11. Bg5 Qe8 12. dxe5 fxe4 13. exd6 Qg6
{ And these complications should end in a draw. } *

