4... Bc5 5. O-O O-O
{ Caruana tried  5...d6  in an online Blitz game against MVL, but I believe that White is better after  6.d4  .   It's nothing special for White, but  5...O-O  is to be preferred here. We avoid a d2-d4 pawn push, this way, and are not afraid of the capture on c6. Now the pseudo sacrifice on e5 is the critical line, but White often tries slow moves that pose no problem at all. }
6. Bxc6
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This is a rather harmless choice here. White's capture on e5 is harmless on the next move, so the game will look a lot like an Anti-Berlin @@StartBracket@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Bxc6  dxc6  @@EndBracket@@  where White has castled early on and put a knight on c3 - two choices that are toothless. }
6... dxc6 7. d3
{ This slow move is a lot better than taking on e5. We enter a manoeuvering game where both sides have some flexibility. The most important regrouping you need to know for Black is to play c6-c5 later, and then reroute the knight to d4 via Nf6-d7-b8-c6 or Nf6-d7-f8-e6. }
7... Qe7
{ I suggest starting with this, but, for instance,  7...Re8  is fine as well. It makes sense to study some complete games with this pawn structure, as move-by-move analysis is not very useful in such a slow type of game. From a theoretical point of view this whole line is very innocuous, but the game often gets interesting later after a longer manoeuvering phase. }
