{ The Spanish Four Knights. Black's main lines always have been  4...Bb4  and  4...Nd4  , and those moves are indeed fine. However I am going to recommend a different move, namely  4...Bc5  . I believe this move is absolutely fine and the main lines have practical drawbacks.   I need to be absolutely clear here: Black is completely fine, but in particular  4...Nd4  seems like a tough choice in a practical game. White may play the extremely boring  5.Nxd4  , against which it is very tough to play for a win. Or White may challenge you in a main line. Then you need to know up to 25 moves of super sharp theory to ultimately make a draw with a perpetual. There are multiple lines like that to remember by the way - it is not just one. All this does not matter at the professional level: they are OK with a draw like that, usually.   The second option is  4...Bb4  , which I like better from a practical point of view. It is less tactical, so less effort required to learn it, compared to  4...Nd4  . However after considering some other options I remembered that I had recommended  4...Bc5  already back in 2012, when I released some Youtube videos on the subject. I checked my old analysis and was pleasantly surprised that Black is in even better shape nowadays, compared to some years ago. So why not go for this line? I need to mention that Caruana played  4...Nd4  , but also  4...Bc5  once in this line - so I guess we have an endorsement by the challenger, in this case. }
4... Bc5 5. O-O O-O
{ Caruana tried  5...d6  in an online Blitz game against MVL, but I believe that White is better after  6.d4  .   It's nothing special for White, but  5...O-O  is to be preferred here. We avoid a d2-d4 pawn push, this way, and are not afraid of the capture on c6. Now the pseudo sacrifice on e5 is the critical line, but White often tries slow moves that pose no problem at all. }
6. Nxe5
{ The pseudo-sacrifice must be the critical move, but Black holds his own nicely, at the moment. }
6... Nxe5 7. d4 Bd6 8. f4
{ This pawn phalanx is quite a sight, but concrete analysis shows that Black holds his own in a complicated struggle. }
8... Neg4
{ This is my preference here. Most of time, White tries to regain the piece immediately with  9.e5  , but there have been other attempts to delay this procedure. }
9. Be2 Bb4
{ A good solution, introducing the ...Bxc3/...Nxe4 sequence into the position. }
10. Bxg4 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Nxe4
{ In this roughly equal position I'd rather take Black. The pawn structure deficits in White's position are obvious and the knight on e4 is strong. }
