10. f5 { This seems to be the most dangerous move. } 10... d6 11. exf6 Nxf6 12.
Qf3
{ In the latest Chessbase Magazine GM E. Postny analyzes the line 4... Bc5 and concludes that it is a good alternative to the mainlines. However, he dislikes going into this position, and recommends that Black should deviate earlier. 9... Bb4, as played by Aronian, or 8... Nc6 are possible ways to do that, and Black is OK there. I am still sticking with my preference for 9... Be7, as the lines starting here are very interesting. If you really dislike the coming lines then I do mention good alternatives. }
12... d5
{ I suggest playing this instead of  12...c6  13.Bd3  d5  , when Postny suggests  14.g4!  for White, and concludes that this position is much easier for White to play. I agree - this indeed looks dangerous. The point of my move order is twofold: you may play a quick ...Bb4, trying to take the knight on c3 and get control over e4. The second point is to play ...c5 in one move if appropriate. }
13. Bd3 c5
{ Black gets good play in the centre. The engine also likes the slower  13...b6  ,  again trying to play for control of e4, later. }
14. dxc5 Bxc5+ 15. Kh1 b6
{ With ...Bb7, ...Re8 and ideally ...Ne4 to come. This looks fine to me. } *

