1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Bb5
{ The Spanish Four Knights. Black's main lines always have been  4...Bb4  and  4...Nd4  , and those moves are indeed fine. However I am going to recommend a different move, namely  4...Bc5  . I believe this move is absolutely fine and the main lines have practical drawbacks.   I need to be absolutely clear here: Black is completely fine, but in particular  4...Nd4  seems like a tough choice in a practical game. White may play the extremely boring  5.Nxd4  , against which it is very tough to play for a win. Or White may challenge you in a main line. Then you need to know up to 25 moves of super sharp theory to ultimately make a draw with a perpetual. There are multiple lines like that to remember by the way - it is not just one. All this does not matter at the professional level: they are OK with a draw like that, usually.   The second option is  4...Bb4  , which I like better from a practical point of view. It is less tactical, so less effort required to learn it, compared to  4...Nd4  . However after considering some other options I remembered that I had recommended  4...Bc5  already back in 2012, when I released some Youtube videos on the subject. I checked my old analysis and was pleasantly surprised that Black is in even better shape nowadays, compared to some years ago. So why not go for this line? I need to mention that Caruana played  4...Nd4  , but also  4...Bc5  once in this line - so I guess we have an endorsement by the challenger, in this case. }
4... Bc5 5. d3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ That looks quite conservative in this particular position, but the resultant position is actually frequently played, arising from a different move order. The main move order to reach it is:  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.Nc3  . White has tried just about everything against the Berlin, so it is not a huge surprise that this particular move order has been examined as well. }
5... O-O
{ Note that  5...d6  is answered with  6.Na4  .   Not the end of the world, but White gets the bishop without any real concession. It is more interesting to examine  5...Nd4  , but I don't fully trust it after  6.Nxe5  O-O  7.Bc4  d6  8.Nxf7  . Castling is the most popular move amongst the top players, so it's our choice, too. }
6. Bxc6 dxc6
{ White has tried various moves now, all starting a slow manoeuvering phase. As usual in these positions, Black's main goal is to improve the knight on f6, aiming it towards the d4-square. It is important to note that White has not castled yet and might play with ideas like h3/g4 to attack us. That means Black needs to avoid weakening the pawn cover in front of the king. A move like ...h6, for example, asks for a swift checkmating attack. It's difficult to analyze this position move-by-move, as both sides have various move orders and ideas. As mentioned more than once - the Bxc6/dxc6 structures are slow in nature and studying some complete games by strong players will be extremely helpful. }
7. h3
{ A flexible move, preventing ...Bg4 and at the same time preparing g4, if appropriate. }
7... Nd7 { Black immediately addresses the knight position. } 8. Be3 Bd6
{ A typical way to play this structure. White would be happy with the trade on e3, as the doubled pawn covers important squares like d4 and the f-file is opened. Instead, Black clears c5 for the pawn to allow a later Nb8-c6 regrouping. }
9. Ne2
{ This time we see Caruana on the white side of this structure. 9. Ne2 was played by him against Vishy Anand in London 2017. }
9... Re8 10. g4
{ This was the ambitious idea, but Black is very solidly placed. Caruana mentions in his annotations to the game that engines hate the whole concept, and I can confirm that statement - Stockfish thinks Black is just better. Caruana suggests turning the computer off for this line, which makes some sense - whatever the 'objective' evaluation might be, for human players it is just a very difficult position to play. }
10... Nc5 11. Ng3 Ne6 12. Nf5 c5 13. h4 a5 14. h5 a4
{ This is Caruana's suggestion to improve on Anand's  14...Ra6  , which was not terrible in the first place. However,  14...a4  gains more space on the queenside, the very likely home of the white king later on in the game. The whole situation is complicated and unclear, just as the actual game was. Ultimately Caruana won a nice game against the former World Champion. }
*

