4... Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 7 5@@EndFEN@@ This pawn structure may arise via various lines in our repertoire. However, by capturing this early on White commits a bit prematurely. For example, in the line  5.d3  O-O  6.Bxc6  dxc6  , Black has already castled short, so there are ideas of launching a kingside attack while keeping the white king in the centre or on the queenside. Here Black might wait with castling or pursue other options depending on White's choice on move  6. }
6. d3 Qe7
{ Of course,  6...O-O  is fine and simply transposes to the mentioned line starting with 5. d3 O-O 6. Bxc6 dxc6. But you might as well delay castling. Ideas like Nf6-d7-f8 -e6 are on the agenda, as usual. }
*

