[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Bb5
{ The Spanish Four Knights. Black's main lines always have been  4...Bb4  and  4...Nd4  , and those moves are indeed fine. However I am going to recommend a different move, namely  4...Bc5  . I believe this move is absolutely fine and the main lines have practical drawbacks.   I need to be absolutely clear here: Black is completely fine, but in particular  4...Nd4  seems like a tough choice in a practical game. White may play the extremely boring  5.Nxd4  , against which it is very tough to play for a win. Or White may challenge you in a main line. Then you need to know up to 25 moves of super sharp theory to ultimately make a draw with a perpetual. There are multiple lines like that to remember by the way - it is not just one. All this does not matter at the professional level: they are OK with a draw like that, usually.   The second option is  4...Bb4  , which I like better from a practical point of view. It is less tactical, so less effort required to learn it, compared to  4...Nd4  . However after considering some other options I remembered that I had recommended  4...Bc5  already back in 2012, when I released some Youtube videos on the subject. I checked my old analysis and was pleasantly surprised that Black is in even better shape nowadays, compared to some years ago. So why not go for this line? I need to mention that Caruana played  4...Nd4  , but also  4...Bc5  once in this line - so I guess we have an endorsement by the challenger, in this case. }
4... Bc5 5. Nxe5
{ This pseudo-sacrifice has traditionally been the argument against 4... Bc5, but the current state of theory suggests that Black has good chances to equalize, and not just with one continuation. Let's have a closer look. }
5... Nxe5 6. d4 Bd6
{ Not the only move, actually, even though it looks very natural. Here Black has the good alternative, namely  6...a6  , which has gained ground in recent years. The idea is to include the moves  6...a6  and  7.Be2  before retreating. When I analyzed the 4... Bc5 line for my Youtube repertoire in 2012 I suggested 6... Bd6, and I still see no problems with that move. }
7. f4 Nc6
{ with O-O inserted for both sides we play the knight to g4. In this particular version, however, going back to c6 is simpler to learn and play. }
8. e5 Bb4 9. exf6 Qxf6 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 d5 12. O-O Bf5 13. Rb1
{ This was played in the game R.Praggnanandhaa-I.Lysyj, Moscow 2018. } 13...
O-O-O 14. Bd3 Rhe8 15. a4 g6
{ The 2014 Russian Champion was already better against the Indian prodigy and went on to win this game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Scotch and Spanish Four Knights"]
[Black "Scotch and Spanish Four Knights: 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nf6 #47"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4
{ I have recommended 4. d4 in my Keep it Simple 1. e4 Repertoire for White, so it's my job now to play against my own recommendation. This is not such a big deal actually, as this line does not lead to an advantage for White anyway. Against a main line defence like 1... e5 White does not get an edge, but a line like the Scotch Four Knights is a good choice for White. It is easy to play and Black has many ways to go wrong. White is also very solid, with a sound development and no weaknesses. Sounds like a good advertisement for White? Well, if you look closely at Black's position you will come to the conclusion that those virtues apply equally for Black, as well. From a pawn structure point of view Black will be slightly worse on the queenside, but this is a minor concern. }
4... exd4
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@ The only other active move, 4... Bb4, is unsound. We have checked the lines starting with, for example,  4.a3  d5  5.Bb5  , concluding that White is playing with fire. We should avoid this and play the main line. }
5. Nd5 { The Belgrade Gambit. } 5... Nb4
{ When I started to play 1... e5 the usual book recommendation was to reply  5...Be7  , but nowadays it is well established that, after  5...Nb4  , White needs to fight for equality. }
6. Nxf6+ { This is easy to handle. } 6... Qxf6 7. Bc4 Bc5
{ White is just a pawn down for nothing. } *

