[White "4. Scotch and Spanish Four Knights"]
[Black "Scotch and Spanish Four Knights: 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nf6 #53"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4
{ I have recommended 4. d4 in my Keep it Simple 1. e4 Repertoire for White, so it's my job now to play against my own recommendation. This is not such a big deal actually, as this line does not lead to an advantage for White anyway. Against a main line defence like 1... e5 White does not get an edge, but a line like the Scotch Four Knights is a good choice for White. It is easy to play and Black has many ways to go wrong. White is also very solid, with a sound development and no weaknesses. Sounds like a good advertisement for White? Well, if you look closely at Black's position you will come to the conclusion that those virtues apply equally for Black, as well. From a pawn structure point of view Black will be slightly worse on the queenside, but this is a minor concern. }
4... exd4
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/4P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 5 4@@EndFEN@@ The only other active move, 4... Bb4, is unsound. We have checked the lines starting with, for example,  4.a3  d5  5.Bb5  , concluding that White is playing with fire. We should avoid this and play the main line. }
5. Nxd4 Bb4
{ This move enjoys the best reputation. Black develops quickly and by pinning the knight puts some pressure on the e4-pawn. Note that Black is already set to castle on the next move, and he currently has three pieces in play as opposed to White's two. This is not that relevant if White plays the well-established mainline that I recommend in my 'Keep it Simple 1. e4'-Repertoire, but any deviation that delays development or weakens the structure will prove costly. Usually, White knows what he is doing and you will reach the position on move 8 quickly, but at lower levels you might face one of the bad alternatives that give Black excellent chances. }
6. Bg5
{ White tries to reduce the pressure on e4 by counter-pinning. I always thought that this was just a bad move, but it turns out that it is not at all easy for Black to prove an advantage. I am suggest playing a natural continuation that does not try for an outright refutation. }
6... h6 7. Bh4 O-O
{ Here  7...g5  looks like the most principled way to play, but I couldn't prove an advantage for Black in this line. Castling is very natural, and sets some problems. }
8. Nxc6
{ White needs to take in order to be able to play Bd3 next. Delaying this any further would be punished by ...Re8 and ...d5. }
8... bxc6 9. e5
{ Quite clearly premature, but it is useful to know one particular line. } 9...
Qe7 10. Qe2
{ Black is now fine with more than one move, but the best line is... } 10...
Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qa3 { And Black is close to winning already. } *

