{ This move enjoys the best reputation. Black develops quickly and by pinning the knight puts some pressure on the e4-pawn. Note that Black is already set to castle on the next move, and he currently has three pieces in play as opposed to White's two. This is not that relevant if White plays the well-established mainline that I recommend in my 'Keep it Simple 1. e4'-Repertoire, but any deviation that delays development or weakens the structure will prove costly. Usually, White knows what he is doing and you will reach the position on move 8 quickly, but at lower levels you might face one of the bad alternatives that give Black excellent chances. }
6. Nxc6
{ White needs to develop and cover e4. To play Bd3 you need to take on c6 first. Very logical, but White has tried some worse alternatives. }
6... bxc6 7. Bd3
{ By far the most sensible move. Again alternatives are downright bad or at least questionable. }
7... O-O 8. O-O d5
{ In this position Black has a choice between three lines. Caruana has only faced this opening once, in an online rapid game, and he played  8...d6  . This was certainly played with a fight in mind. However, I am not a huge fan of playing  8...d6  in this particular situation due to the annoying pin,  9.Bg5  . It is not terrible for Black, but I would rather avoid it.   The second option is to play  8...Re8  , keeping options open. This is the move I would play if I needed to win the game at all costs. However, the verdict is still open if Black can actually equalize with this move, as about all main moves against it @@StartBracket@@  9.Qf3  ,  9.Bg5  ,  9.Re1  @@EndBracket@@ pose problems that are not easily met.   The traditional main line is simply to play  8...d5  ,  opening the position immediately. White will capture, after which 9... Bg4!? is our choice. This move was basically unknown until 2018, when it was played in several master level games. This line is perfectly sound, but also may lead to positions that make it very difficult for Black to play for a win with Black. Admittedly, if you have the Petroff in your repertoire you should not mind a draw too much, because there are some forced drawing lines that you can hardly avoid. }
9. exd5 Bg4
{ This move is one of the most remarkable novelties introduced in recent years. It was first played at a higher level in 2018 - maybe someone played it before, outside of mainstream databases. It is amazing that the position, after the traditional  9...cxd5  , has been played more than 8000 times in Mega 2018, while no one ever played  9...Bg4  - for more than a century. When I was writing my 'Keep it Simple 1. e4' repertoire I was not aware of the move, either, as it first saw the light of day when my Chessable release went live. Some months later we have more games and analyses and now we know that  9...Bg4  is perfectly playable, for Black. White has tried some lines to directly refute it, but these fail and end in very drawish positions. White can, however, keep the game going with modest moves, which is my recommendation for White. These lines are about equal, but not an immediate draw. I recommend the whole  9...Bg4  line for Black because you still have surprise value, and objectively it seems to be perfectly fine. I need to mention that  9...cxd5  is, of course, playable as well - I think that White has the easier game there, but Black is close to equal. It involves much more theory, though, than  9...Bg4  , which presents another argument in favour of the bishop move. }
10. f3
{ The most principled move for sure. I checked it for White, of course, and did not find anything convincing. }
10... Bh5 11. Bg5
{ This is the most interesting move, avoiding the long and forcing lines that emerge after taking on c6. }
11... Qd6
{ It looks computerish and it is of course a Stockfish suggestion. Well, if it works I don't mind that much how it looks! First of all, White can't take on c6 now due to Qc5+, so we are not giving up material this way. So what is White supposed to play? The critical move seems to be  12.Bxf6  , but this seems satisfactory to me. What else is there on move  12. We need to check some alternatives. }
12. Qe1 { Looks odd, but Qh4 is not a terrible idea. } 12... Nxd5 13. Bd2 Rfe8
{ Black's activity easily compensates for the pawn structure deficit. } *

