[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. dxe5
{ This move has gained some popularity in recent years, mostly due to the fact that White has nothing in the traditional main lines and ventures less explored ways. }
4... d5
{ The normal move. Black also has  4...Bc5  , which is fun to look at and analyze, but not very practical. It is tons to work to learn and extremely computerish, so we just stick with solid moves. }
5. Bd3 Nc5
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/8/4p3/3Pn3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ This transposes to  4.Bd3  d5  5.dxe5  Nc5  . Please refer to this line for details. }
*

