{ At this particular moment Black has quite a wide choice. Caruana has played the simplest move,  5...Nxd2  , in a game of utmost importance in the final round of the Berlin Candidates against Alexander Grischuk. He went on to win a fine game and become the challenger for the world championship title. I am going to recommend this move, but I need to mention that only 2 weeks later he faced the same line against Nikita Vitiugov and opted for the amazing move  5...Qd7!?!  .  I'd be delighted to explain to you what this move does, but I have no clue to be perfectly honest. The queen move is actually Stockfish's top choice at a very deep level of calculation, so it's not that Caruana just came up with it while showering one Sunday morning. Anyway, I do understand that it addresses the white idea to take on e4 and White has no direct way of punishing the odd queen position. For the purpose of this repertoire I am going with taking on d2 - it has been played by Caruana in a crucial game and it has been tested dozens of times. Still  5...Qd7  will probably shock most people, so it's a good one to try after analyzing it a bit yourself. There is no 'theory' about it, so make up your own if you like! }
