{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. dxe5
{ This move has gained some popularity in recent years, mostly due to the fact that White has nothing in the traditional main lines and ventures less explored ways. }
4... d5
{ The normal move. Black also has  4...Bc5  , which is fun to look at and analyze, but not very practical. It is tons to work to learn and extremely computerish, so we just stick with solid moves. }
5. Nbd2 Nxd2
{ At this particular moment Black has quite a wide choice. Caruana has played the simplest move,  5...Nxd2  , in a game of utmost importance in the final round of the Berlin Candidates against Alexander Grischuk. He went on to win a fine game and become the challenger for the world championship title. I am going to recommend this move, but I need to mention that only 2 weeks later he faced the same line against Nikita Vitiugov and opted for the amazing move  5...Qd7!?!  .  I'd be delighted to explain to you what this move does, but I have no clue to be perfectly honest. The queen move is actually Stockfish's top choice at a very deep level of calculation, so it's not that Caruana just came up with it while showering one Sunday morning. Anyway, I do understand that it addresses the white idea to take on e4 and White has no direct way of punishing the odd queen position. For the purpose of this repertoire I am going with taking on d2 - it has been played by Caruana in a crucial game and it has been tested dozens of times. Still  5...Qd7  will probably shock most people, so it's a good one to try after analyzing it a bit yourself. There is no 'theory' about it, so make up your own if you like! }
6. Bxd2
{ The more natural way to recapture. This was Grischuk's choice in the mentioned crucial game at the Berlin Candidates. }
6... Be7
{ Slightly more precise than the immediate  6...c5  , which allows  7.Bg5  . This would not be terrible for black, but is better avoided. }
7. c4 d4
{ This move leads to complicated fight of a more strategic nature. Black's alternative line  7...O-O  8.Qc2  Nc6  9.O-O-O  Bg4  is a sharper approach that also seems fine for Black. If you prefer to set the board on fire this is something to investigate. }
8. Bd3 c5 9. O-O Nc6 10. a3 a5
{ A very complex position type. Black should try to trade White's strongest piece, the d3-bishop. This bishop would be perfectly placed on e4, eyeing both sides of the board. You may go for ...Be6/Qd7 and then ...Bf5 to play for this desired trade. Another enterprising idea is to go ...g5 if White decides to go h3 at some point. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. dxe5
{ This move has gained some popularity in recent years, mostly due to the fact that White has nothing in the traditional main lines and ventures less explored ways. }
4... d5
{ The normal move. Black also has  4...Bc5  , which is fun to look at and analyze, but not very practical. It is tons to work to learn and extremely computerish, so we just stick with solid moves. }
5. Nbd2 Nxd2
{ At this particular moment Black has quite a wide choice. Caruana has played the simplest move,  5...Nxd2  , in a game of utmost importance in the final round of the Berlin Candidates against Alexander Grischuk. He went on to win a fine game and become the challenger for the world championship title. I am going to recommend this move, but I need to mention that only 2 weeks later he faced the same line against Nikita Vitiugov and opted for the amazing move  5...Qd7!?!  .  I'd be delighted to explain to you what this move does, but I have no clue to be perfectly honest. The queen move is actually Stockfish's top choice at a very deep level of calculation, so it's not that Caruana just came up with it while showering one Sunday morning. Anyway, I do understand that it addresses the white idea to take on e4 and White has no direct way of punishing the odd queen position. For the purpose of this repertoire I am going with taking on d2 - it has been played by Caruana in a crucial game and it has been tested dozens of times. Still  5...Qd7  will probably shock most people, so it's a good one to try after analyzing it a bit yourself. There is no 'theory' about it, so make up your own if you like! }
6. Bxd2
{ The more natural way to recapture. This was Grischuk's choice in the mentioned crucial game at the Berlin Candidates. }
6... Be7
{ Slightly more precise than the immediate  6...c5  , which allows  7.Bg5  . This would not be terrible for black, but is better avoided. }
7. Bd3 c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. h3 Be6 10. O-O Qd7
{ White has prevented the pin with ...Bg4, but Black has nothing to worry about. The general plan is to trade the d3-bishop if possible and try to set the queenside majority in motion after having castled kingside. Chances are about equal. }
*

