[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Nxe5
{ This is a sideline with almost no independent value. Black now actually has a choice of lines. You can play  4...d6  , which after  5.Nf3  transposes into 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 d6 5. d4 or the logical alternative 4... d5.   After  4...d5  White usually goes  5.Bd3  ,  transposing into the main line 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5. He has tried to deviate without much success. Probably it is easiest to just play 4... d6, which will transpose for sure. }
4... d6 5. Nxf7 { This just fails. } 5... Qe7
{ This you need to remember/find - The knight is now lost for no compensation. It is attacked by the queen now and Nc3+ is the main threat, winning the queen. }
