{ As mentioned before Caruana never faced this line so we can only guess what would happen here. However  5...Nd7  is the main line and Black has not experienced problems lately, so this seems like a very good guess. What does the move do? Black immediately challenges the centralized knight on e5, avoiding any long term concessions. For example  5...Nc6  would allow doubled pawns, while  5...Bd6  and taking on e5 later concedes the pair of bishops. It needs to be said that the move has one serious practical implication: if White wants to force an immediate draw, he can do so by sacrificing on f7, which leads to an unavoidable repetition of moves - more on that later. }
6. Qe2
{ This move was played in probably the most famous game of the whole line with 5... Nd7. World Champion Anatoly Karpov played it against Bent Larsen in 1980... and Larsen went on to win an excellent game against the dominant player of that time. After this game 6. Qe2 was still tried quite frequently, and the reason is quite clear: White wins a pawn, which is always tempting. The good news is that the basically mandatory pawn sac gives us great compensation. Let's see what I am talking about. }
6... Nxe5 7. Bxe4 dxe4 8. Qxe4
{ The knight is lost and White will be a pawn up, but Black's compensation will be very convincing as the coming lines show. }
8... Be6 9. dxe5
{ This is worse than  9.Qxe5  . We will get even more tempi now on the queen. }
9... Bd5 10. Qg4 { White needs to cover g2. } 10... h5 11. Qh3 Qe7
{ Black is fine here. White's only way to keep the pawn grants Black a dangerous attack. }
12. f4 Qe6 { This is very strong, forcing the trade on e6. } 13. Qxe6+ fxe6
{ And now White is under pressure, for example after } 14. Kf2 g5 15. fxg5 Bc5+
16. Be3 O-O+ { Black has a promising attack. } *

