{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5
{ This is the traditional way to play the 3. d4 line for White. In recent years this main line has not been tested much on the higher level. The current state of theory suggests that Black should be fine with the lines presented here. Caruana actually never faced this particular line, which shows that it is indeed out of fashion. Whenever an opponent played 3. d4, White would opt for a different approach on move 4 or 5. }
5... Nd7
{ As mentioned before Caruana never faced this line so we can only guess what would happen here. However  5...Nd7  is the main line and Black has not experienced problems lately, so this seems like a very good guess. What does the move do? Black immediately challenges the centralized knight on e5, avoiding any long term concessions. For example  5...Nc6  would allow doubled pawns, while  5...Bd6  and taking on e5 later concedes the pair of bishops. It needs to be said that the move has one serious practical implication: if White wants to force an immediate draw, he can do so by sacrificing on f7, which leads to an unavoidable repetition of moves - more on that later. }
6. Qe2
{ This move was played in probably the most famous game of the whole line with 5... Nd7. World Champion Anatoly Karpov played it against Bent Larsen in 1980... and Larsen went on to win an excellent game against the dominant player of that time. After this game 6. Qe2 was still tried quite frequently, and the reason is quite clear: White wins a pawn, which is always tempting. The good news is that the basically mandatory pawn sac gives us great compensation. Let's see what I am talking about. }
6... Nxe5 7. Bxe4 dxe4 8. Qxe4
{ The knight is lost and White will be a pawn up, but Black's compensation will be very convincing as the coming lines show. }
8... Be6 9. Qxe5 Qd7
{ We enjoy good development and the pair of bishops. Black's position is very simple to play. Even if you don't find the best line at all times there is often the emergency exit to trade the dark squared bishop for the knight and to go into an opposite colored bishops scenario where the pawn count does not matter most of the time. }
10. O-O { The most natural move. } 10... O-O-O 11. Be3 Bb4
{ A truly excellent concept, first played by Larsen against Karpov in 1980. I think it is truly admirable that he looked at the 5... Nd7 line without prejudice, analyzed this far and concluded to have good compensation. Nowadays we just switch on the engine to tell us that it should work - Larsen had to do it completely on his own. Why is that a strong move by the way ? The key is to recognize that White had Qa5 on the agenda, which is now prevented. }
12. c3 Bd6 13. Qa5
{ OK, White got to a5 after all. So why was 11... Bb4 such a good move then ? Couldn't we have played 11... Bd6 right away, not giving White the extra move c3? It turns out that it is useful for for Black to prevent Nc3 in some lines. Let's check the most critical line. }
13... Bd5
{ Very important to remember ! It is the most precise choice, immediately looking to sacrifice on g2. }
14. Nd2 Bxg2
{ Of course! It is not even a true sacrifice, we'll get the piece back in short order. }
15. Kxg2 Qg4+ 16. Kh1 Qh3 17. f4 { The only move, giving back the piece. }
17... Qxe3
{ And we have restored material equality with a fine position. White's king is just less safe in the long run. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #41"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5
{ This is the traditional way to play the 3. d4 line for White. In recent years this main line has not been tested much on the higher level. The current state of theory suggests that Black should be fine with the lines presented here. Caruana actually never faced this particular line, which shows that it is indeed out of fashion. Whenever an opponent played 3. d4, White would opt for a different approach on move 4 or 5. }
5... Nd7
{ As mentioned before Caruana never faced this line so we can only guess what would happen here. However  5...Nd7  is the main line and Black has not experienced problems lately, so this seems like a very good guess. What does the move do? Black immediately challenges the centralized knight on e5, avoiding any long term concessions. For example  5...Nc6  would allow doubled pawns, while  5...Bd6  and taking on e5 later concedes the pair of bishops. It needs to be said that the move has one serious practical implication: if White wants to force an immediate draw, he can do so by sacrificing on f7, which leads to an unavoidable repetition of moves - more on that later. }
6. Nc3
{ White is accepting a worsening of the pawn structure with this move, but gets good development and half open files in return. This line enjoyed some brief popularity a decade ago, but now the best defence has been worked out. }
6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Bc5
{ After 6. Nc3 this position develops quite logically. We trade both knights, giving White a doubled c-pawn. The bishop is now placed on the active square c5. If allowed we will continue with castling kingside and playing ...f6 in order to open the f-file and getting rid of the annoying e5 pawn. }
9. Qh5
{ This idea is the main point of the whole 6. Nc3 line. The active queen stops kingside castling for the moment and Black is still not developed fully. }
9... Qd7
{ This is a novelty suggest by Stockfish. It looks a bit odd, but it is a very concrete approach to the position that works well. Black just wants to play Qg4 to solve all of his problems and to get closer to an endgame when the pawn structure becomes more relevant. The queen move also prepares queenside castling. }
10. Rb1 { A very logical try, attacking b7 in order to stop Qg4. } 10... Qg4
{ It works anyway! That being said,  10...Bb6  is a playable alternative that avoids the possible draw that might occur after  10...Qg4  . }
11. Qxg4 Bxg4 12. Rxb7
{ Obviously the critical move, otherwise Black enjoys the better pawn structure in an endgame. }
12... Bb6
{ The white rook is trapped now, but we don't get more than equality unfortunately. }
13. Be3
{ This is the move that saves White from getting into trouble. Now Black should avoid  13...Bc8  , as  14.Bxb6  Bxb7  15.Bxc7  gives White ample compensation for the lost exchange. }
13... Kd8
{ The surprising solution! The king covers c7, so that ...Bc8 would win the exchange without dropping an additional pawn. With a repitition and a probable draw. }
14. Bg5+ Ke8
{ Trying to play for more than a draw with  14...Kc8  is not leading to much after  15.Ba6  ,  so just going back to e8 is fine, when White is again facing the ...Bc8 threat and may repeat with 15. Be3. }
15. Be3 Kd8 { With a repetition and a probable draw. } *

