[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #50"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5
{ This is the traditional way to play the 3. d4 line for White. In recent years this main line has not been tested much on the higher level. The current state of theory suggests that Black should be fine with the lines presented here. Caruana actually never faced this particular line, which shows that it is indeed out of fashion. Whenever an opponent played 3. d4, White would opt for a different approach on move 4 or 5. }
5... Nd7
{ As mentioned before Caruana never faced this line so we can only guess what would happen here. However  5...Nd7  is the main line and Black has not experienced problems lately, so this seems like a very good guess. What does the move do? Black immediately challenges the centralized knight on e5, avoiding any long term concessions. For example  5...Nc6  would allow doubled pawns, while  5...Bd6  and taking on e5 later concedes the pair of bishops. It needs to be said that the move has one serious practical implication: if White wants to force an immediate draw, he can do so by sacrificing on f7, which leads to an unavoidable repetition of moves - more on that later. }
6. Nxf7
{ As mentioned before this move leads to a draw by force. Please take that into account if you play into this line and a draw is not acceptable. However don't expect that all or even many lower rated opponents will play it. Most players want to play a game against a higher rated opponent and not end the game on move 6. So it is not going to happen all of the time, but this line is a non-starter in a scenario where you need to win at all costs and your opponent secures his game/ tournament goal with a draw. }
6... Kxf7
{ There is an alternative to avoid the immediate draw:  6...Qe7  . This is playable, but you need to play a whole string of only moves, only to be in a worse position without much play. It is not a viable option to play for a win - just take the knight and accept the draw. }
7. Qh5+ { And we need to repeat now with a draw. } 7... Ke7
{ Instead  7...Ke6  leads to the same thing after  8.Qe2  . } 8. Qxd5
{ This is an incorrect try to continue to attack and avoid the draw. Black can refute it quite easily. }
8... Ndf6 9. Qe5+ Kf7 10. Bxe4 Bb4+
{ Developing with tempo to prepare ...Re8. White is the one getting under fire now. }
11. c3 Re8 { And we have a winning attack on top of the extra material. } *

