[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #53"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. dxe5
{ As White was struggling more and more to get anywhere with the traditional 5. Nxe5, this capture became more popular. The e-pawn is obstructing the Black pieces, but Black has a healthy development and chances to set his majority in motion later. These positions are about equal, but not in a sterile way - there is play left, which is not the case in many 5. Nxe5 mainlines. }
5... Nc5
{ The main move. Black either wants to push the d3-bishop back to e2 or take it at an opportune moment. }
6. O-O Be7
{ It is better to develop the kingside first before taking any immediate action.  6...Nxd3  is premature because White gets a quick Rd1 and c4 push in. We want to wait with the capture until a better moment. }
7. Be2 O-O
{ This is a transposition to 6. Be2 and examined via this move order. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #54"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. dxe5
{ As White was struggling more and more to get anywhere with the traditional 5. Nxe5, this capture became more popular. The e-pawn is obstructing the Black pieces, but Black has a healthy development and chances to set his majority in motion later. These positions are about equal, but not in a sterile way - there is play left, which is not the case in many 5. Nxe5 mainlines. }
5... Nc5
{ The main move. Black either wants to push the d3-bishop back to e2 or take it at an opportune moment. }
6. O-O Be7
{ It is better to develop the kingside first before taking any immediate action.  6...Nxd3  is premature because White gets a quick Rd1 and c4 push in. We want to wait with the capture until a better moment. }
7. Nc3
{ Attention! White is threatening to take on d5! The knight does not look all that well placed on c3, but there is an idea behind it. }
7... c6
{ We needed to cover d5 and this supporting move is useful anyway. To be perfectly honest I don't quite understand what White is playing for here. Black has no development problems at all and I see no clear active plan for White. There have been attempts to make Nd4 and f4 work, but Black deals with it quite easily. Let's check. }
8. h3 O-O 9. Ne2
{ This is suggested by engines as about equal, but Black is fine after a simple sequence like the following. }
9... Nxd3 10. cxd3 Na6
{ Intending ...Nc5 and ...Bf5 if possible. Posting the knight on e6 and try for ...c5 and ...d4 later is an idea as well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #55"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. dxe5
{ As White was struggling more and more to get anywhere with the traditional 5. Nxe5, this capture became more popular. The e-pawn is obstructing the Black pieces, but Black has a healthy development and chances to set his majority in motion later. These positions are about equal, but not in a sterile way - there is play left, which is not the case in many 5. Nxe5 mainlines. }
5... Nc5
{ The main move. Black either wants to push the d3-bishop back to e2 or take it at an opportune moment. }
6. O-O Be7
{ It is better to develop the kingside first before taking any immediate action.  6...Nxd3  is premature because White gets a quick Rd1 and c4 push in. We want to wait with the capture until a better moment. }
7. Nc3
{ Attention! White is threatening to take on d5! The knight does not look all that well placed on c3, but there is an idea behind it. }
7... c6
{ We needed to cover d5 and this supporting move is useful anyway. To be perfectly honest I don't quite understand what White is playing for here. Black has no development problems at all and I see no clear active plan for White. There have been attempts to make Nd4 and f4 work, but Black deals with it quite easily. Let's check. }
8. Nd4 Nxd3 9. Qxd3 O-O 10. f4
{ The principled move, fitting with the white concept up to this point. } 10...
f6
{ Kramnik played  10...f5  instead in a game against David Navara. This is a good alternative, but I always like to attack the e5-pawn, trying to get rid of it as soon as possible. Amazingly  10...f6  was played first in a game E. Schiffers-J.Mason in 1889! }
11. e6 f5
{ The big point! Otherwise White would be better with f5 coming next to cover the e6-pawn. }
12. Nxf5
{ The only move. Against others there is ...g6 and then the e6-pawn will be lost in the long run. }
12... Bc5+ 13. Be3 Bxe3+ 14. Nxe3 Bxe6 { Please avoid  14...d4  15.Rad1  . }
15. f5 Bf7 16. f6 Bg6
{ And Black is fine. The white knights don't find good posts against the c6/d5 pawn centre construction. }
*

