[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #58"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. dxe5
{ As White was struggling more and more to get anywhere with the traditional 5. Nxe5, this capture became more popular. The e-pawn is obstructing the Black pieces, but Black has a healthy development and chances to set his majority in motion later. These positions are about equal, but not in a sterile way - there is play left, which is not the case in many 5. Nxe5 mainlines. }
5... Nc5
{ The main move. Black either wants to push the d3-bishop back to e2 or take it at an opportune moment. }
6. Nc3
{ White is threatening Nxd5 with this move, so we should just cover the important central pawn now. Note that this line transposes to 6. O-O almost exclusively. }
6... c6 7. Nd4 Be7
{ The easy solution. Now White will very likely castle, after we transpose to 6. O-O once again. }
8. f4 Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3 O-O 10. O-O f6 { And we transpose to 6. O-O again. } *

