[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Petroff with 3. d4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Sidelines: 3 d4 Nxe4 others #68"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4
{ 3.Nxe5  has been White's most popular reply against the Petroff since the early days of the opening. This move,  3.d4  , is White's main alternative if he does not want to transpose into a Four Knights Game with  3.Nc3  .   After  3.d4  Black should take the pawn on e4. The alternatives don't convince: after  3...exd4  4.e5  Black does not equalize   and  3...d6  , trying for a transposition into a Philidor, is met with  4.dxe5  with a White advantage.   So we just go  3...Nxe4  - if you can take e4 without being punished immediately, you should almost always do it! }
3... Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. dxe5
{ As White was struggling more and more to get anywhere with the traditional 5. Nxe5, this capture became more popular. The e-pawn is obstructing the Black pieces, but Black has a healthy development and chances to set his majority in motion later. These positions are about equal, but not in a sterile way - there is play left, which is not the case in many 5. Nxe5 mainlines. }
5... Nc5
{ The main move. Black either wants to push the d3-bishop back to e2 or take it at an opportune moment. }
6. Be2 { White preserves the bishop pair. } 6... Be7 7. O-O
{ By far the main line. White needs to castle anyway and keeps options open. }
7... O-O 8. Be3 c6
{ Black's idea is to develop with ...Nbd7 and possibly ...Qc7/...f6 to follow.   I also like  8...Nc6  instead, with about equal play. It makes sense to quickly develop and put pressure on e5. It comes down to a matter of taste, but I think my choice  8....c6  is simpler to learn and play. }
9. c4
{ This makes more sense now, compared to 8. c4. Now Black is committed to a pawn on c6, so a later ...Nc6 is impossible. Black is still fine of course, as we will see. }
9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nbd7
{ Black intends to develop with ...Nb6 and then choose the best square for the bishop on c8. Note that the e5-pawn is a possible target if White is not careful. }
12. Nc3 { This looks natural, but it poses no problems at all. } 12... Nb6 13.
Bxc5 Bxc5 14. Bb3 Bf5
{ 14...Bg4  was played in a game before, but Black should prevent Ne4, so this makes a lot of sense. }
15. h3 h6 16. g4 Be6
{ There also is  16...Bh7  , with equal play. After the main move I don't see any problems either. }
*

