[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Petroff with 3. d4 Main Line"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Main line: 3 d4 Nxe4 4 Bd3 d5 5 Nxe5 Nd7 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Nxd7 Bxd7 7. O-O
{ Certainly the most natural move. The alternatives are anaemic at best. } 7...
Bd6
{ This is clearly the main line at the professional levels nowadays. Black has also tried other moves, most notably  7...Qh4  . This active move is probably not entirely sound, but it is worth looking at if you want a sharp option to play occasionally. After  7...Bd6  White's only hope for advantage is some very concrete play based on attacking the knight on e4 and the pawn on d5. Any slow approach is completely harmless - Black has no weaknesses and the pieces are well developed. What White will try is some combination of the moves c4, Nc3 and Qh5. Black's responses are quite natural, but it pays to know the lines precisely. This whole complex of lines is not played that frequently anymore at the top level, because with 'perfect play' Black will fully equalize. }
8. Nc3
{ Putting pressure on e4 and d5 immediately. There are a variety of versions of this idea. Most frequently White plays Nc3 after going c4 first, but doing it right away has its points. Still, Black will equalize with precise play. }
8... Nxc3
{ 8...Qh4  is also playable, but the capture is fine, not to mention easier to play. }
9. bxc3 O-O
{ Black's pawn structure is preferable now, so White must play actively. } 10.
Qh5 f5
{ The only move, because d5 was attacked as well. White now has tried a range of moves, without much success. }
11. Rb1 b6
{ On move 11 White had many alternatives instead of 11. Rb1. All these moves are possible now as well, with the pair of moves Rb1/b6 inserted. It does not make much of a difference if these moves are played or not. Let's check some lines. }
12. Bg5 Qe8 13. Qf3 Qg6 14. Bf4 Bxf4 15. Qxf4
{ This is exactly the same sequence as after an immediate 11. Bg5, just with Rb1/b6 inserted. There is a serious difference though. Without Rb1/b6 we have ...Qc6 now, which is impossible here @@StartBracket@@Bb5 !@@EndBracket@@, but there is a solution. }
15... Qd6 16. Qxd6 cxd6
{ Black is fine here. In the position, without Rb1/b6, White is able to play Rfb1 and a4 next, with nagging pressure. Here White has no active idea at all. We have enough play on the c-file against the pawns. }
*

