{ This is clearly the main line at the professional levels nowadays. Black has also tried other moves, most notably  7...Qh4  . This active move is probably not entirely sound, but it is worth looking at if you want a sharp option to play occasionally. After  7...Bd6  White's only hope for advantage is some very concrete play based on attacking the knight on e4 and the pawn on d5. Any slow approach is completely harmless - Black has no weaknesses and the pieces are well developed. What White will try is some combination of the moves c4, Nc3 and Qh5. Black's responses are quite natural, but it pays to know the lines precisely. This whole complex of lines is not played that frequently anymore at the top level, because with 'perfect play' Black will fully equalize. }
