11. Rb1 b6
{ On move 11 White had many alternatives instead of 11. Rb1. All these moves are possible now as well, with the pair of moves Rb1/b6 inserted. It does not make much of a difference if these moves are played or not. Let's check some lines. }
12. Re1 c6 { This move covers d5 and gives the Black queen the c7-square. } 13.
Bg5 Qc7 14. c4 Be8 15. Qh3 dxc4 16. Bxc4+ Bf7 17. Be6 Bxe6 18. Rxe6 Rae8 19.
Rbe1 Rxe6 20. Rxe6
{ We have almost the same position in our repertoire emerging from 11. Re1, but with the pawn on b7 instead. In this position ...Qb6 is possible, but we have a different way to equalize here. }
20... Qd7 21. Qb3 Rf7
{ We will play ...h6, move the King and ultimately ...Re7 to get rid of the rook. I'll give some more possible moves to show the idea. }
22. h3 h6 23. Bd2 Bf8 24. Re5 Kh7 25. g3 Bd6 26. Re2 Re7
{ And the described rook manoeuvre is completed. } *

