8. Nc3
{ Putting pressure on e4 and d5 immediately. There are a variety of versions of this idea. Most frequently White plays Nc3 after going c4 first, but doing it right away has its points. Still, Black will equalize with precise play. }
8... Nxc3
{ 8...Qh4  is also playable, but the capture is fine, not to mention easier to play. }
9. bxc3 O-O
{ Black's pawn structure is preferable now, so White must play actively. } 10.
Qh5 f5
{ The only move, because d5 was attacked as well. White now has tried a range of moves, without much success. }
11. Bg5
{ This looks very natural, developing with a tempo. The problem is, White is simply forcing moves that Black is actually happy to play. }
11... Qe8 12. Qf3 Qg6
{ This is important to remember/find. The counterattack against the bishop is better than protecting the d5-pawn. }
13. Bf4
{ This looks very logical, trading the good bishop - but it still does not lead to much. }
13... Bxf4 14. Qxf4 Qc6
{ Instead  14...Qd6  15.Qxd6  cxd6  16.Rfb1!  followed by a4 offers a slight edge for White. Note that we have 11. Rb1 b6 12. Bg5 Qe8 13. Qf3 Qg6 14. Bf4 Bxf4 15. Qxf4 Qd6 in our repertoire. This is a substantially different situation, as White has already played Rb1. }
15. Rab1 a6
{ It looks a bit ugly with the bishop on d7, but White does not have enough to get anything going. }
16. Rfe1 Rae8 17. g3 Rxe1+ 18. Rxe1 Qxc3
{ White has enough for the pawn, but no more. } 19. Re7 Qc6 20. Qg5 Rf7 21.
Rxf7 Kxf7 22. Bxf5 Bxf5 23. Qxf5+ Kg8 { And it is completely equal. } *

