[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Petroff with 3. d4 Main Line"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 d4 Main line: 3 d4 Nxe4 4 Bd3 d5 5 Nxe5 Nd7 #53"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d4 Nxe4 4. Bd3 d5 5. Nxe5 Nd7 6. Nxd7 Bxd7 7. O-O
{ Certainly the most natural move. The alternatives are anaemic at best. } 7...
Bd6
{ This is clearly the main line at the professional levels nowadays. Black has also tried other moves, most notably  7...Qh4  . This active move is probably not entirely sound, but it is worth looking at if you want a sharp option to play occasionally. After  7...Bd6  White's only hope for advantage is some very concrete play based on attacking the knight on e4 and the pawn on d5. Any slow approach is completely harmless - Black has no weaknesses and the pieces are well developed. What White will try is some combination of the moves c4, Nc3 and Qh5. Black's responses are quite natural, but it pays to know the lines precisely. This whole complex of lines is not played that frequently anymore at the top level, because with 'perfect play' Black will fully equalize. }
8. c4
{ This is the main line by pure game count. White attacks the base of the e4-knight, which leaves little choice for black. }
8... c6 9. cxd5 cxd5
{ Now White has two ways to win the d5 pawn. In both cases Black will have excellent piece play to compensate for the material deficit. }
10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. Qh5 g6
{ @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pppb1ppp/3b4/3p4/3Pn3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@ Again Black gives up the d5-pawn for activity. Note that there is a line with a similar theme: after  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  O-O  10.Qh5  we need to play  10...f5  , as  10...g6  gives away the d5-pawn for nothing. Here we are able to sac the pawn for counterplay.   One key difference with ...f5 in those two cases is that here Black already has an isolated d-pawn, which makes creating some additional weak squares, with  12...f5  ,  less attractive. I would rather give up the problem pawn and prove equality by playing actively. That being said, Black has scored decently with 12... f5 as well. I just don't regard it as sound as the pawn sacrifice. }
13. Qxd5 Qc7
{ Black has good development and now double attacks the pawns on c3 and h2 @@StartBracket@@with check@@EndBracket@@. At this point White has tried a lot of moves, none of which get anywhere. Still, we need to check a few lines now. White quite often starts with  14.Bh6  , but he might also play this move later, basically forcing the rook to move. This way we get some transpositions, but it is not difficult to play, for Black, as the ideas remain the same. }
14. Bh6 Rfd8
{ I suggest moving to d8 in reply to Bh6. So unless you have a strong argument in favour of another move: just go to d8 when hit by Bh6. It makes sense there, opposing the queen, and later takes aim at the d4-pawn, which will be a target after c3 has dropped. }
15. Qg5 Qxc3 16. Qf6 Bf8
{ This position we examine via the 14. Qf3 move order. } *

