17... Qg7 { Amongst others White was threatening Bb2. } 18. Rxb7 Bc5
{ This is the best post for the bishop. It looks at the f2-pawn and covers a7, so Rab8 is prepared. }
19. Bd5 Bxd5
{ The alternative,  19...Qe5  , has been played in a game, but this solution is even simpler. }
20. Qxd5 Qd4 21. Qf3
{ The most dangerous try. White goes for Bb2 and play on the long diagonal. }
21... Rab8 22. Bb2 Qd6 23. Rxb8 Rxb8 24. Qc3
{ Hmm... what to do about the threats now ? } 24... f6
{ The only move, but it gives up this pawn. It turns out that Black has no problem keeping the balance due to the activity of the pieces. }
25. Qxf6 Qxf6 26. Bxf6 Rb6
{ An important tempo on the bishop, getting the rook to a6. } 27. Bc3 Ra6 28.
Ra1 { White is forced into this passive post. } 28... Ra4
{ I think we can stop here. This is an opening course, after all. If you feel unsure how this could be a draw, I suggest analyzing it a bit - and play it out against an engine. If you fail to hold with Black, switch sides! }
