{ Black has good development and now double attacks the pawns on c3 and h2 @@StartBracket@@with check@@EndBracket@@. At this point White has tried a lot of moves, none of which get anywhere. Still, we need to check a few lines now. White quite often starts with  14.Bh6  , but he might also play this move later, basically forcing the rook to move. This way we get some transpositions, but it is not difficult to play, for Black, as the ideas remain the same. }
14. g3
{ This has been most popular in the few recent games where this line has been chosen. Black is fine here as well. }
14... Be6 15. Qf3 Qxc3
{ The usual sequence. In this line Black also gets the d4-pawn, but White has temporary activity for it. }
16. Rb1 Qxd4 17. Be4
{ White looks very active here, but Black has one - and only one - equalizing sequence. }
17... Qg7 { Amongst others White was threatening Bb2. } 18. Rxb7 Bc5
{ This is the best post for the bishop. It looks at the f2-pawn and covers a7, so Rab8 is prepared. }
19. Bd5 Bxd5
{ The alternative,  19...Qe5  , has been played in a game, but this solution is even simpler. }
20. Qxd5 Qd4 21. Qxd4 Bxd4 22. Rd1 Rfd8 23. Kg2
{ White is still a tiny bit more active, so we need to continue a few more moves. }
23... Bb6 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. Bh6
{ It still looks annoying, but Black has a convincing way to untangle. } 25...
f5 26. h3 { Or any other move. } 26... Bd4 27. Kf3 Rd5
{ This is the idea - the rook is coming to a5 while the bishop is great on d4. It's completely equal now. }
*

