[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petroff with 3. Nxe5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nc4
{ The knight will usually retreat to e3 later. It all looks a bit weird to my eye, but White sometimes goes for this move to get fresh positions and maybe surprise Black. We'll see that it is not very dangerous against common sense play. }
4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the modern main line of the Petroff with the knight on f3 instead. The knight on c4 makes a substantial difference of course. }
5... Nxc3 6. bxc3
{ Capturing towards the centre is harmless. White commits to kingside castling and he is not able to develop anything dangerous while the pawn structure is slightly weakened. }
6... Be7 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3 Nd7
{ The knight is certainly best on f6. From c6 it would only look at protected squares like b4, d4 and e5. }
9. O-O Nf6
{ Black is fine here. It is an idea to delay ...d5 for the moment and play moves like ...Re8 and ...c6 first, waiting until a Ne5 reply is not possible or White has committed in some other way. However you may also just play ...d5 and after Ne5 play ...c5 quickly, which gives Black fine counterplay as well. }
*

