[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nc4
{ The knight will usually retreat to e3 later. It all looks a bit wierd to my eye, but White sometimes goes for this move to get fresh positions and maybe surprise Black. We'll see that it is not very dangerous against common sense play. }
4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the modern main line of the Petroff with the knight on f3 instead. The knight on c4 makes a substantial difference of course. }
5... Nxc3 6. dxc3 d5
{ There is nothing wrong about moves like  6...Be7  ,  playing just like in the modern main line 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7. However it makes perfect sense to push 6... d5 now, a move that is not possible in the main line due to 7. c4. }
7. Ne5
{ This has not been tried yet in practical play, but it is helpful to see the best reply, just in case. }
7... Bd6
{ This is best. Now White needs to retreat, after which we are fine with normal moves. The pawn on d5 is poisoned of course. }
8. Qxd5 Qe7 9. f4 f6 { And the adventurous knight is lost. } *

