[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petroff with 3. Nxe5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nc4
{ The knight will usually retreat to e3 later. It all looks a bit wierd to my eye, but White sometimes goes for this move to get fresh positions and maybe surprise Black. We'll see that it is not very dangerous against common sense play. }
4... Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Ne3
{ Quite an unusual position for the knight. It attacks d5 though and might help to play c4 later. Black is fine now with any standard move like  6...c6  or similar, but I like a different move here. }
6... Qf6
{ I don't know, somehow I always enjoy to play moves that look somewhat crude but are actually fine. Let's just threaten mate in one! }
7. Bb5+
{ This may lead to interesting complications that we will not play into. } 7...
c6 8. O-O Be6
{ I don't want the bishop, thank you very much ! In fact taking the piece is fine, but it leads to tactical complications that end in a draw after some adventures. You may have a look yourself, but it is not very practical to study this if you'll maybe NEVER get this on the board. After our choice Black is just fine without any hassle. }
9. Be2 Nd7
{ With fine play for Black. The only interesting try for White now is play for c4. }
10. c4 dxc4 11. Nxc4 Qd8
{ This is the engine suggestion, and it is a strong move. The queen is wrong on f6 in an anti-IQP scenario. Now simple moves like ...Be7 and ...Nb6 follow. }
*

