[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nc4
{ The knight will usually retreat to e3 later. It all looks a bit wierd to my eye, but White sometimes goes for this move to get fresh positions and maybe surprise Black. We'll see that it is not very dangerous against common sense play. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qe2
{ This is White's main try for something after choosing 4. Nc4 in the first place. It leads to unusual and less explored positions, which is often just enough in the @@StartBracket@@past-@@EndBracket@@ computer age. }
5... Qe7
{ I should mention that  5...d5  is actually playable here, but  5...Qe7  is by far the main move and more reliable. }
6. d3 { This is harmless, but we should look at one line of interest. } 6...
Nf6 7. Bg5 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Be7 9. Nc3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/5n2/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@ In the Lasker line with  3.Nxe5  d6  4.Nf3  Nxe4  5.Qe2  we get a similar position, just with the knight on f3 instead. One difference is that now after ...c6 White may take on f6 when you need to recapture with the pawn which is highly undesirable. This is easily avoided, though. }
9... Nc6 { This is best here, just as in the Lasker line. } 10. Nb5 Kd8
{ This is fine for Black. We have ...Re8 coming and no weaknesses at all. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petroff with 3. Nxe5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nc4
{ The knight will usually retreat to e3 later. It all looks a bit wierd to my eye, but White sometimes goes for this move to get fresh positions and maybe surprise Black. We'll see that it is not very dangerous against common sense play. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qe2
{ This is White's main try for something after choosing 4. Nc4 in the first place. It leads to unusual and less explored positions, which is often just enough in the @@StartBracket@@past-@@EndBracket@@ computer age. }
5... Qe7
{ I should mention that  5...d5  is actually playable here, but  5...Qe7  is by far the main move and more reliable. }
6. Ne3
{ White now threatens Nd5, winning ! So our choice is somewhat limited, but I think Black is fine after 6... Be6. }
6... Be6
{ The main idea to avoid  6...c6  is to be able to develop the knight to c6, potentially eying the queen on e2 with Nd4 jumps. This whole line with 4. Nc4 and 5. Qe2 is still relatively unexplored, so there is no clear main line from here. I will briefly look at some some moves now, rather then drilling deep into a particular continuation. }
7. Nc3
{ This was played by Richard Rapport against Wei Yi in a well known and very chaotic game. }
7... Nf6
{ This was played in the mentioned game, but if the coming complications are too much for you: taking on c3 and playing ...g6 next is also completely fine. }
8. g3 Nc6 9. Bg2 Qd7
{ White was ready for Nd5 jumps, so this sidestep is fine. } 10. b4
{ It's Rapport playing White ! } 10... d5
{ Black does not need to take, of course ! This central reply is fine for us. }
11. b5 Nd4
{ And Black was fine in R.Rapport - Y.Wei, Wijk aan Zee 2017. I'll stop here, but you should study this game in full if you don't know it. It's just a great slugfest ! }
*

