[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nc4
{ The knight will usually retreat to e3 later. It all looks a bit wierd to my eye, but White sometimes goes for this move to get fresh positions and maybe surprise Black. We'll see that it is not very dangerous against common sense play. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qe2
{ This is White's main try for something after choosing 4. Nc4 in the first place. It leads to unusual and less explored positions, which is often just enough in the @@StartBracket@@past-@@EndBracket@@ computer age. }
5... Qe7
{ I should mention that  5...d5  is actually playable here, but  5...Qe7  is by far the main move and more reliable. }
6. Ne3
{ White now threatens Nd5, winning ! So our choice is somewhat limited, but I think Black is fine after 6... Be6. }
6... Be6
{ The main idea to avoid  6...c6  is to be able to develop the knight to c6, potentially eying the queen on e2 with Nd4 jumps. This whole line with 4. Nc4 and 5. Qe2 is still relatively unexplored, so there is no clear main line from here. I will briefly look at some some moves now, rather then drilling deep into a particular continuation. }
7. d4 d5 8. c4 Nc6
{ This basically forces a draw. If you don't want to draw immediately you should play  8...Qb4+  or  8...dxc4  to continue the game. }
9. cxd5 Nxd4 10. Qd3 Qh4 11. g3 Nf3+ 12. Ke2 Nd4+ 13. Ke1 Nf3+
{ And it's going to be a repetition. There is no good option to avoid it. } *

