1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nxf7
{ This is the Cochrane gambit. White sacrifices the knight for two pawns and hopes that the black king in the centre gives compensation. It is not a fully correct line, but you can't expect to just refute it outright. One thing needs to be mentioned: you should play the lines suggest here, alternatives don't convince as much. Let's check details. }
4... Kxf7 5. d4 c5
{ This is the most important idea to remember. Black immediately attacks White's centre and intends to make use of his extra piece and development advantage. Black needs to avoid the clear mistake  5...Nxe4?  due to  6.Qh5+  Ke7  7.Qe2  .  White regains the piece with interest in this line. We should also avoid to play passively with slow moves. White's play is too simple in this case. He will build up a strong centre with f4 and a later e5 and have quite reasonable compensation. }
6. dxc5 Nc6
{ The alternative  6...d5  is also promising. However,  6...Nc6  is a fine move and the following positions may also arise from the different move order 5. Nc3 c5 - it therefore makes sense to choose this line as we need to know it anyway. Black enjoys an excellent development now, making the somewhat open king position less relevant. }
7. Bc4+ Be6 8. Bxe6+ Kxe6
{ Now Black has three pieces in play! Don't worry too much about the king, we will go back to f7 in short order and White does not have any piece developed that could harm us. }
9. Nc3 Kf7
{ The king needs to be withdrawn from the centre quickly. It is worse to play  9...dxc5  due to  10.Qe2  , which gives White too much play for the invested material. }
10. Qe2 Qd7
{ @@StartFEN@@r2q1b1r/pp4pp/2npkn2/2P5/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQ - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ The queen needs to help against the idea to play Qc4+. It is important to note that in the line with  9.O-O  Kf7  10.Qe2  we play  ...Qe8  instead. The reason becomes apparent when we check the move  11.Be3  .  After this move we now simply take on c5 and prevent queenside castling, which would not be possible with the queen on e8. This point is not relevant after the early 9. O-O obviously. Against the quick kingside castling going ...Qe8 is sensible as it also attacks the pawn on e4 immediately. }
11. Be3 dxc5 12. f4 Rd8
{ This is the engine's improvement on 11....Re8, played in the game V.Topalov-V.Kramnik, Linares 1999. I am still quite amazed that Topalov dared to play this line against Kramnik. }
13. h3 { After a slow move like this Black consolidates easily. } 13... Be7
{ And we go ...Rhe8 next. Black is clearly better. } *

