1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Alternatives are  4.Nc4  , which does not seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defence. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4 5. d3
{ A modest looking move, but it has been frequently played by strong GMs, most notably World Champion Magnus Carlsen. }
5... Nf6 6. d4
{ White wants to place the bishop on d3, so the d-pawn needs to be moved again. }
6... g6
{ Why not just  6...d5?  Of course there is nothing wrong with this move, and in fact it has been played by Caruana against Magnus Carlsen. Still I am not going to recommend it for practical reasons. After  6...d5  we will get  7.Bd3  Bd6  8.Qe2+  , against which you don't equalize that easily.   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ I have recommended that way to play for White in this position, coming from the French Exchange variation move order @@StartBracket@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.Bd3  Bd6  6.Qe2+  @@EndBracket@@.  I think it makes sense not to play into this line for Black here, as this move order with d3 and then d4 is usually played intentionally to get this particular line - and why not to avoid to play on the opponent's home turf ? It is interesting to note that White scores a lot better after 6... d5 from the Petroff move order than from the French Exchange move order - probably because White has some detailed knowledge that the Black player lacks. A long speech, but I wanted to explain why I suggest a less natural move. }
7. Bd3 Bg7
{ I need to mention that there is basically no theory available on 6... g6. It is a rare move, but neither engine @@StartBracket@@Stockfish@@EndBracket@@ nor human @@StartBracket@@me@@EndBracket@@ see anything wrong with it. }
8. Qe2+ Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7 10. O-O Re8
{ This is just not enough to pose us any problems. We will develop with ...Nc6 and ...Be6 or ...Bd7 next. }
*

