[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petroff with 3. Nxe5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #22"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Alternatives are  4.Nc4  , which does not seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defence. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qe2
{ The Lasker variation. It is not very ambitious, but very solid for White. The queens will get traded in this line almost all of the time. }
5... Qe7 6. Nc3
{ This move was played in the probably most important and spectacular game of the Berlin Candidates Tournament. After an excellent start to the event Kramnik played it against Caruana in round 4. Caruana managed to win the game after a true rollercoaster ride with missed chances for both sides. This game is worth studying, completely independent of the opening line. It also clearly shows that with some imagination and ambition you can create a fight even out of anaemic looking lines. }
6... Nxc3 7. dxc3 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Nc6 9. Be3
{ The only way to try for something. After castling queenside White might use the pawns on the kingside for some play. }
9... Be7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Rhe1 Bf6
{ This is how the mentioned Kramnik-Caruana game unfolded. Black does not face any serious dangers, which does not mean that nothing is going to happen later ! Please study this game if you don't know it already. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petroff with 3. Nxe5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #23"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Alternatives are  4.Nc4  , which does not seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defence. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qe2
{ The Lasker variation. It is not very ambitious, but very solid for White. The queens will get traded in this line almost all of the time. }
5... Qe7 6. d3 Nf6
{ In this symmetrical position White tries to prove that the extra tempo counts for something. This is tough to believe, but actually quite often White plays this way to be super solid and make a draw. If you need to the win the game and a draw is completely unacceptable: be patient and try to play for little things. It needs to be mentioned @@StartBracket@@as I do at several points in this repertoire@@EndBracket@@ that the Petroff is not the most suitable opening to play if you have to win at all costs. This is an issue against a player of a similar or higher rating than yours that just wants to make a draw. If you fear this scenario, you should problably opt for a different, non-symmetrical opening. }
7. Nc3
{ This move has been played against Caruana by Magnus Carlsen and Wesley So in important, classical time control events. This actually shows that players facing the Petroff have a hard time to gain any pull, so even harmless looking lines like that are explored. In fact there is a point to it, as we will see shortly. }
7... Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 g6
{ Caruana played this move twice, so we can be reasonably sure that he believes it is best. The rationale behind the move is twofold. First of all the bishop is not bad at all on g7, a development scheme that is impossible against 7. Bg5 instead. The second point is that in case of the more conventional looking 7... Be7 it turns out that Nc3 is more useful than Bg5 and White has some hope to get a small pull on the e-file. It can't be much, but 8... g6 is the more attractive option anyway. We are going for a setup involving ...Bd7 and ...Nc6 now, pretty much against anything White may try. }
9. Nd4
{ Carlsen's choice in January 2018 against Caruana, at the Tata Steel tournament in Wijk aan Zee. }
9... a6 { Not strictly necessary, but it is useful to cover b5. } 10. Bf4 Bg7
11. h3 Bd7 12. Bf3 Nc6
{ Black has completed the desired setup and it is even useful that we have not castled yet. After trades on c6 Black's king is nicely placed on d7, as it happened in M.Carlsen-F.Caruana, Wijk aan Zee 2018. The game ended in a draw. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petroff with 3. Nxe5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #24"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Alternatives are  4.Nc4  , which does not seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defence. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4 5. Qe2
{ The Lasker variation. It is not very ambitious, but very solid for White. The queens will get traded in this line almost all of the time. }
5... Qe7 6. d3 Nf6
{ In this symmetrical position White tries to prove that the extra tempo counts for something. This is tough to believe, but actually quite often White plays this way to be super solid and make a draw. If you need to the win the game and a draw is completely unacceptable: be patient and try to play for little things. It needs to be mentioned @@StartBracket@@as I do at several points in this repertoire@@EndBracket@@ that the Petroff is not the most suitable opening to play if you have to win at all costs. This is an issue against a player of a similar or higher rating than yours that just wants to make a draw. If you fear this scenario, you should problably opt for a different, non-symmetrical opening. }
7. Nc3
{ This move has been played against Caruana by Magnus Carlsen and Wesley So in important, classical time control events. This actually shows that players facing the Petroff have a hard time to gain any pull, so even harmless looking lines like that are explored. In fact there is a point to it, as we will see shortly. }
7... Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 g6
{ Caruana played this move twice, so we can be reasonably sure that he believes it is best. The rationale behind the move is twofold. First of all the bishop is not bad at all on g7, a development scheme that is impossible against 7. Bg5 instead. The second point is that in case of the more conventional looking 7... Be7 it turns out that Nc3 is more useful than Bg5 and White has some hope to get a small pull on the e-file. It can't be much, but 8... g6 is the more attractive option anyway. We are going for a setup involving ...Bd7 and ...Nc6 now, pretty much against anything White may try. }
9. Bg5
{ Played by Wesley So at the Berlin Candidates, two months after the World Champion had tried this line first against Caruana. }
9... Bg7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Rhe1 h6 12. Bh4 Nc6
{ This is how the So-Caruana game continued. Black has no problems at all and even got the more promising position later, but So defended well and managed to draw. }
*

