6. Qe2 { Certainly a critical try. White simply tries to grab a pawn. } 6...
Qe7
{ Stockfish actually suggests  6...f5  or even  6...Be7  , giving up a pawn immediately or some moves later. I don't trust these moves, even though the engine points out compensation for Black. The queen move is fine if followed up correctly. }
7. O-O Nd6
{ The knight supports the idea to play Bf5 later. Now the most testing move by White is the retreat  8.Qd1  ,  which will likely transpose into the line starting with 6. O-O instead of 6. Qe2. We need to briefly check the alternatives. }
8. Re1 Qxe2 9. Bxe2
{ This line proved to be quite tricky to analyze. Black is fine, but there are many pitfalls to avoid, surprisingly. }
9... Be7 10. Nc3 c6
{ Here  10...Be6  11.Nd4  Kd7?  does not work due to  12.Nxe6  fxe6  13.Bg4  and White wins. }
11. b3
{ This is the tricky move that White has available. The combination of Re1 and Ba3 is awkward to meet. }
11... Nd7
{ You need to remember this idea. Black intends to block the e-file by playing Nf8-e6. It is slow but it is the only satisfactory line that I could find. }
12. Ba3 Nf8 13. Bc4 { This leads nowhere, but you need to avoid a trap. } 13...
Nf5
{ Instead  13...Be6  looks simpler, but I am not sure that it equalizes completely. }
14. Bxd5
{ White goes in for the kill, but it only leads to simplifications with best play. }
14... cxd5 15. Nxd5 Be6 16. Bxe7 Bxd5 { And Black wins ! } *

