[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #35"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Alternatives are  4.Nc4  , which does not seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defence. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4 5. Bd3
{ Not the move you show to your beginner level students! You don't place the bishop in front of pawns early in the opening - this is a common advice for opening play. In fact it is not that simple, nowadays there are many lines where this development makes some sense. 5. Bd3 is one of those cases. White intends to later play c3, Bc2 and d4 ultimately. As you might suspect this move is not a main line, but it is encountered now and then as a surprise weapon on the higher level. }
5... d5
{ Black only has two sensible moves anyway. The simple  5...Nf6  and the more ambitious  5...d5  . Caruana has played  5...d5  in a very important game against Wesley So at the US Championships, so I am going to recommend this way of playing. It is a bit more complicated than just retreating the knight, but I feel the retreat makes it a bit too easy for White. }
6. Qe2 { Certainly a critical try. White simply tries to grab a pawn. } 6...
Qe7
{ Stockfish actually suggests  6...f5  or even  6...Be7  , giving up a pawn immediately or some moves later. I don't trust these moves, even though the engine points out compensation for Black. The queen move is fine if followed up correctly. }
7. O-O Nd6
{ The knight supports the idea to play Bf5 later. Now the most testing move by White is the retreat  8.Qd1  ,  which will likely transpose into the line starting with 6. O-O instead of 6. Qe2. We need to briefly check the alternatives. }
8. Qd1
{ This is the most common move. Play now transposes to the line starting with 6. O-O after the following moves. }
8... Qd8 9. Re1+ Be7
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/4n3/3B1N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ And we have transposed to mentioned game between Wesley So and Fabiano Caruana that went  6.O-O  Be7  7.Re1  Nd6  . }
