1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Alternatives are  4.Nc4  , which does not seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defence. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4 5. c4
{ White is going for a sideline that has some pitfalls for Black to avoid. We should equalize, but in some cases the move orders are relevant. With  5.c4  White stays flexible to some extent. He might still continue with d4 in one go, but there is also d3 and only then  d4  available. The other option is to play just Nc3 next, similar to the modern main line  5.Nc3  . }
5... Nc6
{ I like this move best. The knight is immediately taking up the optimal post against a possible future pawn on d4. }
6. d4 d5
{ Black now is happy to play Bb4 @@StartBracket@@+@@EndBracket@@ next, developing quickly and maybe trading some minor pieces. This is desirable with an IQP structure likely to occur. }
7. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black is obviously fine here. We are ahead in development already and there is pressure on c3 and d4. }
8. Qc2
{ The only interesting move to check, because there is an unusual possibility ahead. Against other moves Black gets a good attack with natural development. }
8... O-O
{ This is best. The interesting point I mentioned before is that instead  8...Qe7  is answered by the stunning  9.Kd1  , which is not clear at all! I recommend to just castle kingside, completing development. }
9. Be3 Re8
{ Black is to be preferred here. White needs to be precise to stay in the game. }
*

