6. d3
{ I mentioned a move order trickery earlier. This move order issue is related to this line. }
6... Nf6 7. d4 Be7
{ This is very important to remember! You should avoid the natural looking  7...d5  , as  8.c5!  is a good reply. White intends to play Bb5 next, setting up for the capture on c6 and Ne5 to follow. You should check the related line 6. d4 d5 7. c5, when Black still has the knight on e4, which makes a huge difference. All this is avoided by just playing ...Be7 first and only later push the d-pawn. }
8. d5 Ne5 9. Be2 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 O-O
{ We will play ...Nd7 and ...Bf6 next, getting the bishop on a great diagonal. From d7 the knight has some options, depending on what White plays. Anyway Black is fine here. }
