[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petroff with 3. Nxe5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Sidelines: 3 Nxe5 Others #50"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3
{ Certainly the most natural move. Alternatives are  4.Nc4  , which does not seem very dangerous, and the Cochrane gambit with  4.Nxf7  . The Cochrane is a dubious sacrifice, but you need to know the best defence. Let's check the moves. }
4... Nxe4 5. c4
{ White is going for a sideline that has some pitfalls for Black to avoid. We should equalize, but in some cases the move orders are relevant. With  5.c4  White stays flexible to some extent. He might still continue with d4 in one go, but there is also d3 and only then  d4  available. The other option is to play just Nc3 next, similar to the modern main line  5.Nc3  . }
5... Nc6
{ I like this move best. The knight is immediately taking up the optimal post against a possible future pawn on d4. }
6. Nc3
{ This is the most popular move at this stage. The play now is somewhat similar to the modern main line with 5. Nc3, but there is one substantial difference. The pawns are on c3 and c4 instead of c2 and c3. In the modern main line the doubled pawns are excellent for the king protection after O-O-O, which is invariably played. Here the pawns on c3 and c4 control the centre nicely, but the white king does not feel as safe on this queenside as he does in the different doubled c-pawn scenario. }
6... Nxc3 7. dxc3 Bf5
{ An alternative, popular move for Black is  7...g6  . The only drawback is that  8.Bg5  needs to be answered with  ...Be7  , after which  9.Bh6  Bf8  10.Bg5  is tough to avoid. Of course you can still play 7... g6, just be aware of this possible immediate draw. This exact draw occured in the game G.Jones-S.Mamedyarov, Wijk aan Zee 2018.   I don't think  7...Bf5  is objectively worse than  7...g6  ,  so why not avoid this immediate drawing option? Moving the bishop to f5 now makes sense as White's next move after something else is likely  8.Bd3  ,  when we don't have f5 available anymore for the bishop. }
8. Nd4 Bd7
{ This more precise than taking on d4, when Qxd4 puts annoying pressure on g7. We want to wait with the capture until a more appropiate moment arises. }
9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Bf6
{ Black is fine here. We have no weaknesses at all and no bad pieces. } *

