[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Petroff with 3. Nxe5 Main Line"]
[Black "Petroff with 3 Nxe5 Main Line: 3 Nxe5 with 5 d4 d5 6 Bd3 Bd6 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3
{ The only sensible move and the main line not by miles, but rather light years. }
6... Bd6
{ This is Caruana's choice, but I like to point out that Black also has excellent results with a line that most of the Chinese top players play. This line starts either  6...Be7  7.O-O  Bf5  or  6...Bf5  7.O-O  Be7  and is extremely solid for Black. I have employed this line in a crucial game this year @@StartBracket@@2018@@EndBracket@@ when I needed a draw with Black against GM Stanley Martinez to fight for the top prizes in the San Sebastian Open. The 'Chinese Wall line' is a worthy alternative to our choice  6...Bd6  , which is a more ambitious way to play. Black is placing the bishop on the most active square and challenges White to prove that the knight on e4 is a liability in an otherwise symmetrical position. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ Almost invariably played, and for good reason. White needs to put pressure on the d5-pawn and knight on e4, there is just no other reasonable plan to pursue. }
8... c6
{ This is the actual starting point, the tabiya of the 6... Bd6 Petroff main line. All deviations before are harmless for Black or at best transpose here. Now White has tried a range of moves and ideas. The key piece is the knight on e4. It is active on e4, but also subject to attacks. All the natural moves available to White have some connection to the knight. White may play Nc3 now or after the trade or attack the knight on e4 with either Re1 or Qc2. The further play is very concrete and tactical, so knowing the lines well and calculating precisely are important key virtues in this complex of lines. }
9. Re1
{ One of the main lines at this point. White attacks the e4-knight, threatening to win a pawn. We need to support the centralized outpost of course. }
9... Bf5
{ This natural move has been Caruana's choice on multiple occasions. White has tried various moves now to increase the pressure on e4 and d5. }
10. Qc2
{ I believe the queen move to c2 is more challenging on move nine than here, with 9. Re1 Bf5 inserted. Black's standard reply to Qc2 is... }
10... Na6
{ The most active reply, threatening ...Nb4. White has little choice now. } 11.
a3 Bg6
{ This is an important move to remember. The bishop is covered on g6 and we are also preparing to push ...f5 if appropiate. }
12. c5
{ This is the most ambitious move, but I think it is very risky. Black has good attacking chances now. }
12... Bb8
{ Retreating all the way, because we should leave c7 open for the knight to join the party. The route a6-c7-e6 is a very tempting prospect. On e6 the knight plays an excellent role by attacking the d4-pawn and being close to the kingside. }
13. Nc3 f5
{ Of course ! The knight is fantastic on e4 and we will keep it there at almost all costs. The only drawback is the weakening of the central square e5, but this is difficult to exploit for White. }
14. Ne2 { Very logical, preparing to move a piece to f4. } 14... Nc7 15. Bf4
{ This natural move already lands White into trouble. } 15... Bh5
{ Simple and strong. The coming Bxf3 demolishes the pawn structure and weakens both the king position and the central pawn on d4. }
16. Ng3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Ne6
{ Very strong play ! As mentioned we don't want to move the knight on e4 - and here even a sacrifice is completely correct and good for Black. }
18. Bxb8 Nxd4 19. Qd1 Rxb8
{ Black has a dangerous attack. Let's look the most critical line. } 20. fxe4
fxe4 21. Be2 Qf6 22. Rf1
{ Otherwise we'll take the third pawn on f2 and continue to attack. } 22... g6
{ Very strong and good to remember. The idea h7-h5-h4 is tough to meet. } *

