{ Black has also played  10...Bg4  here, but we follow Caruana's repertoire and taking on c4 seems like the soundest choice anyway. }
11. Bxc4 Bf5
{ We reached the most common pawn structure in the Petroff. White does not have many options with pawn play, but rather relies on piece activity. Now  12.Bg5  is the latest trend, but White has tried a lot of moves besides that. }
12. Re1 Nd7 13. Bg5
{ Certainly the most active. It is tough to imagine any problems for Black after slow moves. If given time, Black connects rooks with ...Qc7 or ...Qa5 and gets in ...Re8. }
13... Qa5 14. Qb3
{ Played by Vishy Anand against Caruana in St. Louis 2017. Black's reaction is worth remembering, as it is a common strategy. }
14... b5
{ Taking control of the light squares. Ideally Black would like to blockade the pawns, then use d5/c4 for his pieces. }
15. Bf1 Rfe8 { The immediate  15...Be6  fails to  16.Rxe6  . } 16. c4 Be6 17.
Qc2 bxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4 Qd5
{ And in the mention Anand-Caruana game they agreed to a draw 11 moves later. Black has comfortably equalized. }
