9. Nc3
{ The most popular move, and the one I would expect to happen most frequently at the non-professional level. It is a very natural continuation for sure, and often the choice of players who don't know deep theory at this point. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4
{ Black has also played  10...Bg4  here, but we follow Caruana's repertoire and taking on c4 seems like the soundest choice anyway. }
11. Bxc4 Bf5
{ We reached the most common pawn structure in the Petroff. White does not have many options with pawn play, but rather relies on piece activity. Now  12.Bg5  is the latest trend, but White has tried a lot of moves besides that. }
12. Bg5
{ One of the most recents tries to break down Caruana's Petroff featured this move. It was played in A.Giri-F.Caruana, Baden-Baden 2018. }
12... Qa5 13. Nh4
{ The concrete idea of this line. Black now needs to drop back to e6. After  13...Bg6  14.f4!  is terrible for Black. }
13... Be6 14. Bxe6 Qxg5 15. Nf3 Qa5
{ Caruana played  15...Qd8  against Giri. He equalized with this move, but ultimately lost the game after some inaccurate decisions. I suggest to play  15...Qa5  instead. I don't think it is much of a difference, but I feel you are organizing a bit quicker with Black. }
16. Qb3
{ @@StartFEN@@rn3rk1/pp3ppp/2pbB3/6q1/3P4/2P2N2/P4PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@ This is a difference to playing  15...Qd8  , when  16.Qb3  is not available. }
16... Qb6
{ Forces the queen trade, after which Black has completely equalized. The only point of White's play is the better bishop that always exerts some pressure on the kingside and f7 in particular. Without queens this is easier to neutralize. }
