9. h3
{ Avoiding all theoretical disputes. White just stops ...Bg4 by making a generally useful move. It is not putting any pressure on the centre though and thus quite harmless. }
9... Bf5
{ We will follow up with ...Nd7, ...Re8 - the useful centralizing moves available. Most of the time White now goes for  10.Nc3  ,  which leads to positions that we have examined via 9. Re1 Bf5 10. Nc3 - nothing to worry about. }
10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Nd7
{ Here h3 can hardly be more useful than Re1. Black enjoys easy equality. } *

