6... Bd6
{ This is Caruana's choice, but I like to point out that Black also has excellent results with a line that most of the Chinese top players play. This line starts either  6...Be7  7.O-O  Bf5  or  6...Bf5  7.O-O  Be7  and is extremely solid for Black. I have employed this line in a crucial game this year @@StartBracket@@2018@@EndBracket@@ when I needed a draw with Black against GM Stanley Martinez to fight for the top prizes in the San Sebastian Open. The 'Chinese Wall line' is a worthy alternative to our choice  6...Bd6  , which is a more ambitious way to play. Black is placing the bishop on the most active square and challenges White to prove that the knight on e4 is a liability in an otherwise symmetrical position. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ Almost invariably played, and for good reason. White needs to put pressure on the d5-pawn and knight on e4, there is just no other reasonable plan to pursue. }
8... c6
{ This is the actual starting point, the tabiya of the 6... Bd6 Petroff main line. All deviations before are harmless for Black or at best transpose here. Now White has tried a range of moves and ideas. The key piece is the knight on e4. It is active on e4, but also subject to attacks. All the natural moves available to White have some connection to the knight. White may play Nc3 now or after the trade or attack the knight on e4 with either Re1 or Qc2. The further play is very concrete and tactical, so knowing the lines well and calculating precisely are important key virtues in this complex of lines. }
9. Qc2 Na6 10. a3 Bg4 11. Ne5 { The only critical move at this moment. } 11...
Bf5
{ This is Caruana's choice, but the traditional  11...Bxe5  is interesting as well. }
12. b4
{ This not only gains space, but it has a very tactical justification. Black has the idea to play ...Nac5, using the unstable position of the knight on e5. }
12... Nc7
{ Caruana's novelty in his game against Vishy Anand in Wijk aan Zee 2018. Fabiano lost this game, but it was not due to this new concept. The amazing point actually comes on the next move. I'd like to mention that black also has the stunning  12...c5  at his disposal. I couldn't find a white advantage against this either, but you can do worse than trust Caruana in the Petroff. A general note: general considerations don't play a huge role in the upcoming complications, it's just a matter of 'it works' or 'it doesn't work' in most cases. The lines are extremely tactical and I advise to analyze them for yourself to better understand the tactical ideas. I will guide you through the jungle, but in some cases there are so many possibilities that showing all lines is just overkill - you should put it on the board and use your engines to explore on your own. }
13. f3
{ The most obvious and critical move - what is black doing with this pin now  ? Still it is worth checking the alternative move  13.Nc3  . }
13... Bg6
{ It is really remarkable that 13. f3 can be answered by this calm retreat  ! It is not the only move by the way: in a game played some months after the debut of the line  13...Bxe5  was tried and Black drew later in A. Shirov-M.Antonsen, Helsingor 2018. I checked this line and found no substantial problem, but I see no reason to deviate from Caruana's original concept. }
14. cxd5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Qxd5
{ The knight is hanging on e4, but all works out for Black in the upcoming tactical melee. }
16. fxe4 Qd4+ 17. Kh1 Rad8 { An important zwischenzug, gaining a tempo. } 18.
Bc4 Qxa1 19. Nc3
{ Our queen is in trouble it seems, but we have a great reply. } 19... Nd5 20.
Bb2 Ne3 21. Qf2 Rd2
{ Nice, huh ? It would be good fun to get that on the board once, blitzing all out. }
22. Qxd2 Nxc4 23. Bxa1 Nxd2
{ And after all this craziness we have an endgame where Black is clearly better. }
*

