[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. (Alternative) Petroff Modern Main Line"]
[Black "Alternative Chapter"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ When I was writing this course, back in 2018, it was just before the World Championship Match between Magnus Carlsen and Fabiano Caruana. I couldn't know what Caruana was going to play in the match.   It was tough to say if he would castle Queen-side or King-side.  Caruana had played both approaches, and it wasn't clear which one was his favorite. So I had to make a decision and I gave Nc6 as the mainline, but now in 2021 I have updated the course with another Chapter castling King-side.  This was his choice during the World Championship Match and since then it has become the mainline for everyone.   You can study both, and mix them. Both options are correct but this chapter will be set as an alternative for that reason and the new chapter will be set as the mainline. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. (Alternative) Petroff Modern Main Line"]
[Black "Petroff Modern Main Line: 3 Nxe5 d6 4 Nf3 Nxe4 5 Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the modern main line of the Petroff. When the Petroff got more popular at the start of the Millenium, White had a hard time to prove anything in the traditional main line of  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@this is still the case actually !@@EndBracket@@. So White turned attention to other tries and  5.Nc3  quickly emerged as an interesting weapon to combat the Petroff. Nowadays  5.Nc3  is the mainline of the Petroff, so we need to take it very seriously. We'll discuss the ideas connected to after the next move. }
5... Nxc3
{ Most natural and best. However I'd like to mention that I have played  5...Nf6  in classical time control chess and quicker formats. The main reason is not so much the quality of the move, but rather my lack of knowledge of the main lines. When I prepared the Petroff as a surprise weapon at the end of 2017, I wanted a simple line that my opponents probably don't know all that well, so I went for  5...Nf6  . I still think this is a decent choice, but it should not be the main recommendation in a repertoire that is heavily influenced by Fabiano Caruana's way of handling the black pieces. Caruana always played  5...Nxc3  , so this has to be the choice. }
6. bxc3
{ This capture is harmless. White takes 'towards the centre', as it is often recommended. However the queenside is now weaker compared to  6.dxc3  @@StartBracket@@two pawn islands instead of one@@EndBracket@@ and White has no simple, yet dangerous ideas, like castling queenside and go for a pawn storm. Let's look at some sample moves. }
6... Be7 7. d4 O-O 8. Bd3 d5 9. O-O c5
{ This idea is worth to take note of. Black wouldn't mind to push ...c4, kicking the bishop to a more passive square. Taking on c5 also looks unimpressive, so this is a good way to play for Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. (Alternative) Petroff Modern Main Line"]
[Black "Petroff Modern Main Line: 3 Nxe5 d6 4 Nf3 Nxe4 5 Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the modern main line of the Petroff. When the Petroff got more popular at the start of the Millenium, White had a hard time to prove anything in the traditional main line of  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@this is still the case actually !@@EndBracket@@. So White turned attention to other tries and  5.Nc3  quickly emerged as an interesting weapon to combat the Petroff. Nowadays  5.Nc3  is the mainline of the Petroff, so we need to take it very seriously. We'll discuss the ideas connected to after the next move. }
5... Nxc3
{ Most natural and best. However I'd like to mention that I have played  5...Nf6  in classical time control chess and quicker formats. The main reason is not so much the quality of the move, but rather my lack of knowledge of the main lines. When I prepared the Petroff as a surprise weapon at the end of 2017, I wanted a simple line that my opponents probably don't know all that well, so I went for  5...Nf6  . I still think this is a decent choice, but it should not be the main recommendation in a repertoire that is heavily influenced by Fabiano Caruana's way of handling the black pieces. Caruana always played  5...Nxc3  , so this has to be the choice. }
6. dxc3
{ This is the idea connected to the modern main line. By capturing this way White is emphasizing development and prepare a quick queenside castling. In fact the next moves by White will often be Be3/Qd2/O-O-O. It is important to understand that the queenside pawn formation for White is excellent in terms of king safety. White will therefore play queenside castling, almost no matter what Black is doing... so Black needs to decide where to place the king. You may castle queenside as well, which is the safe and sound choice. It is more exciting to castle kingside, but this will frequently lead to games where you need to defend against a vicious attack that is rather easy to conduct by White. Fabiano Caruana has mostly played with O-O-O as Black, but he also tried the sharper option twice in 2018: he played the early O-O vs. Ray Robson at the US Championships and against Levon Aronian at the Olympiad, basically when this course was already completed. I decided that aiming for queenside castling should be focus of our study. It has been played by Caruana and is the trusted choice of most Petroff experts, in particular of the chinese top players. }
6... Be7
{ This has to be played, completely regardless of future castling plans. } 7.
Bf4
{ White's traditional alternative to the current main line  7.Be3  .  In recent years this line has lost its popularity on the top level, as it transpired that Black has more than one way to get equal chances. One way to play is to castle kingside - it seems that Black benefits from the bishop being on f4. However in this repertoire I advocate to go queenside whenever possible and in fact in this setup the bishop is also better placed on e3, as we will see later. I am not going to analyze this line in huge detail, as the similarities to the Be3 version are obvious. If you learn how to handle this line with Be3, than you will be able to face Bf4 as well. One fact worth mentioning: Fabiano Caruana never faced  7.Bf4  ,  showing that this line is currently not regarded as very testing. }
7... Nc6 8. Bd3 Be6 9. Qe2 { This is the idea behind the early Bd3. } 9... Qd7
10. O-O-O O-O
{ I recommend to castle kingside here, as  10...O-O-O  11.Bb5  is awkward to meet. This version with the bishop on f4 actually seems somewhat playable for Black, with the bishop on e3 it is just not feasible at all. In any case, going kingside is fine and the play is very similar to the Be3 version. There is one particular idea you should be aware of though. }
11. Rhe1
{ Now Qe4 is an idea for White, only possible due to the bishop being on f4. }
11... Rfe8
{ Black is OK in this position. The main thing is to avoid the setup that we usually play against the bishop on e3 - if you play  11...Rae8?  White has the strong  12.Qe4  g6  13.Bh6  and we lose the exchange. }
*

