[Round "?"]
[White "9. (Alternative) Petroff Modern Main Line"]
[Black "Petroff Modern Main Line: 3 Nxe5 d6 4 Nf3 Nxe4 5 Nc3 #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the modern main line of the Petroff. When the Petroff got more popular at the start of the Millenium, White had a hard time to prove anything in the traditional main line of  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@this is still the case actually !@@EndBracket@@. So White turned attention to other tries and  5.Nc3  quickly emerged as an interesting weapon to combat the Petroff. Nowadays  5.Nc3  is the mainline of the Petroff, so we need to take it very seriously. We'll discuss the ideas connected to after the next move. }
5... Nxc3
{ Most natural and best. However I'd like to mention that I have played  5...Nf6  in classical time control chess and quicker formats. The main reason is not so much the quality of the move, but rather my lack of knowledge of the main lines. When I prepared the Petroff as a surprise weapon at the end of 2017, I wanted a simple line that my opponents probably don't know all that well, so I went for  5...Nf6  . I still think this is a decent choice, but it should not be the main recommendation in a repertoire that is heavily influenced by Fabiano Caruana's way of handling the black pieces. Caruana always played  5...Nxc3  , so this has to be the choice. }
6. dxc3
{ This is the idea connected to the modern main line. By capturing this way White is emphasizing development and prepare a quick queenside castling. In fact the next moves by White will often be Be3/Qd2/O-O-O. It is important to understand that the queenside pawn formation for White is excellent in terms of king safety. White will therefore play queenside castling, almost no matter what Black is doing... so Black needs to decide where to place the king. You may castle queenside as well, which is the safe and sound choice. It is more exciting to castle kingside, but this will frequently lead to games where you need to defend against a vicious attack that is rather easy to conduct by White. Fabiano Caruana has mostly played with O-O-O as Black, but he also tried the sharper option twice in 2018: he played the early O-O vs. Ray Robson at the US Championships and against Levon Aronian at the Olympiad, basically when this course was already completed. I decided that aiming for queenside castling should be focus of our study. It has been played by Caruana and is the trusted choice of most Petroff experts, in particular of the chinese top players. }
6... Be7
{ This has to be played, completely regardless of future castling plans. } 7.
Be3 Nc6
{ Fabiano Caruana has also tried the sharpest option  7...O-O  in the already mentioned games against Ray Robson and Levon Aronian. However in the vast majority of his games he went for  7...Nc6  , still being flexible about the side to castle. Most of the time we will go queenside, but there are some specific scenarios where the kingside is preferred or it is even necessary to castle this way. We will examine this in detail. }
8. Bc4
{ The latest try by the World Champion Magnus Carlsen against Fabiano. Magnus got very close to a win, so this not yet very well known line might get some more attention in the future. }
8... Bf6
{ This move has not yet been played in professional chess, but I still like to recommend it. Caruana played  8...O-O  against Carlsen and only survived the kingside attack with extreme resilience and some luck. I don't think that castling kingside is bad in general, but I like to go queenside with my king to avoid the 'who comes first' scenarios where White's attack is simpler to conduct. Okay, let's talk about  8...Bf6  now. I got to this move after checking  8...Be6  .  I felt trading this bishop on c4 is helpful, but couldn't quite make  9.Bxe6  fxe6  10.h4!  work for Black. One issue was that the white queen was still on d1, being flexible where to go next. This led to going ...Bf6 first, as white's next move is most likely going to be a queen move. Only then we will play ...Be6. Let's check some possibilities. I need to stress that the coming lines are all untested analysis and rather deep to illustrate the play. }
9. Qe2 Be6 10. O-O-O { This sets more problems compared to the capture on e6. }
10... Bxc4
{ Instead  10...Qd7  is met by  11.Bg5  ,  which is a bit awkward to meet. This highlights why the queen is best on e2 if White intends to avoid the trade on e6. }
11. Qxc4 Qd7
{ White needs to act quickly now. If Black gets castled queenside there will not even be a hint of an advantage. }
12. g4 g6
{ And O-O-O next. After the the immediate castling 13. g5 is uncomfortable for Black. Now retreating to g7 is possible is that case. }
*

