6... Be7
{ This has to be played, completely regardless of future castling plans. } 7.
Be3 Nc6
{ Fabiano Caruana has also tried the sharpest option  7...O-O  in the already mentioned games against Ray Robson and Levon Aronian. However in the vast majority of his games he went for  7...Nc6  , still being flexible about the side to castle. Most of the time we will go queenside, but there are some specific scenarios where the kingside is preferred or it is even necessary to castle this way. We will examine this in detail. }
8. Bd3
{ White's idea is to play the Queen to e2 and then castle queenside. This setup has gained momentum in recent years and is indeed not easy to meet - especially if Black intends to castle queenside. }
8... Be6 9. Qe2
{ White has also played  9.Qd2  at this point,   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp1bppp/2np4/8/8/2P1BN2/PPP2PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 4 8@@EndFEN@@ but it is just a worse version of the mainline  8.Qd2  Be6  9.O-O-O  .  The white bishop just does not help on d3 at all. The point of playing Qe2 is to not block the d-file, as will become apparent as we examine the next moves. }
9... Qd7 10. O-O-O O-O
{ This is one of the rare cases where I advocate to castle kingside. There is a very concrete reason: going queenside just does not work  ! Against  10...O-O-O ?  White has the strong reply  11.Bb5!  and the threat of Ne5! is awful for Black. Well, with immediate castling impossibe you may try to improve/wait until a later stage to castle queenside, but I failed to make it work in a satisfactory manner. Ultimately I checked the move I am suggesting now and found that in this particular case White's attacking play is not that dangerous. Let's check some lines now. I need to mention that is tough analyze all possible permutations of useful moves that White might play. Moves like Kb1, h3, Rhe1 can be played in many move orders, but it's most important that you get a feel for Black's setup. }
11. h4
{ This is yet untried, but certainly logical enough. One idea is to play Ng5. }
11... Rae8
{ Sticking to the standard idea to play ...a6 and ...Bd8, then ...Bf5 or ...f5 according to circumstances. I need to mention that 11. h4 also allows moves like  11...Bg4  , which seems OK as well. This would prevent the upcoming complications. }
12. Ng5 { Trying to make use of the h4-push and leading to sharp play. } 12...
Bf5 13. g4 Bxg4 14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15. f3 Bh5
{ This is obviously quite sharp. I think Black is OK here, but it is messy. As mentioned, there is a quieter alternative on move 11. }
