11. b3
{ @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pppqbppp/2npb3/8/8/2P1BN2/PPPQ1PPP/2KR1B1R w kq - 8 10@@EndFEN@@ Covering the a2-pawn. Note that it is not just about Black possibly taking the pawn with the bishop, but also about tactical motifs based on ...Qa4. The most important line to illustrate this idea is  10.Kb1  Bf6  11.h4  O-O-O  , when  12.Nd4  Nxd4  13.Bxd4  Be5  is possible because a7 is tactically covered due to the ...Qa4 resource. At first sight you might think this idea of playing b3 is very similar to going a3, but in fact there is the major difference that c3 and possibly the long diagonal h8-a1 is weakened. This gives Black a defensive resourse that is not effective against other setups.   Going  11.b3  is closely related to 10. b3 of course. Here Black has some more options, but playing in similar style as against 10. b3 is perfectly viable. }
11... a6
{ In the position after 10. b3, without the h-pawn having moved, White's main move is 11. h3 as played in many grandmaster games. In the h4-version we don't have many practical game examples yet, very likely because strong players rather want the h3-option to still be available. }
12. Kb2 O-O-O 13. Nd4 Bf6
{ In the game M.Dann-Z.Xiang, Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2018, Black played  13...Nxd4  . This is not a bad move, but I think going  13...Bf6  is more in spirit of the ...a6 setup. }
14. Be2 Ne7 { Black introduces ...Nd5 into the position. } 15. Nxe6 fxe6
{ Black is fine here, with both ...Nf5 and ...Nd5 on the cards. } *

