{ The main tabiya of the modern main line of the Petroff. Studying it is quite a challenge, as from here both sides have a range of moves to play to improve their position, and these moves may be played in various move orders that all have their points. Small differences may have serious consequences and it is highly transpositional. One key point to understand is that White's main idea is to play Nd4 at a good moment. It is most natural for Black to take it and after a piece recaptures on d4 Black needs to watch out for the pawns on a7 and g7. Most of the move order trickery is about not allowing White to get to a favourable version of this scenario. White has tried many moves at this point that are either direct attempts or belong into the category of improvement moves that try to outmanouvre or trick Black. The direct attempts are actually quite harmless. Let's get into details. }
10. b3
{ Covering the a2-pawn. Note that it is not just about Black possibly taking the pawn with the bishop, but also about tactical motifs based on ...Qa4. The most important line to illustrate this idea is  10.Kb1  Bf6  11.h4  O-O-O  , when  12.Nd4  Nxd4  13.Bxd4  Be5  is possible because a7 is tactically covered due to the ...Qa4 resource.   At first sight you might think this idea of  10.b3  is very similar to  10.a3  ,  but in fact there is the major difference that c3 and possible the long diagonal h8-a1 is weakened. This gives Black a defensive resourse that is not effective against other setups. }
10... a6
{ Black is anticipating the Nd4 idea, moving the a7-pawn to avoid a possible double attack on a7 and g7. AHA }
11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 O-O
{ After the knight trade on d4 castling kingside gains in strength, but I would still advise to avoid it if you have played ...h6 already. Here with a perfectly sound structure everything is fine for Black. Note that we have clear counterplay as b3 has weakended the white king position. We may play ...d5/...c5/...a5 next. }
