9. O-O-O Nc5
{ After  9...Nc5  , White's mainline is  10.Be3  , but the moves  10.Nd4  and  10.h4  are frequently played, too. }
10. Nd4
{ White is now ready to capture a knight on e6 and prepares the move f3. In the long run, a pawn storm on the kingside is an idea for White. }
10... Re8
{ A bit more precise than  10...Ne6  , when White has  11.Nxe6  Bxe6  12.Bd3  .   We want to play the knight to e6, but our move  10...Re8  is more useful than any move that may respond with, so we'll get a slightly improved version of 10... Ne6. This is demonstrated in the mainline after 10... Re8, which is  11.f3  Ne6  ,  when ...Re8 is certainly more useful than f3. }
11. f3
{ White has no good alternative to this move. The square e4 needs some cover because of...Ne4 ideas. }
11... Ne6 { Trading the active knight is very logical and now well-timed. } 12.
Be3
{ This looks more logical than  12.Nxe6  , but still poses no particular problems. }
12... Nxd4
{ A simple and good move. It is possible to play the more sophisticated,  12...Bg5  13.f4  Bf6  , which should lead to equal chances, too. }
13. cxd4 Be6
{ This natural move is a novelty, suggested by Stockfish. The pawn on a2 is attacked but can only be taken in rare cases. }
14. Kb1
{ White does not want to worry about the pawn forever and covers it. As mentioned, in some cases, it is possible to take on a2. If White plays the crude  14.g4?  ,  ...Bxa2!  works. After  15.b3  a5  16.Kb2  a4  17.Kxa2  axb3+  Black's attack smashes through.   After a much better move, like  14.Bd3  ,  you can't take on a2!   After  14.Bd3  Bxa2??  15.b3  a5  16.Kb2  a4  17.Ra1!  is the key difference.  Instead, Black should play  14...Qd7  or  14...c6  ,  similar to the line 14. Kb1 c6, which is the recommended continuation.   The line  14.d5  Bd7  is not to be feared, as Black is happy about ...Bf6 next. }
14... c6
{ We prepare the pawn storm ...b5, ...a5 and have equal chances in this position. }
