{ After  9...Nc5  , White's mainline is  10.Be3  , but the moves  10.Nd4  and  10.h4  are frequently played, too. }
10. h4
{ The 'Harry!' move h4 is a frequent guest in the Modern Mainline. White gains some space on the kingside and takes more control of the g5-square. }
10... Re8
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1bppp/3p4/2n5/5B2/2P2N2/PPPQ1PPP/2KR1B1R w - - 7 10@@EndFEN@@ Similar to  10.Nd4  Re8  , we play this universally good move before committing to anything more concrete. }
11. Bc4
{ White's major move by a mile, but Black is not bothered much in any case. The 7. Bf4 complex has been explored quite deeply by Petroff experts like Kramnik and Gelfand on the Black side many years ago. The theoretical assessment that Black is fine has never been overturned by modern engines, which is why White mostly plays 7. Be3 nowadays. }
11... Be6 { It's very logical to trade the strong bishop. } 12. Bxe6 Nxe6 13.
Be3 Qd7
{ We connect our rooks and have a good position without any weaknesses. Our queen may be activated on the a4-d7 diagonal soon, as the next moves show. }
14. Qd3
{ White is aiming for Ng5 to threaten mate on h7, hoping to create a weakness on our kingside. In the high-level encounter R. Ponomariov - B. Gelfand, Moscow 2008, the alternative  14.Qd5  was tested. After  14...Qc6  15.Qf5  Qc4  Black had good counterplay on the light squares and equal chances. }
14... Qc6
{ This move looks like the most reliable option. After  14...Qa4  15.Ng5  Nf8  16.Qd5  Black probably needs to take on g6, which we rather want to avoid. }
15. Ng5
{ White may also try  15.Qf5  , when  15...a5  is an excellent reply to start queenside play. Note that this way, we also activate the a8-rook, in some cases even via the square a5. }
15... Nf8
{ Black's position is perfectly fine and offers equal chances. We have no weaknesses around our king and might push the a-and b-pawns soon. The e7-bishop can be placed on f6, but there might be cases when you just take on g5, followed by play on the light squares with ...Re4 in mind.. }
