10. Be3
{ White move the bishop again, before ...Ne6 would come with a tempo. In some cases, Bxc5 is an option for White, too. Our reply prevents this idea. }
10... Ne4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/8/2P2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@ This move is rather rare but strong. It is suggested by GM Dhopade in his 'Playing the Petroff' book and is a good solution, as it leads to very similar positions to  7.Be3  O-O  8.Qd2  Nd7  9.O-O-O  Nf6  , which looks attractive for Black and is covered in the current chapter. }
11. Qd4
{ Centralizing the queen has some logic, but it is not a stable post. We are ready to play ...c5 in many cases, as we will see. }
11... Nf6 { We are ready to play ...c5 next, gaining time on the white queen. }
12. Qf4
{ This looks like a good idea, preventing ...c5 for the moment. We don't mind lines like  12.h4  c5  13.Qf4  d5   or  12.h3  c5  13.Qh4  d5  ,  which are nice versions of this chapter's mainline 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nd7 9. O-O-O Nf6. }
12... Nh5
{ Black has good alternatives, like  12...c6  . Attacking the queen is the most principled decision, though - White does not have an attractive square to go to. }
13. Qe4 { The line  13.Qd4  c5  can't scare Black, either. } 13... Re8
{ After  13...Nf6  we'd likely see a repetition of moves with  14.Qf4  ,   but Black can avoid this easily with my suggested move or the equally viable  13...c6  . }
14. Bd3 Nf6 { Instead  14...g6  is also possible. } 15. Qh4
{ Against  15.Qf4  it is possible to play  15...c5  , with typical counterplay in this line. }
15... h6
{ An important resource. After  15...c5?  White has the strong reply  16.g4!  ,  which is tough to meet. The move ...h6 stops the threats on h7, which allows the f6-knight to move. An additional idea for Black is ...Bd7, with ...b5 and ...a5 to follow. We have equal chances in this unexplored position. }
