6... Be7
{ In this chapter, we will cover Black's approach to castle kingside in the Modern Main Line. Before the World Championship Match 2018, Caruana had frequently played the lines covered in Chapter 9, involving ...O-O-O. In the actual Match in London, however, his choice was to castle kingside. This approach is now the main battleground of the Modern Mainline and therefore covered in this chapter. White's choice now is between  7.Bf4  and the more popular move  7.Be3  . Black needs to be aware that the difference between these moves is quite substantial. Black is in fine shape, but you don't have a universal plan for both lines. We'll also have a quick look at White's rare alternatives on move 7, but these pose no particular problems. }
7. Be3
{ White mainline by a mile. The bishop move prepares queenside castling, just like  7.Bf4  does. The square e3 seems to be the slightly better spot, as the maneuver ...Nd7-c5 is unattractive for Black. Against 7. Bf4, this idea works well. }
7... O-O
{ Almost a 'premove' in this chapter. Now White's clear mainline is the natural  8.Qd2  , but playing  8.Bd3  ,  followed by Qe2, is possible, too. }
8. Bd3 { The main point of this move is to place the queen on e2 next. } 8...
Nd7 9. Qe2
{ The point of 8. Bd3, but sometimes White still plays  9.Qd2  here. I decided to cover this harmless line via 8. Qd2 Nd7 9. Bd3 - please see this move order for details. }
9... Nf6
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/3p4/8/8/2P2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@ The usual post for the knight in the 7. Be3 line - we play in the same way against  7.Be3  O-O  8.Qd2  with 9... Nf6.   This is not the only possible option, though. Dhopade makes a good case for  9...Nc5  ,  eyeing the d3-bishop, when White usually takes the knight on c5. The resulting open e- and d-file often lead to further exchanges and drawish positions. I think that  9...Nf6  is more combative and in line with our approach against 8. Qd2, making it easier to remember. }
10. O-O-O Re8
{ It's essential to avoid  10...c5?  , as after  11.Rhe1  the idea of the queen placement on e2 is demonstrated. Black has no fully satisfactory reply to the threat of Bxc5!. Instead, we should delay the advance of the c-pawn and first place the rook on the open file. We cover the e7-bishop and prepare ...Bf8. White also has to reckon with ...Ng4, which also explains the next move. }
11. h3
{ A useful move for White. After an alternative move like  11.Rhe1  Bf8  White needs to address the ...Ng4 move anyway and play h3 after all. }
11... Bd7
{ Or  11...Bf8  ,  which is just as good. Black's setup involves ...Bd7, ...Bf8 and ultimately ...c5 to start the pawn advance in the center and queenside. }
12. g4 Bf8 13. Rhe1 c5
{ This is the setup we are aiming for. Our bishop has a good spot on c6, and ...Ne4 is possible, too. Black may also advance pawns on the queenside to attack the white king. White's play is less clear to me, as Black's position has no clear weakness. }
