12... Rb8 { The correct move order.  12...Be6?!  13.Ng5  should be avoided. }
13. Bg5
{ White's most dangerous and demanding try. The following lines are deep and quite tactical. }
13... Be6
{ It is crucial to avoid  13...c4?  14.Nd4!  Bd7  15.Nf5  Bxf5  16.Bxf5  , when White is much better. }
14. Qf4
{ White goes for the Qf4-h4 plan. The following lines are extremely tactical and worth learning, as it would be tricky to figure them out over the board. }
14... Qa5 { The most logical choice, going for a counter-attack. } 15. Rxe6
{ White's only good alternative to Nisipeanu's  15.b3  , as  15.a3?  b4  makes little sense. }
15... fxe6 16. Qh4
{ After forcefully removing the key piece on e6, White grabs the initiative. With precise play, we are fine, though. }
16... g6 17. Qh3
{ This is the point of White's play. We can't keep the e-pawn and have to allow Qxe6, }
17... Rf7 18. Qxe6 Qd8
{ You need to remember this idea. The queen returns to the center and helps to defend. The move ...Qd7 is a crucial idea to fight the dangerous intruder on e6. }
19. c4
{ A good move, stopping a possible c5-c4 advance. After  19.a4  a6  20.Re1  c4!  this recource is important. }
19... b4 20. Re1
{ White stops ...Qd7, which we enable again with our precise reply. } 20... Rb7
{ Now ...Qd7 is back on the map, which secures equal chances. The move 15. Rxe6 is untested as of September 2021, but it's good to know this antidote. }
