{ GM Liviu-Dieter Nisipeanu played this move in his game against GM Daniel Fridman in Magdeburg 2019. He won a great game, but Black's defense can be improved, as we will see. }
15... c4
{ Black has playable alternatives here. In the game Nisipeanu-Fridman  15...h6  was the choice of my former teammate. This is move should lead to a draw after  16.Bxh6  ,  but Daniel later slipped and allowed an attractive finish for his opponent. I suggest 15... c4, as it looks much easier to handle and gives Black chances to play for a win, too. }
16. Bf5 cxb3 17. axb3
{ This is more challenging than  17.cxb3  , when  17...b4  18.Bxe6  fxe6  looks fine for Black. We immediately threaten ...Nd5 in this position. }
17... d5 { The move  17...b4  also works and leads to equal chances. } 18. Rxe6
{ This is a way for White to force a draw. After  18.Bxe6?!  fxe6  we already have ...Ne4 as a threat, making White's position a bit awkward. }
18... fxe6 19. Re1
{ Not very obvious, but White has enough play now to keep the balance. Various moves are possible now that all end in draws. }
19... Rb6 { instead  19...exf5  or  19...Ne4  work, too. } 20. Rxe6 Qxc3 21.
Qh4 Rxe6 22. Bxe6+ Kh8 23. Bf5 Nh5
{ This secures a clean draw, for example, after the following line. } 24. Bxh7
Ba3 25. Bc1 Bxc1 26. Kxc1 Qa1+ 27. Kd2 Kxh7 28. Qxh5+ Kg8 29. Qxd5+ Kh8 30.
Qh5+ Kg8 { And it's a draw. } *

