[White "10. Petroff Modern Main Line with ...O-O"]
[Black "Petroff Modern Main Line: 5 Nc3 with ...O-O #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the modern main line of the Petroff. When the Petroff got more popular at the start of the Millenium, White had difficulty proving anything in the traditional mainline of  5.d4  @@StartBracket@@this is still the case, actually!@@EndBracket@@. So White turned attention to other tries, and  5.Nc3  quickly emerged as a challenging weapon to combat the Petroff. Nowadays, 5. Nc3 is the mainline of the Petroff, so we need to take it very seriously. We'll discuss the ideas connected to it after the next move. }
5... Nxc3
{ Most natural and best. However, I'd like to mention that I have played  5...Nf6  in classical time control chess and quicker formats. The main reason is not the quality of the move, but rather my lack of knowledge of the main lines. When I prepared the Petroff as a surprise weapon at the end of 2017, I wanted a simple line that my opponents probably don't know all that well, so I went for 5... Nf6. I still think this is a decent choice, but it should not be the primary recommendation. This repertoire, obviously, is heavily influenced by Fabiano Caruana's preferences - and he always played  5...Nxc3  , so this has to be the choice. }
6. dxc3
{ This is the idea connected to the modern mainline. By capturing this way, White emphasizes the development and prepares a quick queenside castling. The following moves by White will often be Be3/Qd2/O-O-O. It is essential to understand that White's queenside pawn formation is excellent in terms of king safety. White will therefore play queenside castling, almost no matter what Black is doing. Black needs to decide where to place the king. You may castle queenside as well, which is the safe and sound choice, but it is more exciting to castle kingside, When this course was released in 2018, Fabiano Caruana mainly had played with O-O-O as Black, but he had also tried the sharper option twice: he played the early O-O vs. Ray Robson at the US Championships and against Levon Aronian at the Olympiad. So at the time of writing, it was not 100% clear what Fabiano's preference was. I decided to cover O-O-O, but just a couple of weeks later, during the World Championship Match in London, Caruana played the ...O-O version and later analysis and games indicated that Black's chances are entirely satisfactory. While ...O-O-O lines remain playable, the current theoretical status of ...O-O is better, and therefore I decided to focus on this approach for the 2021 update of the course. }
6... Be7
{ In this chapter, we will cover Black's approach to castle kingside in the Modern Main Line. Before the World Championship Match 2018, Caruana had frequently played the lines covered in Chapter 9, involving ...O-O-O. In the actual Match in London, however, his choice was to castle kingside. This approach is now the main battleground of the Modern Mainline and therefore covered in this chapter. White's choice now is between  7.Bf4  and the more popular move  7.Be3  . Black needs to be aware that the difference between these moves is quite substantial. Black is in fine shape, but you don't have a universal plan for both lines. We'll also have a quick look at White's rare alternatives on move 7, but these pose no particular problems. }
7. Be3
{ White mainline by a mile. The bishop move prepares queenside castling, just like  7.Bf4  does. The square e3 seems to be the slightly better spot, as the maneuver ...Nd7-c5 is unattractive for Black. Against 7. Bf4, this idea works well. }
7... O-O
{ Almost a 'premove' in this chapter. Now White's clear mainline is the natural  8.Qd2  , but playing  8.Bd3  ,  followed by Qe2, is possible, too. }
8. Qd2
{ White prepares queenside castling immediately, a very natural choice. } 8...
Nd7
{ We would like to transfer our knight to f6, where it serves multiple purposes. It helps to defend the kingside but also eyes the squares e4 and d5. Now White castles queenside in the overwhelming majority of games, but 9. Bd3 has been tried, too. }
9. O-O-O
{ If Black decides to castle kingside in the Modern Mainline, this position is very likely to appear on the board. White's deviations are not particularly challenging, as we have already examined in this chapter. }
9... Nf6
{ Black has two main setups to choose from: Playing for ...c6 and ...d5 or aiming for the more aggressive setup with ...c5 and ...d5, which needs to be prepared with 9... Nf6. The first plan seems viable, but Fabiano Caruana successfully employed the more ambitious approach in the World Championship Match in London 2018. After this important game 9... Nf6 quickly gained popularity and is now established as Black's main way to fight the Modern Main Line.   The most important and popular reply to  9...Nf6  is  10.Bd3  ,  but we'll examine some alternatives, too. Black's play is very similar against all of them: we play ...c5 and start play on the queenside quickly. Ideas including ...Be6, ...Qa5 and ...b5 as a pawn sacrifice come to mind. }
10. Bd3
{ By far the most popular move. After our natural reply  10...c5  White has a wide choice, with the moves.  11.Kb1  and  11.Rhe1  being the main lines.   White may also start with moves like  10.Kb1   or  10.Re1  ,  and after  10...c5  go for  11.Bd3  to transpose to our chosen move order 10. Bd3. }
10... c5
{ We play this move, pretty much regardless of White's 10th move. Now White has tried many moves. In most cases, we'll continue developing with ...Be6, but there are some cases where the pawn sacrifice ...b5! should be played. We should take this opportunity against 11. Kb1 and 11. c4, while against other moves, I recommend developing the bishop first. The bishop development does not work well against 11. Kb1 or 11. c4, as 12. Ng5 is annoying. We can't capture on a2, compared to other moves. This is a good way to remember the difference between the two scenarios: develop the bishop if it attacks a2, while against 11. Kb1 and 11. c4 we switch to the aggressive ...b5! pawn sacrifice. }
11. h4
{ I am unsure what White intends to accomplish with the h-pawn push. Black's counterplay is more or less identical to the one after the mainline  11.Rhe1  and h4 is just a less beneficial move for White. The same rationale applies for  11.h3  , which we'd answer in the same standard fashion. Black goes for  ...Be6  and  ...Qa5  and gets good play. }
11... Be6 12. Kb1
{ White can't give up the a2-pawn with  12.Ng5  , as  12...Bxa2  13.b3  a5  is fine for Black. We examine the same idea in the line 11. Rhe1 Be6 12. Ng5 Bxa2, when the rook move is more useful than h4, but still Black is more than fine. }
12... Qa5 13. a3
{ Of course  13.c4  is possible, too. The resulting endgame after  13...Qxd2  is even less critical than in the line 11. Rhe1 Be6 12. Kb1 Qa5 13. c4, because again, the move of the h-pawn does not help White at all. }
13... d5
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2bppp/3p1n2/2p5/8/2PBBN2/PPPQ1PPP/2KR3R w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ In the comparable position after  11.Rhe1  Be6  12.Kb1  Qa5  13.a3  we play  13...c4  ,   because  13....d5  14.c4  looks a bit better for White.  Here playing the d-pawn first looks tempting. We immediately threaten ...c4, followed by ...Ne4 and ...Bxa3! now. }
14. h5 { White ignores our attacking idea. Alright, here we go! } 14... c4 15.
Be2 Ne4 16. Qe1 Bxa3 17. bxa3 Qxa3
{ Black has a crushing attack. After  18.Bd4  many moves win, like  18...Rac8  or  18...Rfc8  ,  with the idea ...Rc6-a6 }
