11... Be6 12. Kb1
{ White covers the a2-pawn with the king. This move is the most popular and was played by Magnus Carlsen in the London match against Fabiano Caruana. }
12... Qa5
{ A natural reply. Here  12...b5?!  is wrong due to  13.Ng5  .   After the better move  12...Qa5  White has a fundamental choice between the solid  13.c4  , leading to a queen trade,   and the sharper  13.a3  .  Carlsen played 13. c4 in the World Championship match, but it seems that 13. a3 is the more critical and certainly more exciting choice. }
13. c4
{ The conservative choice. White forces the queen trade and tries to claim a slight edge due to the more active pieces and the d6-pawn. A closer look reveals that Black is okay and should equalize comfortably, as in the Carlsen-Caruana encounter. }
13... Qxd2 14. Nxd2
{ One idea of this move is to gain the option f3 + g4, the other could be to play Nd2-e4 at the right moment. }
14... Rad8
{ I recommend this movie because it was played in the high-level encounter between Fabiano Caruana and Wang Hao at the Candidates Tournament 2020. Black is also fine with other moves, like  14...Rfe8  or  14...h6  .  The general idea for Black is to play ...d6-d5 at the right moment. Moves like ...Rad8, ...b6 and ...h6 are useful to prepare this pawn push. }
15. f3
{ We follow the mentioned Caruana-Wang game. After  15.Ne4  I suggest playing  15...h6  ,  stopping Ng5. Black's plan involving ...b6, ...Rfe8 etc., and finally ... d5 remains the same. }
15... b6 { Black adds some stability to the queenside first. } 16. g4 d5
{ And Black has fully equalized. We have no weaknesses and no bad pieces to be concerned about. Wang Hao drew this game without any problems. }
