13... Qxd2 14. Bxd2
{ White intends Ng5 with this move, which we need to attend to. } 14... Rfe8
{ Caruana played  14...h6  against Carlsen, which is fine, too. I still suggest  14...Rfe8  , as  15.Ng5  is not a threat after we have covered the e7-bishop. We can simply reply  15...Bd7  .  A closer look shows that moving the e6-bishop to c6 via d7 is a very reasonable setup, so we don't mind being provoked by Ng5. }
15. h3
{ As mentioned, we don't need to be afraid of  15.Ng5  , as  15...Bd7  16.Ne4  Bc6  is completely harmless.   A slower move like  15.h3  is more challenging but still rather easy to meet. }
15... Bd7
{ We'd like to place the bishop on c6, which works particularly well against 16. g4, which is the key idea of 15. h3.   That being said, Black is also in good shape after  15...Rad8  or  15...h6  . }
16. Bc3
{ After  16.g4  Bc6  White needs to play  17.Ng5  ,  when this knight has little choice but to go to e4 later, leading to mass trades and a drawish position. }
16... Rad8
{ This is better than  16...Bc6  , when  17.Nh4  is somewhat annoying to meet. }
17. Nh4
{ It's also possible to still play slow moves and delay direct action with moves like  17...Kf8  or  17...b6  . }
17... d5 18. Nf5
{ White needs to pull the plug with this move. Black is already threatening ...d4 with some space advantage. }
18... Bxf5 19. Bxf5 dxc4
{ White now has various ways to trade down to complete equality, for example, with  20.Bxf6  or  20.Rxd8  . Black's extra pawn is not relevant due to the opposite-colored bishops. }
