{ Black has two main setups to choose from: Playing for ...c6 and ...d5 or aiming for the more aggressive setup with ...c5 and ...d5, which needs to be prepared with 9... Nf6. The first plan seems viable, but Fabiano Caruana successfully employed the more ambitious approach in the World Championship Match in London 2018. After this important game 9... Nf6 quickly gained popularity and is now established as Black's main way to fight the Modern Main Line.   The most important and popular reply to  9...Nf6  is  10.Bd3  ,  but we'll examine some alternatives, too. Black's play is very similar against all of them: we play ...c5 and start play on the queenside quickly. Ideas including ...Be6, ...Qa5 and ...b5 as a pawn sacrifice come to mind. }
10. Bd3
{ By far the most popular move. After our natural reply  10...c5  White has a wide choice, with the moves.  11.Kb1  and  11.Rhe1  being the main lines.   White may also start with moves like  10.Kb1   or  10.Re1  ,  and after  10...c5  go for  11.Bd3  to transpose to our chosen move order 10. Bd3. }
10... c5
{ We play this move, pretty much regardless of White's 10th move. Now White has tried many moves. In most cases, we'll continue developing with ...Be6, but there are some cases where the pawn sacrifice ...b5! should be played. We should take this opportunity against 11. Kb1 and 11. c4, while against other moves, I recommend developing the bishop first. The bishop development does not work well against 11. Kb1 or 11. c4, as 12. Ng5 is annoying. We can't capture on a2, compared to other moves. This is a good way to remember the difference between the two scenarios: develop the bishop if it attacks a2, while against 11. Kb1 and 11. c4 we switch to the aggressive ...b5! pawn sacrifice. }
11. Rhe1
{ White centralizes the rook on the open e-file. This natural move is the most popular and was chosen by Magnus Carlsen in the mentioned World Championship game against Fabiano Caruana. }
11... Be6 12. Kb1
{ White covers the a2-pawn with the king. This move is the most popular and was played by Magnus Carlsen in the London match against Fabiano Caruana. }
12... Qa5
{ A natural reply. Here  12...b5?!  is wrong due to  13.Ng5  .   After the better move  12...Qa5  White has a fundamental choice between the solid  13.c4  , leading to a queen trade,   and the sharper  13.a3  .  Carlsen played 13. c4 in the World Championship match, but it seems that 13. a3 is the more critical and certainly more exciting choice. }
13. a3
{ The World Champion didn't dare this move in the World Championship match against Fabiano Caruana. The stakes in such a match are high, and  13.a3  leads to sharp play that you want to have prepared to the utmost detail. Magnus probably wanted to avoid a nasty surprise and went for the safe  13.c4  instead. The current theoretical verdict of 13. a3 is: equal but fascinating play. }
13... c4
{ We start direct action immediately. This line was tested in the game F.Caruana - J.Duda, Paris 2019. }
14. Be2 Ne4 15. Qc1
{ White can't play  15.Qd4?  , as  15...d5  threatens ...Bc5 and ...Bf6. }
15... d5 16. Bd4 b5
{ I suggest  16...b5  instead of  16...Rac8  , as played in the mentioned Caruana-Duda game. }
17. Nd2
{ Stockfish suggests this surprising move. At first, it looks like a blunder due to  17...Bg5  , but let's have a look. }
17... Bg5
{ Here  17...Nf6  is also possible if you like to avoid the following line that involves a possible forced draw. }
18. h4 Nxd2+ 19. Rxd2 Bxd2 20. Qxd2
{ White has sacrificed the exchange in return for the fantastic bishop on d4. At the moment, White also threatens Bxg7, forcing a perpetual. }
20... Qc7
{ Or  20....Qd8  , getting the queen back to the defense.   It's important to avoid  20...f6  , when  21.g4  starts a very dangerous attack. }
21. g4 { White can force the draw with  21.Bxg7  , of course. } 21... Rae8
{ The plan is ...f5 now. Again, White may take on g7 to force a draw or continue an exchange down. I am cutting the line here, as we are already very deep. }
*

